<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SchoolShootings-Scene 1stLd-Writethru a0</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shootings-Scene, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0832,0650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posh Suburb Shaken by Violence; It Can Happen Here</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs: `School District... to UPDATE suspect
found dead; SUBS 11th and 12th graf, pvs: `Reporters were... with
DETAILS about discovery of suspect; picks up 13th graf: `Village
residents ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The yellow police tape surrounding the
sprawling one-story brick school provided a jarring note on the
quiet, tree-lined, sunny street with its comfortable homes.
   But the tranquility of this affluent North Shore community had
already been shattered by a shooting rampage that left an
8-year-old boy dead and five other children and an adult critically
wounded.
   The children were shot at Hubbard Woods Elementary School in a
15-minute assault by a woman Friday morning in a school restroom
and in a second-grade classroom.
   The woman barricaded herself in a neighboring home and was found
dead by police later in the day. Police said she shot herself once
in the head with a .32-caliber pistol.
   School District 36 Superintentent Don Monroe, his shirt stained
with blood, tried to reassure anxious parents who gathered outside,
and the crowd dispersed quickly.
   ``There were a lot of mothers trying to get to the school''
immediately afterward, said a resident of the neighborhood, Anne
Belmont.
   ``They're all crying on my front lawn,'' said another resident,
Phil Prange.
   ``These things happen 2,000 miles away. They don't happen next
door to you,'' said a third resident, Susan Bosler.
   After the classroom shooting, the drama shifted to the nearby
home, where a young man was shot and the suspect, identified as
30-year-old Lori Dann, barricaded herself inside.
   ``I just heard police surrounding the house, calling, `Lori,
let's get it over with.' I didn't hear any response. Then I heard a
shot, a blast I would say,'' said Hildegard Oberstoetter, a
housekeeper at the home next door.
   The afternoon dragged into evening. Reporters were kept behind a
police line. Trees obscured the houses. Dozens of police officers
waited in the street, and squad cars came and went.
   After eight hours, Winnetka Police Chief Herbert Timm announced
Ms. Dann had been found dead in the house.
   Village residents talked of little else. Teen-agers sitting on
cars in a local gas station were discussing the events, and a man
sat in his garage listening to developments on a police radio.
   The boy's death was only the third slaying in his community
since 1957, Timm said.
   ``We never have a drill for something like this. But we do have
fire and tornado drills, so the kids were on the floor in the other
classrooms'' after the shooting, Monroe said.
   Standing outside the school at the end of the day, Jim Romey
said his 7-year-old daughter, Katie, was in another classroom when
the shooting occurred.
   ``I'm relieved to hear our child is safe. It's a tragedy. It's
just terrible for the family who lost their child,'' he said.
   ``The kids are calm,'' said his wife, Blanche, adding that
school officials ``told us to take them home and let them talk
because they've been talked to a lot today.''
   ``The school system here is known for being fantastic, and they
have handled this whole thing fantastically,'' Ms. Romey said.
   Hubbard Woods ``is a fabulous school _ one of the best in the
country. ... It's a family neighborhood,'' said Ms. Belmont, who
lives nearby with two pre-school-age children.
   The shady suburb north of Chicago is nestled on Lake Michigan
and marked by large homes and comfortable incomes. Chicago Bears
president Michael McCaskey lives there, as do numerous Chicago
realty barons, bankers and industrialists.
   A survey released last year by a Roosevelt University
urbanologist ranked the community of 12,482 the nation's
22nd-wealthiest suburb with an estimated per-capita income of
$35,406.
</TEXT>
