<DOCNO> AP880520-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0044EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AnglerWars     05-20 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Angler Wars,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anglers Angered Over Fishing Licenses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KILDORRERY, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like the one that got away, the Great
Anglers' Strike of '88 is assured of an honorable place in the
folklore of Irish fishing.
   It is a tale of defiance, anger and of farce tinged with menace.
It invokes the memory of Ireland's freedom wars, reflects rural
resentment against big-city bureaucrats, and climaxes with an
11th-hour truce mediated by an archbishop.
   And all because of a fishing license.
   The trouble began on New Year's Day, when a law took effect
requiring anglers, for the first time, to buy licenses.
   At 15 pounds ($26.50) for a year's trout fishing and 10 pounds
($15.60) for other fish, the permits aren't exorbitant or unusual
for Europe. But the anglers were outraged.
   They threatened to shut down angling and deal a severe blow to
western Ireland's multimillion dollar tourism industry unless the
license law was withdrawn. The government refused, and in mid-April
the strike began.
   Signs popped up along roads and at fishing venues saying ``No
Rod License'' and ``Licensed Anglers Not Welcome Here.'' Angling
clubs declared their waters off-limits to fishers. Hotels told
guests with bookings to stay away. Fishing stores refused to sell
the licenses.
   Dark tales circulated of anglers' car tires being slashed and a
fishing boat being sawed in half. True or not, they had the desired
effect.
   By mid-May, as the lakes and rivers swarmed with trout feasting
on the newly hatched mayflies, not an angler was in sight, and all
angling competitions were canceled.
   Dick Willis, head of the Munster Trout Fly Anglers' Association,
says it's not the money, but the principle.
   ``We believe we have a God-given right to fish,'' said the
54-year-old pub owner, smacking the dashboard of his car.
   ``I want to hand down to my children and grandchildren what my
forefathers gave to me _ the right to fish over these waters for
free.''
   In the tiny County Cork village of Kildorrery, Willis' friend
Peter Collins harked back 70 years to Ireland's war for
independence from Britain.
   ``My father and Dick's father put their lives on the line
fighting for our freedom, and freedom includes the right to fish,''
he said.
   ``It's a battle for control,'' Willis said. ``We anglers have
developed these waters, cleaned up pollution, restocked them,
without one penny in government aid, and we want to keep it that
way.''
   Commented lawmaker Enda Kenny: ``In the land of Capt. (Charles)
Boycott, attitudes have become deeply entrenched,'' a reference to
the 19th-century land agent who lost his crops to a peasants'
boycott and gave his name to the English language.
   The debt-ridden economy urgently needs cash, and the government
sees nothing wrong with the angling licenses. But its attitude is
under attack.
   ``It is government by diktat rather than by any sort of
consensus,'' charged the Cork Examiner. ``This whole matter has
been handled in a very nonsensical manner.''
   Indeed, the law passed so quickly and with so little fanfare
that the government tourism agency didn't have time to alter its
latest promotional literature, which still says Irish waters are
license-free.
   Meanwhile, the $60 million annual tourism industry in western
Ireland says hotels catering to anglers have been hit hard by
cancellations.
   ``We are facing ruin at the moment,'' said June Hodgson, who
runs a classy anglers' hotel on Lake Corrib in County Galway.
   ``It's devastating, heartbreaking to look out over an empty lake
and see no boats,'' she said Tuesday.
   Unbeknownst to her, however, higher powers were working to get
the anglers and the government off the hook.
   Late Wednesday, the Archbishop of Tuam, Dr. Joseph Cassidy,
announced he had secretly negotiated a deal whereby the licensing
law would not be implemented until further discussion.
   Tommy Tuck of the Anti-Rod-Licensing Campaign saw this as a
face-saving compromise and said the boats would return to Corrib
later. But Willis remained suspicious.
   ``I don't see any government commitment to repeal the law, so
for the time being our strike is still on,'' he said.
   ``This is a tax on our sport,'' he said. ``If they get away with
this, next year it'll be the tennis racket, then the golf club,
then the hurling stick. You know governments. Once they get one leg
in, it's all over. Next year they'll double it, then treble it.''
</TEXT>
