<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CopIndicted     05-20 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cop Indicted,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Grand Jury Indicts Former Cop in 1983 Motorcycle Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white former police officer, acquitted of
state charges in the 1983 shooting death of a black man, was
indicted Thursday by a federal grand jury for civil rights
violations in the same shooting.
   U.S. Attorney John Volz said the indictment charges Stephen
Michael Rosiere with shooting Gerard Glover, 18, in the back on
Aug. 31, 1983. The federal charges accuse Rosiere of violating
Glover's civil rights.
   The maximum penalty in the federal case would be life in prison.
Rosiere's attorney, Arthur Lemann III, said he would try to get the
indictment dismissed on the grounds that it subjects Rosiere to
double jeopardy.
   Volz would not say whether any new evidence was uncovered in the
federal investigation.
   Asked why it took so long to bring the federal charges, Volz
would say only that prosecutors had been watching post-trial
developments and felt the time finally had come to move on the case.
   He said federal officials were interested in the case because
``the boy was shot in the back riding on the back of a motorcycle
fleeing from what was at worst a traffic arrest.''
   Also, Rosiere and his partner admitted that they planted a gun
near the scene to make it appear that the shooting was in
self-defense, he said.
   Glover, the son of a policewoman, was a passenger behind the
driver of a speeding motocycle that Rosiere and his partner were
chasing.
   Rosiere testified during the trial that he thought he was being
fired upon and that his own gun went off when the police car
accelerated. His partner, who testified in exchange for immunity,
said no one fired from the cycle.
   Rosiere, a nine-year officer, was suspended from the police
force after the shooting and was fired three months later. He was
charged in state court and convicted of second-degree murder in
1984.
   The verdict was overturned by the Louisiana Supreme Court in
1985 and Rosiere was aquitted in a second trial in 1986. He works
as a carpenter in New Orleans.
</TEXT>
