<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PokerSeries 1stLd-Writethru a0836 05-20 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poker Series, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0836,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defending Champion Beats New Yorker For $700,000 World Series Of
Poker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 2, `Chan, who ..., and graf 7, `Seidel, 28, .. .,
to CORRECT that final losing hand was pair of queens.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defending champ Johnny Chan capped his
comeback fight with a queen-high straight on the final hand
Thursday to beat rookie Eric Seidel of New York for the $700,000
first prize in the World Series of Poker.
   Chan, who at one point was down more than $1.1 million in chips
to Seidel, used the straight to beat Seidel's two queens and win
the final $592,000 pot. ``It's not over until it's over,'' said
Chan. ``I wasn't about to give up.''
   It was the second straight World Series win for the 30-year-old
Las Vegas restaurateur, who beat a field of 167 players over four
days in the Texas Hold `Em tournament.
   Chan, who entered the final day's table of six remaining players
with $529,000 in chips and the lead, had only $270,000 in chips to
$1.4 million for Seidel when head-to-head play among the two
finalists began.
   Chan risked all his chips on the first hand against Seidel, who
folded, then steadily mounted a comeback that saw him go ahead with
$1.2 million in chips to $470,000 for Seidel.
   Seidel, however, came back to win the game's biggest pot _ more
than $1.2 million _ with a pair of 9s to Chan's pair of 8s, and the
game turned into a marathon with both players betting
conservatively.
   Seidel, 28, playing in his first Series, was down to $296,000
when he threw all his chips in on the pair of queens. ``I'm not
unhappy with what I did, but it would have been nice to win,'' he
said. He wins $280,000 for second place.
   Finishing third and winning $140,000 was Ron Graham of Tacoma,
Wash. Humberto Bremnes of Costa Rico earned $77,000 for fourth,
while T.J. Cloutier of Dallas won $63,000 for fifth place.
</TEXT>
