<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--GEBlast     05-20 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--GE Blast,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1 Killed, 2 Injured In Explosion At General Electric Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROTTERDAM, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion blew a 12-ton metal door off
a pressure vessel at General Electric Co's steam turbine plant
Thursday, killing one worker and injuring two others.
   The explosion took place at about 3:40 a.m. in Building 273, the
largest building and main manufacturing plant for steam turbines
and generators at the Schenectady plant, said GE spokesman Larry
Stone.
   Killed in the explosion was 60-year-old Thomas Dwojakowski of
Schenectady, a GE worker since 1956, Stone said.
   Stone said a metal door weighing 12 tons was blown off the
pressure vessel, called an autoclave, used in curing insulation
applied to a component in the manufacturing of generators.
   The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration is
investigating the accident, Stone said, as well as GE's own
investigation team.
</TEXT>
