<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Belgium     05-20 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Belgium,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Wins Confidence Vote on Ending Linguistic Strife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Wilfried Martens' new
government won a Senate vote of confidence in a step toward
advancing its program to end the country's age-old linguistic
strife.
   The vote Thursday endorsed the program of the 10-day-old
center-left government that the House of Representatives approved
on Sunday.
   The votes came seven months after Martens' previous center-right
alliance government fell apart in a linguistic dispute.
   Martens now plans to put into effect sweeping constitutional
reforms to quell perennial bickering between Belgium's 5.5 million
Dutch speakers and 4.5 million French speakers. His new alliance
plans to boost the powers of autonomy of northern Flanders and
southern Wallonia, Belgium's two linguistic regions.
   The prime minister has said he will send the constitutional
changes by August to Parliament, where he will need a two-thirds
majority.
</TEXT>
