<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0834 05-20 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0834,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Wins Reagan Praise, Meets Civil Rights Leaders</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3rd graf with Post report; edits 14th graf pvs to
delete full first reference to Noriega</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush basked on Thursday in
the praise of President Reagan who called him ``an important part
of everything we have achieved in this so-called revolution.''
   The vice president also received a dispensation of sorts from
the White House to disagree with the president's policies.
Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters Thursday,
``He has his ideas on how he's going to want to do things, and
that's fine.''
   Meanwhile, The Washington Post, quoting sources, reported in
Friday's editions that Bush urged at a high-level meeting of
administration policymakers that negotiations with Panamanian
leader Manuel Antonio Noriega be ended. Bush campaign spokesman
Peter Teeley said Thursday night he had no knowledge of any such
recommendation by the vice president.
   Bush met held a private evening meeting with civil rights
leaders at his official residence. The vice president's chief of
staff told reporters that Bush asked the black leaders to ``share
open discussion with him.''
   Bush called it a ``very good session.''
   Benjamin Hooks, head of the NAACP and one of the participants,
said a wide range of issues was discussed. But Hooks said: ``At
this point I'd say the vice president has a long way to go if he
actually expects to get a substantial black vote.''
   John E. Jacob, president of the National Urban League, who also
attended the meeting, said the fact that the meeting had taken
place was in itself important.
   ``This is the first meeting of this type in some eight years,
and that is significant,'' he said.
   Jacob told a recent news conference that the group was trying to
set up a similar session with Democrat Michael Dukakis.
   Jacob, a supporter of Democrat Jesse Jackson, said, ``Any
candidate who wins will have to come to get the black votes.
Neither (Bush nor Dukakis) has demonstrated that he has the
capacity to get black voters.''
   Reagan, who officially endorsed his vice president two weeks
ago, made his comments in an interview with foreign broadcasters.
   ``I have to say that the vice president has been an important
part of everything that we have achieved in this so-called
revolution in these seven years or so,'' he said.
   ``I have always believed that vice presidents in our system of
government were relegated to a kind of just standing and waiting
position, and I think that's a waste of talent. I have always
believed that your vice president should be like a vice president
in a private corporation. He should be an executive with duties and
functions.''
   Reagan cited Bush's work at the helm of task forces, one on
reducing regulations and another on drugs.
   Reagan's spokesman took pains to make clear that Bush was his
own man and was free to differ from administration policy.
Fitzwater spoke a day after comments by Bush and his aides
suggested a break with Reagan on the question of dismissing
drug-trafficking indictments against Noriega.
   ``I won't bargain with terrorists and I won't bargain with drug
dealers either, whether they are on U.S. or foreign soil,'' Bush
said Wednesday.
   ``I'm saying that he has his ideas on how he's going to want to
do things, and that's fine,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``As we go through this campaign, I would expect to see the vice
president speaking out on a number of issues in terms of what he
would do,'' he said. ``I expect a number of them will be different
than existing policies and we will not criticize them in any way.
If you want to drive a wedge between the White House and the vice
president, forget it.''
   In the interview with foreign broadcasters, Reagan was asked
about Bush's apparent effort to distance himself from White House
policy on Noriega.
   ``I can see why the vice president said what he said,'' Reagan
said in the interview. ``Because the impression has been given,
based not on information from us, but based on rumors and news
leaks and so forth, that we are in negotiations over, with a
participant in the drug trade and all. And I think he was making
himself plain that you don't negotiate with people of that kind.''
   The president said his talks with Noriega were not about his
involvement in the drug trade.
   ``Our goal, what we're trying to achieve, is the restoration of
democracy in Panama,'' he said.
</TEXT>
