<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DominicanRepublic     05-20 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dominican Republic,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Central Bank Governor Resigns; Economic Outlook Grim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor of the
Central Bank has resigned in the face of mounting economic
pressures in this Caribbean nation, where inflation has soared to
50 percent.
   Robert Saladin gave no explanation for his action Thursday. The
economist appeared briefly at the National Palace, the seat of
government, to deliver a letter of resignation to the government of
President Joaquin Balaguer.
   Saladin, 50, has disagreed with some of Balaguer's solutions for
stimulating the economy in this nation of 6.5 million people.
   ``Unfortunately, I am not a politician and I cannot be in these
political fights,'' Saladin said in a brief interview at the
National Palace.
   By late afternoon, the government had made no comment nor named
a replacement.
   Saladin is the second Central Bank governor to resign since
Balaguer was elected in May 1986. Luis Julian Perez quit in
November after suggesting that repayments on the Dominican
Republic's $4 billion debt be limited to 10 percent of export
earnings.
   Last year, debt repayments amounted $750 million, or more than
the value of total exports.
   Saladin has chafed at Balaguer's policy to stimulate the economy
by pumping $600 million into public works. About 210,000 jobs have
been created and economic growth is projected at 8 percent this
year, but there have been unwelcome side-effects.
   Inflation has soared to 50 percent, private economists estimate.
The foreign exchange value of the peso has dropped by about 20
percent to 19 cents since late last year.
   Residents of the capital Santo Domingo clashed in February with
police during demonstrations to protest increases in the cost of
living and the scarcity of basic goods like milk and cement. Public
employees demanded and received an increase in the minimum wage.
</TEXT>
