<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hastings-Impeach     05-20 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hastings-Impeach,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impeachment Panel Seeks Testimony From Convicted Hastings Friend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House impeachment panel is seeking crucial
testimony from a closemouthed Washington lawyer who was convicted
in 1982 of arranging a bribe for federal judge Alcee L. Hastings
from two Miami racketeers.
   William A. Borders, a prominent criminal lawyer, was among the
witnesses summoned to testify before the House Judiciary
subcommittee on criminal justice when it resumes impeachment
proceedings against Hastings next week.
   But there was no assurance that Borders will break his silence
on the case. Borders previously has refused to testify against
Hastings, his close friend, and never testified at his or Hastings'
trials.
   The subcommittee, which will meet again on Tuesday, is eager to
ask Borders the critical question of whether Hastings was ever
aware that his friend was arranging a $150,000 bribe for him.
   Hastings was acquitted in 1983 of conspiring with Borders to
solicit the bribe from the two convicted racketeers, Frank and Tom
Romano, in exchange for a promise of lenient sentences.
   The subcommittee is investigating charges by a special
five-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta that Hastings actually took part in the bribery scheme and
tried to conceal his involvement by lying under oath and
fabricating evidence at his trial.
   When FBI agents arrested Borders in his car outside a suburban
Arlington, Va., hotel in October 1981 _ hours before an evening
boating party to have been held by fellow lawyers in Borders' honor
_ they found a garment bag stuffed with $125,000 in cash on the
front seat.
   The money had just been delivered to Borders as the final bribe
payment by an undercover FBI agent who sat in the car posing as
Frank Romano.
   Another Hastings friend, Hemphill Pride, testified Thursday that
when he told the judge of Borders' arrest later that day, ``he was
shocked, he looked like his mouth went dry, he couldn't believe it
happened.''
   Hastings then hurriedly left Washington to return to Florida.
The judicial investigative panel concluded that Hastings fled
``because he knew he was criminally involved with Borders in the
Romano bribery scheme.''
   His fellow judges, in a 381-page report on the affair, said
Hastings boarded a flight from an airport near Baltimore instead of
Washington ``because he wanted to avoid being interviewed by the
FBI.''
   The results of the 3{-year judicial investigation were outlined
by New York lawyer John Doar, a former assistant U.S. attorney
general and special counsel to the House Judiciary Committee during
the Watergate impeachment proceedings against President Nixon in
1974.
   Doar said the appellate panel had uncovered evidence not
available to the trial jury that Hastings had given false testimony
about a series of telephone calls and had drafted phony letters
intended to obscure his alleged involvement in the bribery
conspiracy.
   Under questioning by House investigators, Doar said he had found
no evidence of any racial motivation behind Hastings' prosecution
or the subsequent inquiry by the judicial panel.
   If the subcommittee recommends impeachment, and the full
Judiciary Committee concurs, the House must vote whether to impeach
Hastings. Then the Senate would conduct a trial. A two-thirds
majority vote of the Senate is required for conviction and removal
from office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
