<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ManassasBattlefield     05-20 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Manassas Battlefield,4450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Says 175 Parks Threatened by Development</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new coalition of preservationists says
national parks across the country face threats from commercial
development similar to a plan by a Virginia company to build a
shopping mall next to the Manassas National Battlefield.
   ``At 175 parks, the threat is so significant that the reason the
park was established may be lost,'' Paul Pritchard, one of the
founders of the National Heritage Coalition, said Thursday.
   Pritchard said other endangered parks include Richmond and
Fredericksburg-Spotsylvania in Virginia; Gettysburg, Pa.; the
Everglades National Park in Florida; and Olympic National Park in
Washington.
   At a press conference, Pritchard and other opponents of the
Manassas shopping mall announced their intention to stop it and any
other project that endangers a historic site.
   President Carter's former press secretary, Jody Powell, is
helping the group free of charge with public relations and
organized the gathering.
   The coalition _ sponsored by the National Trust for Historic
Preservation and the National Parks and Conservation Association _
is calling for Congress to enact legislation giving the federal
government power to halt development temporarily so that
negotiation, compromise or federal acquisition of disputed property
can take place.
   As part of its project to protect the Manassas battlefield, the
coalition is working for passage of a bill recently introduced by
Reps. Michael Andrews, D-Texas, and Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., that
directs the Interior Secretary to acquire the land now owned by
developers.
   Meanwhile, bulldozing is under way to prepare for townhouses and
detached homes that will accompany the shopping mall. Bob Kelly,
spokesman for the developer, Hazel-Peterson Co., said nothing can
stop construction short of an act of Congress.
   The acreage in question includes the site where Confederate Gen.
Robert E. Lee directed troops for the second battle of Manassas and
includes land used for hospital space and as a burial ground for
some of the war dead.
   Though the land has been part of a master plan for expanding the
4,500-acre park since 1935, it never was acquired by the federal
government and Hazel-Peterson bought it about three years ago for
$10 million.
   The Interior Department is promoting a compromise in which the
developer would move the mall so it is not visible from the park.
   The plan is acceptable to Hazel-Peterson, but not the
preservationists who say even the mall still will generate so much
traffic that visitors won't be able to get to the park without
massive traffic jams.
   Fifteen organizations, including the American Association of
Museums, the American Association of State and Local History, the
Council on America's Military Past, the National Center for
Preservation Law, the Society of Civil War Historians and the
Wilderness Society, are included in the National Heritage Coalition.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Nicaragua     05-20 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Nicaragua,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Funds Monitoring Commission, Blasts Sandinistas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has approved $10
million to monitor compliance with the Nicaraguan peace process,
drawing congressional criticism for taking so long to decide how to
use the money.
   The money was part of a $48 million package approved by Congress
in late March, a week after Nicaragua's leftist government and the
Contra rebels signed a temporary truce at Sapoa, Nicaragua.
   That agreement called for the creation of a verification
commission to monitor compliance with the accord.
   Of the funds, $8 million will go for activities of Joao Baena
Soares, secretary general of the Organization of American States,
and $2 million for Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, leader of the
Nicaraguan Roman Catholic Church.
   The allocations are based on a budget submitted by the
commission to which the two men belong.
   Shortly after the grant was announced, House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, criticized the administration for taking six weeks to
determine how to spend the funds. Other Democrats have made the
same criticism.
   Money for the verification commission had been held up because
the State Department and the OAS were unable to agree on a proposal
that met U.S. goverment accounting requirements.
   This drew an angry reaction from Rep. Tony Coelho, D-Calif., who
said that U.S. officials were demanding an elaborate accounting
system from the OAS on the one hand while, on the other, they were
giving money to the Contras and letting it ``simply disappear into
the jungle.''
   In announcing the grant, the administration launched a harsh
attack on the Sandinista government.
   The administrator of the Agency for International Development,
Alan Woods, charged that Nicaragua had engaged in a campaign of
``harassment and intimidation'' and ``menacing militarism'' in
apparent violation of agreements signed by Sandinista authorities.
   Alan Woods said in letters to Baena Soares and Obando y Bravo:
``Anyone who shares our interest in peace, democracy and
reconciliation in Nicaragua must be greatly alarmed by the recent
crackdown on human rights and civil liberties by the Sandinista
government.''
   ``This barrage of harassment and intimidation makes it clear
that the verification commission must fully monitor the very
fundamental issues of democracy, civil liberties and human rights.''
   Woods told the commission members that a series of incidents in
recent weeks has undermined ``the process of reconciliation to
which the Nicaraguan government committed itself.''
   He said the process is being further scuttled by the Nicaraguan
government's ``menacing militarism.'' He cited a statement by
Nicaraguan Defense Minister Humberto Ortega in which he threatened
the Contras with ``actions on a scale never before seen in this
war.''
   Woods also said Nicaraguan authorities have placed severe
limitations on press freedom and that more than 30 persons
supporting construction workers conducting a hunger strike were
arrested.
   The Sandinistas and the Contras are attempting to negotiate a
permanent settlement but have made little progress. The deadline
for reaching an agreement is June 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
