<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Baker-Financial     05-20 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baker-Financial,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Rules Out Sweeping Changes In World Monetary System</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Release at 2:30 a.m. EDT, TIME set by source.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-World Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The global economy is changing too rapidly for
governments to successfully impose major changes in the way they
manage exchange rates, U.S. Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III
said today.
   Baker said he favors gradual, step-by-step efforts to improve
coordination of monetary policy among the major industrialized
countries.
   He cited as an example a possible broadening of coordination on
national tax reform and deregulation of financial and labor
markets. The United States also could work more closely with its
major trading partners in monitoring the performance of their
economies, he said.
   But in remarks prepared for delivery to the Council on Foreign
Relations, Baker ruled out any ``sweeping, revolutionary changes in
the system.''
   His appearance before the council was closed to the news media.
Copies of his speech were made available in advance.
   Baker met on Wednesday and Thursday in Paris with trade and
finance ministers from the 24 members of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development.
   ``An attempt to make an abrupt or major change in the structure
of the system by imposing a detailed set of formal constraints
might well be viewed by the markets as overly ambitious and
unsustainable,'' Baker said.
   ``The global economy is too dynamic, and the forces of change
too strong, to be able to look ahead with great certainty and
envision a highly defined international monetary structure that
will fit the world economy of 1995 as well as that of 2005,'' he
added.
   Baker told reporters after the OECD meeting Thursday that the
seven largest industrial countries were pleased with the relative
stability of exchange rates since last December, when they jointly
bought massive amounts of dollars in the open market in order to
halt its steep decline.
   ``We see no reason to believe that that won't continue,'' Baker
said.
   In his speech to the foreign relations group, Baker said the
major economic powers' efforts since 1985 to improve monetary
coordination had been a remarkable, although incomplete, success.
   ``I strongly suspect the world economy is better off today than
we would have been had we not followed this course,'' he said.
   Some government officials and private experts have said the
world monetary system should undergo more radical reforms than
suggested by Baker.
   A study published earlier this month by the Institute for
International Economics in Washington said existing international
agreements on ways of keeping exchange rates stable were
``agonizingly fragile.''
   The issue of reforms to the world monetary system is expected to
be discussed at a June 19-21 summit meeting in Tornoto of leaders
from the United States, Canada, Britain, France, West Germany,
Italy and Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
