<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NCI-BreastCancer     05-20 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NCI-Breast Cancer,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Studies Show Benefits Of Additional Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women with early stage breast cancer would
benefit from treatment in addition to initial surgery or radiation
therapy, the National Cancer Institute says, citing three studies
that have yet to be published.
   Such additional treatment _ chemotherapy or hormonal therapy or
both _ has been the institution's formal recommendation for the
past two years in cases involving more advanced breast cancer.
   The NCI announcement Thursday shows the institute views the new
findings significant enough to publicize before they are formally
published in a medical journal or presented at a scientific meeting.
   Women with early stage breast cancer _ before it has spread to
lymph nodes under the arm _ have been regarded as having a
relatively favorable prognosis after primary treatment, but it is
now recognized that up to 30 percent have recurrences of their
cancer, the NCI said.
   ``The richness of the clinical evidence from a variety of trials
now shows that this outlook can be improved upon,'' NCI Director
Dr. Vincent T. DeVita Jr. said.
   The data that prompted the NCI's statement were presented to the
National Cancer Advisory Board on May 9 and a special clinical
alert was mailed Monday to 13,000 cancer specialists and cancer
organizations.
   ``Each year more than 60,000 women in this country are diagnosed
with node-negative breast cancer ... and we cannot delay informing
them and their physicians that additional treatment beyond surgery
and-or radiotherapy may be beneficial,'' DeVita said.
   Dr. Michael Friedman, an NCI researcher, said future U.S.
studies will focus on which forms of additional treatment are best,
rather than whether there is a benefit from any such treatment.
   It is estimated that 135,000 American women will get breast
cancer this year and that 42,000 will die from it. One in 10 women
will develop breast cancer in her lifetime.
   ``The emerging information from the three American studies is
consistent with a more mature body of information from European
investigators,'' the NCI announcement said.
   One U.S. study of 679 patients found 80 percent of those given
additional treatment were cancer-free after four years compared
with 71 percent who were not given additional treatment.
   The other study involved 2,644 patients in which 82 percent of
those given additional treatment were cancer-free after four years
compared with 77 percent of those receiving a placebo.
   The third involved about 350 patients and found 84 percent of
those given additional treatment cancer-free after three years
compared with 67 percent of those given a placebo.
</TEXT>
