<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ForeignAid     05-20 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foreign Aid,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs $14.3 Billion Foreign Aid Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has been given a $14.3 billion
foreign aid bill that represents a 2 percent increase over last
year's level and largely continues current programs.
   On a voice vote Thursday, the House Appropriations Committee
approved without amendment the bill passed earlier this month by
its foreign operations subcommittee. The bill covers the fiscal
year beginning Oct. 1.
   There was little debate on the measure because Congress has
little flexibility in dealing with appropriations as a result of
budget-cutting agreements reached late last year.
   Israel again would receive more than any other country under the
bill _ some $1.8 billion in military aid and $1.2 billion in
economic assistance.
   Egypt, which is favored for making peace with Israel, receives
the second-largest amount _ $1.3 billion in military assistance and
$815 million in economic aid.
   Pakistan, which has been regarded as a front-line country
because of the Soviet occupation of neighboring Afghanistan, would
receive $220 million in economic aid and $240 million in forgiven
loans for purchase of military goods.
   The Philippines would receive $124 million in economic aid and
$125 million in military aid.
   Some $90 million in economic support and $655 million in
economic development money would be used for African countries.
   In Central America, Honduras would get $85 million in economic
aid, Costa Rica $90 million, El Salvador $185 million and Guatemala
$80 million. Military aid for those and other countries was not
earmarked, but would come out of separate military aid and credit
accounts.
   The bill also would give economic aid of $40 million to
Portugal; $20 million to Morocco; $10 million to Tunisia; $15
million to Cyprus; between $10 million and $35 million for Ireland;
and $2 million for Poland's Solidarity trade union.
   Some $34 million would be set aside for Middle East development
projects, of which $11 million is for projects in Jordan and $23
million for those in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The bill would allocate $150 million to the Peace Corps, $101
million for international narcotics control, $362 million for
migration and refugee assistance, $35 million for the prevention of
AIDS worldwide and $254 million to pay past-due debts of
international financial institutions.
   It would send $217 million to support a long list of United
Nations organizations, and stipulate that the money for UNICEF must
be obligated within 30 days of passage of the bill, or the
administration would suffer an automatic cut of $50 million in
money for military aid.
   It is up to the State Department to decide how to divide up the
balance of funds for nations not specifically mentioned in the
bill. About 100 countries receive U.S. aid directly.
</TEXT>
