<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     05-20 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hardly Mentions Jackson As Both Campaign In California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, making only passing
references to the upcoming Democratic presidential primary in
California, was placing his emphasis squarely on the fall campaign
against Republican George Bush.
   The Democratic front-runner, who expects to lock up his party's
presidential nomination with another windfall of delegates in the
closing primaries on June 7, scheduled appearances today in Los
Angeles, Sacramento and San Francisco.
   He flew into the state Thursday and told a rally in Los Angeles
that in the fall election voters would have a choice ``between two
fundamentally different sets of values. Between two different sets
of beliefs about how we build a strong economy; about how we build
the best America.''
   Despite heckling by protesters claiming he was not doing or
saying enough about AIDS, Dukakis drew repeated cheers from the
crowd as he delivered a speech that belied his reputation as a dull
speaker.
   Hecklers in the auditorium of the Musicians' Hall on the west
side of Los Angeles held up signs saying, ``Bush + Dukakis More
AIDS Deaths.''
   ``We need a president who's not afraid to talk about AIDS,''
hecklers shouted.
   When Dukakis came to a section of his speech in which he
referred to changing research priorities from the military to
health care, he referred to acquired immune deficiency syndrome as
``a disease that must be conquered'' and said Massachusetts was
spending ``more per case for AIDS than any other state in America.''
   Homosexuals in Massachusetts accused the governor of
discriminating against them when he supported giving heterosexual
couples preference in adopting foster children.
   The only references Dukakis made to his Democratic primary rival
Jesse Jackson were tributes to the fact the Democratic race had
come down to choice between the son of Greek immigrants and a black
man born in poverty in the South.
   He hardly mentioned the June 7 primary, instead referring
several times to the importance of California in the fall election.
   ``The election this fall will be the most important and closest
since 1960,'' he said. ``And it may well be decided right here in
California.''
   He sounded his familiar themes of the need to attract more
people to teaching, of the need for a broader health care system,
for child care, and for a war on drugs.
   One of the loudest cheers came when he said, ``On January 20,
1989, we're going to have an attorney general _ no matter who she
or he is _ that will put the word ``justice'' back in the
Department of Justice.''
</TEXT>
