<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Economy     05-20 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Economy,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Presidential Candidate Outlines Economic Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate Carlos Salinas
de Gortari said Mexico will not pay its foreign debt if the burden
of its loan obligations keeps the country's economy from growing.
   Salinas de Gortari also pledged to open Mexico to foreign
investment, loosen state restrictions on the economy and guide the
nation into the battle for international markets.
   The nominee of the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party
and the man virtually certain to succeed President Miguel de la
Madrid chose this conservative industrial city to outline his
economic policy.
   The PRI, as the governing party is known by its Spanish
initials, has not lost a presidential or gubernatorial election
since it was founded in 1929.
   In a speech Thursday night, Salinas de Gortari told businessmen
in this northeastern city near his family home that Mexico's
limping economy will grow again.
   He promised a policy of cooperation with foreign creditors
instead of ``irresponsible formulas of confrontation.''
   Mexico's foreign debt is about $100 billion, the second highest
in the developing world after Brazil. Mexico has been meeting
payments on its foreign loans and has built up a record amount of
foreign reserves.
   It has negotiated with its creditors for easier terms on the
foreign debt and is seeking more ways to ease the payment burden.
   But economic growth will have priority over payments on the
foreign debt, Salinas de Gortari said. ``If we fail to grow because
of the burden of the debt, we will not pay,'' he added.
   The candidate was cheered as he spoke of curtailing government
controls, reducing budget deficits and letting private business
invest in such areas as telecommunications, petrochemicals and
other fields that have been reserved for state investments.
   Previous administations have favored a more centralized economy
and tight economic controls.
   ``We will consolidate the opening of our markets and we will
promote foreign investment,'' Salinas de Gortari told the gathering.
   ``The opening of our economy to the foreign competition is an
irreversible fact,'' he said. ``Foreign investments must play a
more positive role contributing to the creation of jobs, to
technological modernization and the opening of foreign markets.''
   He stressed the need to eliminate subsidies and exercise
``financial discipline'' to make economic growth possible.
   Salinas de Gortari said the time was past in Mexico when the
state was ``the only instrument for the solution of each and every
problem of the economy and society.
   ``In this new strategy to develop exports, you will have to take
chances,'' he told the businessmen.
   Mexico's economy has been seriously affected in the past six
years by rocketing inflation that reached a record 159.2 percent in
1987.
   The government this year has managed to reduce the inflation
rate by persuading labor unions and private businesses to sign a
``solidarity pact'' that has put a lid on prices and wages in
recent months.
   ``We have no option,'' Salinas de Gortari said. ``Either we
succeed in making the economy work or the adverse social impacts
will magnify.''
   Presidential elections are scheduled for July 6, with the winner
sworn in on Dec. 1 for a six-year term in office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
