<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham     05-20 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospective Jurors Screened As Mecham Criminal Trial Begins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Evan Mecham planned to spend
the weekend weeding out obviously biased candidates for the jury in
the former governor's criminal trial on charges he concealed a
campaign loan.
   The trial began Thursday, when 100 prospective jurors were sworn
in and filled out long questionnaires aimed in part at eliminating
people who may have been influenced by the publicity surrounding
the case.
   ``There goes my weekend,'' said Mecham's defense lawyer, Michael
Scott, noting that attorneys on both sides hope to analyze the
forms before meeting again Monday.
   Mecham, 64, and his brother, Willard, are charged with
concealing the $350,000 campaign loan by failing to report it on
the former governor's campaign or personal finance statements.
   Mecham, a Republican, is charged with six felony counts of
perjury, willful concealment and filing false documents. Willard
Mecham, his brother's 1986 campaign treasurer, faces three similar
counts.
   Mecham was removed from office last month when the state Senate
convicted him on impeachment charges. He could face up to 22 years
in prison if convicted of all six counts in the trial, while his
brother could be sentenced to up to 9{ years if convicted on the
three counts he faces.
   Neither attended Thursday's initial session in Maricopa County
Superior Court. Scott said Mecham probably will attend court next
week, after the questioning of potential jurors begins.
   The questionnaire was worked out by the prosecution, defense and
trial Judge Michael Ryan.
   Among the 99 questions were whether the panelists know anyone
involved in the case, whether they signed or circulated petitions
for or against Mecham while he was governor and whether they belong
to the John Birch Society.
   Also, they were asked whether they knew anyone on a long list of
people associated with Mecham or his criminal case.
   The former governor has refused to predict whether he will fare
better in court than at his impeachment trial. The Senate removed
Mecham on April 4, 15 months into his first term, by convicting him
of trying to thwart a death threat investigation and of misusing
$80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning the money to
his auto dealership.
   Mecham was also impeached on charges of concealing the $350,000
loan, but the Senate decided not to consider that charge for fear
of prejudicing Mecham's criminal trial.
   Prosecutors said the Mechams failed to report the loan from
Tempe developer Barry Wolfson until after a newspaper reported it
in October 1987.
   On Wednesday, a state Supreme Court justice refused a defense
request to delay the trial until the high court considers a defense
motion to return the charges to the grand jury. The Arizona Supreme
Court is to hear arguments on that issue June 1.
   The defense filed two new motions, released Thursday. One asks
the judge to dismiss the charges based on a claim that the campaign
and personal finance reporting laws are unconstitutionally ``vague,
ambiguous, imprecise and overbroad.''
   The other asks that the charges be remanded to the grand jury
for a new finding of whether probable cause exists. That motion
argued that grand jury materials were improperly turned over to the
prosecutors in Mecham's impeachment trial.
   Ryan did not schedule arguments on the motions.
</TEXT>
