<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Sikhs     05-20 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>14 More Deaths Blamed On Sikhs; Temple Cleaning Nearly Complete</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh radicals were blamed for the
killings of 14 more people in Punjab state. At the Golden Temple,
crews worked today to clear Sikhism's holiest shrine of debris from
a 10-day siege by security forces.
   Five of the victims killed Thursday night in Punjab state were
Hindu migrant workers from the eastern state of Bihar.
   Police said the workers were lined up against a wall and shot by
eight Sikh gunmen, the United News of India reported. The killings
occurred in Chinna Karam Singh village, 18 miles northwest of
Amritsar.
   It was the second attack on migrant workers this week,
suggesting that the extremists are trying to undercut agriculture,
the mainstay of this northern state's economy.
   On Tuesday night, Sikh gunmen killed more than 30 Hindu workers
as they slept at a camp near the state capital of Chandigarh.
   Other deaths reported Thursday night which police blamed on
Sikhs included five people killed in a village in Jalandhar
District and four shot to death as they waited for a bus in
Bhatinda District.
   The deaths raised to more than 1,100 the number of people killed
by Sikh extremists in Punjab this year. In all of 1987, about 1,030
people were slain.
   Sikh militants have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for
more political autonomy or an independent homeland in Punjab, where
they are a majority. Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of India's
800 million people and claim they are discriminated against by the
nation's majority Hindus.
   State-run All India Radio today quoted an unidentified
government official in Amritsar as saying cleaning was nearly
complete at the Golden Temple and ``steps are being taken to
restore traditional rituals.''
   The government siege of the temple ended Wednesday with the
surrender of the last Sikh extremists.
   Police cordoned off the complex May 9 after radicals inside
fired on police officers conducting an inspection outside its
walls, wounding five of them.
   Rituals at the golden-domed temple include a continuous reading
of the Sikh holy book, the Guru Granth Sahib, and the singing of
hymns. Sikhism was founded 500 years ago as an alternative to
Hinduism and Islam.
   Visitors to the inner sanctum of the temple often take a
ceremonial dip in the surrounding pool, which is considered sacred.
   On Thursday, bomb disposal squads searched the temple to make
sure the surrendering extremists did not leave explosives behind.
There were no reports of any explosives being found.
</TEXT>
