<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Noriega-Morale     05-20 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega-Morale,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Dropping Noriega Charges Could Crush Morale in War
On Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morale among prosecutors and drug agents battling
narcotics trafficking could be undermined if drug charges are
dropped against Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
say those involved in the case.
   ``Why are we prosecuting all these people?'' asked U.S. Attorney
Leon Kellner. ``Why are we investigating all these people who do
drugs, when people who sit outside this country and allow their own
countries to be used for drug trafficking can make deals without
even our input?''
   Jack Hook, spokesman for the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration in Miami said the handling of the Noriega case
``sends one signal to the law enforcement community and sends a
totally opposite signal to the drug traffickers in South America.''
   ``Are we just wasting our time?'' he asked.
   Kellner, whose office brought the indictment against Noriega,
was in Washington last week to try to block any deal for dropping
the charges. He criticized his exclusion from the Reagan
administration's negotiations with Noriega.
   ``I have not had a single phone call from anybody,'' he said
Wednesday. ``I'm upset. Apparently, I guess, I'm going to find out
what's going to happen to our cases at the same time as everybody
else does.''
   Not long before the reports of the negotiations with Noriega
surfaced, Kellner announced late last month he would be leaving the
U.S. attorney's post to rejoin his old law firm. He said he was
leaving for personal reasons.
   Chief Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Gregorie said the
possibility of a political defeat in the Noriega case has crushed
his spirit and that of other prosecutors and agents in Miami who
worked on the case.
   ``We've spent a lot of time and effort making this case,'' he
said. ``The assistants who worked on the case in this office and
myself ... would certainly be most disappointed if the case is not
allowed to go forward.''
   Other prosecutors, however, had mixed reactions to the Noriega
negotiations.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles Senatore, a prosecutor in the
public corruption section, said he differentiates between ``any
political decisions that go on in Washington'' and ``my job of
fighting crime here in this district.''
   Noriega was indicted in February in Miami and Tampa on drug and
racketeering charges. The Reagan administration is conducting
negotiations to drop the charges in exchange for Noriega's
agreement to step aside as leader of the troubled nation.
</TEXT>
