<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   05-20 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0447,0805</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Say Israel Can't Handle Flood of Arab Prisoners</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th, `Army officials...' to UPDATE with
comments from army official; PICKS up 9th pvs: `A military...';
INSERTS 1 graf after 22nd, `Israel officials...' with soldiers
investigated; PICKS up 23rd pvs: `In another...' Minor editing to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for detained Palestinians claimed the
Israeli military justice system has buckled under a flood of Arab
inmates, but army sources said prisons will be centralized and
computerized for efficiency.
   Many of the thousands of Palestinians imprisoned during the
5-month-old uprising in the occupied lands are held incommunicado
for weeks or miss court appearances because authorities can't
locate them, their lawyers said Thursday.
   ``It's a big mess,'' Israeli lawyer Lea Tsemel told The
Associated Press. ``The army is completely inefficient.''
   Also Thursday, left-wing Israeli legislator Dedi Zucker issued
new figures on detentions. He said 1,900 Arabs _ one in every 200
men over 18 _ are being held in jail for six months without trial.
   Another 8,100 Palestinians are in prison awaiting trial or
serving sentences for specific charges, Zucker said.
   Similar figures were released by Law in the Service of Man, a
human rights monitoring group founded by West Bank lawyers. The
organization said between 7,000 and 9,000 Palestinians are in
jails, in addition to about 2,000 administrative detainees held
without trial.
   Since the uprising started Dec. 8, 17,000 Palestinians _ 4
percent of the male population over 14 _ have been detained, said
Jonathan Kuttab, a lawyer and member of the human rights group.
   Army officials refused comment, saying they had to check their
detention figures.
   Israel radio today quoted the army legal adviser in the West
Bank, Lt. Col. Dudu Yahav, a saying 1,800 Palestinians were being
held without trial in administrative detention.
   Most are leaders of the outlawed youth group Shabibe, which is
linked to the Palestine Liberation Organization's mainstream Fatah
faction, Yahav was quoted as saying.
   He said most detainees were being held without trial because
there was insufficient evidence to bring them to court.
   A military prosecutor said last week that 5,000 Palestinians
were being held, including 1,700 in administrative detention.
   According to U.N. figures, 191 Palestinians have been killed
since anti-occupation protests began in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip. Two Israelis also have died. Israel seized the lands
from Egypt and Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war.
   The army has built five detention centers in Israel and the
occupied lands to accommodate those detained during the unrest and
has housed some detainees in 17 other prisons.
   A military source said Thursday that the army is adopting
several measures to make the West Bank prison system more efficient.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the army
plans to appoint a high-ranking officer to oversee all prisons in
the West Bank, install a computer in each facility to keep track of
prisoners, and close smaller detention centers.
   And a senior officer in the West Bank's central command,
identified only as Lt. Col. Shuki, was quoted as saying that
detainees with the same legal status will be housed in the same
prison.
   All administrative detainees will be moved to a prison camp in
Israel's southern Negev Desert, the domestic Itim news agency
quoted Shuki as saying.
   Lawyers for Palestinian prisoners were skeptical about the plans.
   ``We have filed many complaints, and now they say they are going
to organize everything,'' said Ms. Tsemel. ``We've been hearing
this for two months.''
   Ms. Tsemel said she and several colleagues sent a letter to the
army on Wednesday saying the lawyers strike if the situation does
not improve.
   Lawyer Felicia Langer, who has represented more than 100
Palestinians, said she often searched for clients two or three
weeks before prison authorities located them.
   ``Even those who are charged are sometimes not brought to court
on the date of their trial,'' Ms. Langer added.
   ``The only thing that will improve the situation is to release
people and not to treat them as animals, dehumanize them,'' she
added.
   Israeli officials have denied allegations of mistreatment and
inefficiency.
   Shuki was quoted by Israel radio today as saying that three
soldiers were investigated recently on charges they mistreated
prisoners, and three detainees were released after a probe showed
they were being held without justification.
   In another development Thursday, the West Bank's military
government permitted reunification of 40 Palestinian families as a
goodwill gesture.
   The government applies stringent standards in issuing residency
permits, often granting only temporary tourist visas to
foreign-born spouses of West Bank residents. As a result, hundreds
of Palestinian families are separated.
</TEXT>
