<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     05-20 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hispanics Can Shape Results of Presidential Race, Study Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study says the Hispanic vote could be
the deciding factor affecting the results in a close presidential
race in several states.
   The report said Hispanic voters can influence the selection of
71 percent of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
   California, which has 47 electoral votes, and New York, with 36,
were cited as two among nine key states where the strength of the
Hispanic vote could alter statewide results.
   ``The Hispanic vote has the potential of being a true swing vote
in 1988,'' said Harry Pachon, national director of the National
Association of Latino Elected and Appointed Officials, which
sponsored the study that was released Thursday.
   The other states mentioned by the group include Texas with 29
electoral votes, Illinois with 24, Florida 21, New Jersey 16,
Colorado 8, Arizona 7 and New Mexico 5.
   NALEAO is a national, nonpartisan civic affairs group with more
than 3,300 members nationwide.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kean Says Bush Must Not Be Reagan Clone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican governor who is sometimes mentioned
as a possible vice presidential candidate says George Bush must
cast off his ``identical twin'' image and mark out his differences
with Ronald Reagan if he intends to succeed Reagan in the job.
   ``Ronald Reagan is a very popular man but nobody wants a
clone,''said New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean in an interview Thursday.
   Kean said Bush has to show voters how his presidency would
differ from Reagan's.
   ``Vice presidents are often co-opted by the president when they
try to run. George Bush can't allow that to happen,'' Kean said.
   Kean said Bush must spell out where he differs with Reagan with
the president's blessings.
   ``I have said I did not want the position ... but it would be
totally arrogant to say that were the position offered ... you
would turn it down,'' said Kean, in not ruling out accepting the
No. 2 spot on the GOP ticket.
