<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rejected Georgia GOP Delegates Can Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In response to a court order, the Georgia
Republican Party has agreed that 968 would-be delegates to the
party's state convention in Albany can appeal their
disqualifications.
   GOP spokesman Lee Raudonis announced Thursday evening that the
delegates could appear today before the party's interim credentials
committee in Albany. They also have a right to appeal to the full
convention, he said.
   The two-day convention was scheduled to start today at the
Albany Civic Center.
   Superior Court Judge William Towson ruled Thursday afternoon
that the 968 disqualified delegates can go to the convention and
appeal their status.
   In his temporary restraining order, the Laurens County judge
enjoined the party from deciding the fate of the contested
delegates without first notifying them of their right to appeal.
   He also enjoined the party from denying them admission to the
convention or restricting their rights.
   Raudonis said the 11-member credentials committee would begin
meeting today and the challenges probably would be heard on a
county-by-county basis.
   After all appeals are heard, the committee will issue a report
to the full convention, which will then hear any appeals and vote
on the list of approved delegates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Prominent Michigan Democrat to Skip Atlanta Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One prominent name will be missing from
the roster of Michigan delegates to the 1988 Democratic National
Convention.
   Richard Austin, secretary of state for the past 17 years and
consistently the highest vote-getter among candidates for statewide
office, has decided to stay in Michigan instead of joining fellow
Democrats in Atlanta.
   He will become Michigan's acting governor while Gov. James
Blanchard is in Atlanta.
   ``I'm going to be minding the store,'' Austin said Thursday.
``The governor has informed me that he has some things that he
feels might develop.''
   If Austin hadn't agreed to stay behind there would have been a
dramatic, though brief, philosophical change in the control of
state government.
   All four of the top elected officials in the state are
Democrats. Blanchard, Lt. Gov. Martha Griffiths, Austin, who is
third in line of succession and Attorney General Frank Kelley.
   Kelley, Blanchard and Lt. Gov. Martha Griffiths are going to be
convention delegates.
   If Austin joined the other top elected Democrats in crossing the
state line at the same time, Michigan would get a Republican as
substitute governor: Senate Pro Tempore Nick Smith of Addison who
has been fifth in line of succession for 17 months and has yet to
get a shot at the top.
</TEXT>
