<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Sweden-AIDS     05-20 0155</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Sweden-AIDS,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worldwide AIDS Conference Expected To Draw 6,000 Scientists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 6,000 researchers and
scientists from 121 countires are expected in Stockholm next month
for a fourth annual international conference on AIDS, organizers
say.
   Conference Chairman Lars Olof Kallings, director of the World
Health Organization's Center on AIDS, said 6,300 scientists have
sought accreditation for the conference to be held June 12-16.
   Scientists from 45 U.S. states are among those seeking to attend
the conference. The first annual international AIDS gathering drew
about 3,000 participants in Atlanta in 1985.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a fatal disease in which
a virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to a wide variety of infections and cancers. There is
no known cure.
   AIDS is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or
syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products,
and from pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
