<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LawDeans     05-20 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Law Deans,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deans Of Two Law Schools In DC Resign The Same Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The law school deans at American University
and Georgetown University announced their resignations the same
day, adding to the list of law school deans around the country who
have quit in recent years.
   Frederick R. Anderson, 46, dean at AU's law school, said
Thursday he will become a professor at the law school June 1. He
will hold the law school's first endowed professorship, for which
he raised $1.5 million two years ago. Anderson was dean for three
years.
   Robert Pitofsky, 58, said he plans to resume teaching at
Georgetown after a one-year sabbatical. He was dean for six years.
   Both cited a desire to devote more time to teaching and
scholarship.
   George Washington University Law School, also in the District of
Columbia, named a new dean last month, and new deans have assumed
positions at the law schools of Catholic and Howard universities in
the past two years. The George Mason University law school in
suburban Arlington, Va., also named a new dean in the last two
years.
   According to the American Bar Association, 86 of the nation's
174 ABA-approved law schools have hired new deans in the last three
years, and the average stay of deans has slipped from six years to
3.2 years.
   Top law school faculty, Pitofsky said, are paid almost as much
as deans. In addition, faculty members have the time and
opportunity for outside earnings, said Pitofsky and others.
</TEXT>
