<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuban Defector,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuban Cyclist Defects to United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has agreed to accept
as a political refugee a member of Cuba's cycling team, according
to a local newspaper report.
   El Norte said Thursday that Roger Vazquez Vazquez, 25, was in
the newspaper's offices when U.S. authorities telephoned him on
Wednesday with word of his acceptance.
   Vazquez was then taken to the border town of Laredo, Texas,
according to the news account.
   The U.S. Consulate in Monterrey said the U.S. government cannot
grant asylum to people until they are physically present in the
United States.
   Consulate spokesman Bob Brown said, however: ``We can help them
get to the United States as a refugee if they qualify.''
   Vazquez abandoned his team after a cycling race in Mexico City
last week and was given refuge by Mexican cyclists in this
northeastern industrial town. They cyclists took Vazquez to the
U.S. Consulate where his case was being considered.
   However, Vazquez became impatient and tried to leave Mexico on
his own. He was apprehended Sunday as he tried to go through a
federal migration checkpoint at Nuevo Laredo, about 16 miles south
of Laredo.
   He was jailed in Monterrey, the capital of Nuevo Leon state
about 135 miles south of Laredo, but was later released.
   In a letter published Thursday in El Norte, Vazquez described
himself as one ``who abandoned his beloved country to seek the
liberty that we lost 29 years ago and that we're going to regain in
the future.''
   Vazquez told the newspaper he plans to join family members in
Miami.
</TEXT>
