<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     05-20 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Proposal Would Modify War Powers Act</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnam-era law that has been the focus of a
long-running fight between the White House and Congress may be
overhauled by a proposal introduced in the Senate.
   ``Our goal is to make the statute more workable,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., a sponsor of the measure to
reform the War Powers Act.
   ``Frankly, if I were president, I would thumb my nose at this
legislation. The War Powers Act has never really worked,'' said
Byrd Thursday about the existing legislation.
   The law, enacted in 1973, requires a report from the president
when U.S. military personnel are sent to situations of ``imminent
hostilities.'' Under some circumstances, those troops must be
withdrawn after 60 days or 90 days, unless Congress specifically
votes to authorize them to remain.
   Then-President Nixon vetoed the legislation, arguing that it was
an unconstitutional restriction on his authority, a position taken
by all three subsequent presidents.
   The new proposal would let the troops remain for an unspecified
length of time unless Congress votes to remove them. It also
creates a group of 18 senior congressional leaders who would
regularly meet with the president to discuss national security
matters.
   Congress, most recently threatened to invoke the War Powers Act
when President Reagan instituted his Persian Gulf policy of
reflagging 11 Kuwaiti-owned tankers and protecting them with Navy
warships.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Limits On Children's TV Advertising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee has approved legislation
that would require television stations to limit advertising during
children's programs.
   The measure, approved Thursday in 22-2 vote by the House Energy
and Commerce subcommittee on telecommunications, is a bipartisan
compromise.
   Stripped from the House subcommittee's version are earlier
proposals to prohibit so-called ``program-length commercials''
built around toy manufacturers' products which Senate legislation
would have barred.
   The bill passed by the House subcommittee would limit TV
stations to no more than 10 1@2 minutes of commercials per hour
during children's shows on weekends and 12 minutes per hour during
these programs on weekdays.
   The bill, which was scheduled for consideration by the full
committee next week, also requires the Federal Communications
Commission consider whether a station has complied with the
advertising limits and served the educational needs of children in
its overall programming when the station's license is reviewed for
renewal.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Bill Approving Radioactive Waste Compact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With some reservation, President Reagan has
signed federal legislation approving the Appalachian States
Low-Level Radioactive Waste Compact.
   In a statement announcing his signature, Reagan Thursday hailed
the more than three quarters of the states that have now entered
compacts on low-level radioactive waste, but he warned the
Appalachian commission against attempting to enforce federal laws. .
   He said the compacts ``underscore this nation's commitment to
take those actions needed to ensure the future availability of
nuclear power as an energy supply option for this country.''
   Reagan objected, however, to a provision of the bill giving the
commission federal law enforcement responsibility without requiring
that commissioners be appointed according to the appointments
clause of the Constitution.
   ``Any effort by the commission to enforce federal regulations
would contravene the Constitution,'' the president said.
   Under the compact _ which includes Pennsylvania, West Virginia,
Delaware and Maryland _ the four states are required to ensure that
there is a regional facility sufficient to dispose of the region's
low-level waste, and that each state has equal access to it.
</TEXT>
