<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LotteryWinner     05-20 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lottery Winner,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Man Wins Lotto Drawing For Second Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA C. HUSLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck driver has made state lottery history
by winning two jackpots, with his latest prize totaling more than
$6 million, lottery officials announced.
   Robert E. Humphries of Philadelphia, who said he spends $45 a
week on the game, bought the computer-picked Wild Card Lotto ticket
May 6.
   The total annuity value of the jackpot is $6,364,818.18, the
12th largest individual prize won in lottery history, lottery
officials said Thursday.
   Humphries won his first lottery jackpot on March 7, 1986, and
shared the prize with four other winners. His share totaled
$421,433.25. He is the first person to win two jackpots since the
game began in 1972, said lottery Executive Director James Scroggins.
   Combined, Humphries' prizes have an annuity value of
$6,786,251.43. His net annual earnings from both wins are more than
a $250,000.
   ``I'm ecstatic,'' Humphries said after receiving his first of 21
payments of $242,469.27. ``I always had it in the back of my mind
that I was going to (win) again.''
   Humphries said he has been playing the Lotto and Super 7
lotteries since the early 1970s.
   He said he buys 15 tickets three nights a week, then carefully
records the winning numbers.
   ``I believe in giving yourself a winning edge,'' he said.
``You've got to try to cut down the odds.''
   His initial reaction to the news was caution, then elation, and
finally speculation about what he should do with the winnings,
Humphries said.
   Cars, homes and other such luxuries first came to mind, he said,
but he and his wife Marie decided instead to spend the money
helping out relatives.
   Humphries said he would take some time off from his job as a
truck driver for Marstan Industries.
   ``I won't be climbing on the truck real soon,'' he said.
</TEXT>
