<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Korea-Parole,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ministry Announces Special Parole For Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's Justice Ministry
announced today that 1,013 prisoners will be released Saturday
under special a parole to mark Buddha's birthday.
   No political detainees will be released under the amnesty and
ministry officials refused to comment.
   Opposition groups and dissidents are demanding the release of
all political prisoners. The government was reportedly considering
the release of some political prisoners to seek national
reconciliation.
   The political opposition and dissidents claim there are about
1,000 political detainees. Government officials say there are only
about 340, not counting people convicted of treason and sedition.
   The government freed 125 dissidents from prisons across the
country Feb. 27 in an amnesty marking the inauguration of President
Roh Tae-woo.
   About 15 million of South Korea's 42 million population are
Buddhists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
