<DOCNO> AP880520-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0528EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JacksonThreat     05-20 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson Threat,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Self-Described Racist Indicted On Charge Of Threatening Jesse
Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A self-described racist indicted on a charge of
threatening to kill black presidential candidate Jesse Jackson says
he's innocent and authorities can't ``railroad'' him for his
beliefs.
   ``My views shouldn't persecute me, actions should,'' Londell
Williams said Thursday after a federal grand jury returned the
indictment. ``I haven't done anything. I haven't taken any actions
towards Mr. Jackson. My views haven't pointed a gun at anyone.
   ``They can't railroad me just because of what I believe,'' he
told the Belleville (Ill.) News-Democrat in an interview from the
federal detention facility at the St. Clair County Jail in
Belleville.
   Williams, 30, of Washington, Mo., was named in all four counts
of the indictment. His wife, Tammy, 27, was named in three of the
counts, but she was not accused of being involved in the threat on
Jackson's life.
   Federal agents initially said Williams claimed he belonged to
two violent white-supremacist groups: the Covenant, the Sword and
the Arm of the Lord, otherwise known as CSA, and The Order.
   But Tom Den Ouden, who heads the Springfield, Mo., FBI office,
said he had found no evidence Williams or his wife belonged to the
groups. And leaders of the groups said they never heard of Williams.
   ``It's possible that there are people who say they're in The
Order,'' said Order leader Bruce Carroll Pierce, 34, in a telephone
interview from the U.S. Penitentiary in Leavenworth, Kan. ``But
they're not writing me letters telling me what they're planning.''
   Pierce is one of two men convicted in the slaying of Denver
radio personality Alan Berg in 1984.
   Ollie Ellison, one of two wives of imprisoned CSA leader James
Ellison, said Thursday she never heard of Williams. Ms. Ellison,
who is in hiding, answered questions for the Rocky Mountain News of
Denver through a third party.
   Both of the Williamses have denied any links to organized white
supremacist groups, and the Secret Service said Londell Williams
passed a lie detector test on the subject.
   The indictment differs from the initial arrest charges, which
accused the couple of being part of a conspiracy to kill Jackson.
   ``It does not appear to be a large overall plot as was first
reported,'' said Secret Service agent Rich Adams.
   The indictment said that on or about May 10, Williams
``knowingly and willfully did threaten to kill and inflict bodily
harm upon Jesse Jackson.''
   It charges both of the Williamses with possessing an AR-15
assault rifle that had been altered to make it fire like a machine
gun. The gun was to be used in a plot to kill Jackson, the
government said.
   The pair also were charged with two counts of threatening to
harm a government informant in retaliation.
   Prosecutors and the couple's attorneys met for several hours
after the indictments were issued but declined comment afterward.
Cynthia Short, Mrs. Williams' lawyer, would say only that ``They
(the Williamses) are scared.''
   Williams, a construction worker, faces a maximum penalty of
three years in prison and $250,000 in fines on the first count. On
each of the other three counts, the Williamses could be sentenced
to 10 years in prison and fined $250,000.
   U.S. District Judge Edward L. Filippine set arraignment for
Monday.
   The Williamses, who live in rural eastern Missouri with their
three daughters, have been held without bond since federal agents
arrested them Friday at their apartment. The arrests were announced
Tuesday.
   Franklin County, Mo., Sheriff Paul J. Bruns said an informer
told investigators that Williams not only possessed the rifle, but
that he was part of a plot to kill Jackson on June 21 or July 4.
   The sheriff said the informer led officers to a wooded area,
where they found the rifle.
   A Secret Service agent testified Tuesday that agents taped a
conversation in which Williams told the informer that the Covenant
wanted the rifle back and was planning Jackson's assassination.
</TEXT>
