<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-20 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Little Change In Dollar; Stocks Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was little change in the dollar today but
share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed higher despite a
computer problem during the morning session.
   The dollar finished the day at 124.82 yen, 0.02 yen higher than
Thursday's close of 128.80 yen. After opening at 124.85 yen, the
dollar moved in a narrow range of 124.80 to 124.90 yen.
   ``Because a long weekend is nearing, traders don't seem to be
enthusiastic about setting up a new position,'' said Hiroaki
Shukuzawa of Sumitomo Bank. Markets in Europe will be closed Monday
in observance of Whitsunday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 20.61
points, or 0.08 percent from Thursday to close at 27,393.85.
   ``The strong dollar lifted share prices, but not as much as the
market expected,'' added Keiichi Nishida of Kidder Peabody's Tokyo
office.
   ``Overall trading was slow because of concern over the inflation
and the beginning of a long weekend,'' he said.
   Traders said the brief computer shutdown during the early
morning session kept the market from recovering further after two
consecutive days of decline.
   The computer system at the Tokyo Stock Exchange shut down
shortly after 9:00 a.m. (0000 GMT) during a bullish period in the
market, traders said.
   ``The computer problem may have had some effects on the market
in the sense that it could discourage investors from taking a
position,'' said a trader at a major securities firm. ``But it is
also true that there are other elements of concern such as
inflation and rising interest rates.''
   Yoshio Hirano of the TSE said they were forced to shut down the
entire computer system briefly to swith the main system to a
reserve system.
   The computer that controlled the trading of Mitsubishi Steel
Manufacturing Co. shares, one of the most popular shares in recent
trading, became inoperable, he said.
   Hirano denied speculation that excess orders for the shares
caused the computer to break down. Investigations were continuing
into the system failure, he said.
   The volume traded today was 800 million shares.
</TEXT>
