<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Soviet     05-20 0293</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Soviet,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Wants Trade Office In South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union wants to open a trade
office in South Korea after the Olympic Games in Seoul, local
business leaders said today.
   Some high-ranking Soviet officials expressed their interest when
South Korean businessmen visited Leningrad last week to take part
in an electronics show, officials of Goldstar Co. said.
   Goldstar and three other top South Korean electronics firms are
participating in the ``Leningrad Electronics Show,'' which opened
May 12 in that Soviet city for an 11-day run.
   It is the first time South Korean firms have been invited to a
trade show in the Soviet Union. Despite the absence of diplomatic
relations, the two countries have been expanding sports, cultural
and economic contacts in recent years.
   Koo Young-soo, chief of Goldstar's motor sales department,
quoted I.T. Kanaev, deputy chief of the Soviet Union's Chamber of
Commerce and Industries, as saying: ``We hope to open a trade
office in Seoul immediately after the Olympics.''
   The Games begin in September.
   Kanaev specifically asked Goldstar managing director Shin
Dong-ki to help with the Soviet plan and relay it to the South
Korean government, Koo said.
   Koo, who returned from Leningrad early this week, said Leningrad
Mayor P. Kyurshin also called for expanded trade contact with South
Korea when he visited a Goldstar showroom.
   The Goldstar and other South Korean showrooms attracted about
1,000 people daily and many Soviet officials said they wanted to
import electronic parts such as motors and color television tubes
from South Korea, Koo said.
   Trade between the Soviet Union and South Korea has so far been
conducted through third countries. Their two-way trade was
estimated at $140 million in 1986. Figures for 1987 were
unavailable.
</TEXT>
