<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WrongBodies     05-20 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wrong Bodies,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Body Mixup Leads To Unintended Cremation, Mistaken Open Casket</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who died on the same day were
mistaken for each other, leading one to be cremated in the other's
place while horrified mourners viewed the wrong man in an open
coffin.
   Both men died May 9 and were taken to the morgue at Yale-New
Haven Hospital, authorities said. Both were transported from there
to Sisk Brothers funeral homes in New Haven and in Hamden.
   Patrick Sisk, one of the funeral home's owners, blamed the
hospital.
   ``The tags were wrong,'' he said. Sisk said his attorney was
preparing to file a complaint with the state against the hospital.
   Authorities said the body of Thomas P. Eagan, 68, of North Haven
was to have been buried May 13 but instead was cremated. William J.
Gormley, 73, of East Haven was to have been cremated, but his body
appeared dressed in Eagan's suit in an open coffin May 12 during
calling hours at the funeral home in Hamden, the New Haven Register
reported in today's editions.
   Thomas Urtz, a hospital spokesman, said four bodies were
released May 9 to Sisk Brothers, which was handling arrangements
for all four, and added, ``We take great precautions to make sure
that we appropriately identify bodies before they leave the
hospital.''
   The Eagans filed a complaint Thursday against the funeral home
with the state Department of Health Services. The family also hired
an investigator to find out who made the error.
   ``There had to be an extremely large number of mistakes made in
order for this to have happened,'' said Thomas P. Eagan Jr. of
North Branford, one of Eagan's three sons. ``There had to be major
negligence. I would never want another family to have to go through
this.''
   The Eagans must cope with the knowledge that Thomas Eagan was
cremated against his and his family's wishes, said the family's
attorney, Thomas W. Boyce Jr.
   Eagan died unexpectedly overnight and the wake was important to
the family, Boyce said.
   ``The grieving process is an important part of dealing with it,
and the wake is an important part of the whole structure,'' Boyce
said.
   Gormley's daughter-in-law, Karen Gormley, said the funeral home
did not tell the family what had happened, other than to ask that a
relative on May 13 affirm the identity of the deceased William
Gormley.
   Boyce said Thursday he did not know who was responsible for the
mistake. He said the family filed the complaint to make sure a
similar mistake doesn't happen again. It was filed against the
funeral home because ``they're the ones that ultimately made the
arrangements,'' Boyce said.
   A state medical examiner had signed a certificate that allowed
Eagan's cremation, the newspaper reported.
   Eagan's cremated remains were placed in a casket May 13 by
Keenan Funeral Home, which replaced Sisk Brothers at the request of
the family. A traditional funeral was held, along with a mass of
Christian burial and burial of the remains.
   Gormley's body since has been cremated. A memorial service for
him was held at Sisk Brothers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
