<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CableCarCrash     05-20 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cable Car Crash,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Rookie Operator Caused Cable Car Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An error by an inexperienced cable car
operator who nevertheless managed to warn his passengers of danger
caused a crash this week that injured 36 people, a federal
investigator said.
   Gerald Bolden, who had been a cable car gripman less than a
month, did not properly tighten the car's grip on the underground
cable, said Mark Garcia, an investigator for the National
Transportation Safety Board.
   A lever operated by gripmen clamps metal dies against the cable,
preventing the car from moving faster than 9{ mph, the speed of the
cable.
   The operator's error Monday allowed the car to slip down Hyde
Street, two blocks above Fisherman's Wharf, and to slam into a
truck at a red light, sending some of the 40 tourists and other
passengers flying into the intersection.
   Garcia recommended gripmen be given more training and that
automobiles be banned from the tracks on the two-block stretch
where the accident occurred.
   Garcia said several factors contributed to the accident,
including rain-soaked tracks on the steep hill, the cable car's
outmoded braking system and the fact that cars and trucks also
drive on the tracks.
   He praised the gripman, however, for yelling to passengers
moments before the crash, ``Hold on!''
   Garcia also contradicted reports by witnesses that the car sped
up to 25 mph. The car was traveling no faster than 15 to 18 mph
when it hit the truck, he said.
   William Stead, manager of the city's Municipal Railway, which
operates the cable cars, had no comment on the report. Bolden also
declined to talk to a reporter.
   Meanwhile, a $2 million claim was filed Thursday against the
city on behalf of a couple injured in the crash. The claim, filed
by attorney Melvin Belli for Harry and Lillian Shuttenberg, was the
first stemming from the accident to be submitted to the city
attorney.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
