<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson, Dukakis Plan Meeting to Discuss Convention Platform</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to restore dropped letters</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAKERSFIELD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two remaining Democratic
candidates are planning a meeting to discuss strategy and a
platform for their party's national convention, according to one of
the candidates.
   Jesse Jackson told reporters Thursday that he had spoken to
Michael Dukakis by telephone about the meeting, and he said the two
hoped to get together while they are both campaigning in California
prior to the June 7 primary. Both candidates are scheduled to be in
San Francisco today.
   ``We must keep in mind our role is to expand and unify our
party,'' Jackosn said.
   Jackson gave no other details on the meeting.
   Earlier in the day Jackson took his campaign to California's
farmland, telling students to give life a chance without drugs and
agricultural workers to preserve their fields from dangerous
chemicals.
   Jackson gave several scheduled interviews Thursday morning
before embarking on a full day of appearances in Bakersfield and in
Fresno, stressing agricultural themes such as keeping farms in the
family.
   A private fund-raiser netted $50,000 for the Democratic
presidential hopeful, who faces a tough battle in the state's
primary against Dukakis, the Democratic front-runner.
   Jackson also spoke at a ``Latino Salute to Jesse Jackson'' at
the Civic Auditorium in this San Joaquin Valley city 120 miles
north of Los Angeles.
   At a noon rally before a mostly white crowd of 4,000 Kern County
high school students, Jackson blew a kiss and gave a thumbs-up sign
as multi-colored balloons were released into the sky.
   ``I can sense the joy in the air, the sense of hope, the
celebration of people coming together because we care,'' Jackson
said as students clapped and chanted ``Jesse, Jesse'' from the
bleachers at West High School. At one point, Jackson took off his
suit jacket to put on a yellow and green T-shirt bearing a Viking,
the school's mascot.
   Jackson told the students to chant ``I am somebody'' and asked
those who knew of friends who either tried drugs or attempted
suicide to stand.
   ``That's why my heart is heavy and you bring tears to my eyes,''
Jackson said as nearly the entire group stood up. ``You have to
make a big decision today. You have to give life a chance. You have
to give hope a chance.''
   About 100 students who claimed they had tried drugs joined
Jackson on the field afterward.
   ``He's just not talking politics, he made a lot of sense. He's
the first person I've heard (talk about drugs) who I understood,''
said Jennifer, 16, who declined to give her last name.
   Jackson also went to nearby McFarland, a farming town where 12
children have contracted cancer and half of those have died. While
the cause of the cancer is unknown, parents fear agricultural
chemicals played a part.
   ``So long as we poison the environment, and as we contaminate
the water and the air, we will poison the people,'' Jackson said.
   He ended the evening by bringing the audience of 2,500 to its
feet with cries of ``Jackson, action!''
   Jackson appeared relaxed, just two days after a St. Louis couple
was arrested in an alleged assassination plot against him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
