<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama     05-20 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Publishes Accusatory List, Photos of U.S. Diplomats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pro-government newspaper published
photographs of U.S. Embassy employees and their families so that
Panamanians will ``know the Gringos who are starving us to death.''
   The supplement in the newspaper Critica, a propaganda organ of
the government, said the Americans ``think the walls of their
embassy are impregnable.''
   U.S. Embassy spokesmen said it was a significant escalation of
what they called a harassment campaign by Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, who is chief of the 15,000-member Panamanian Defense
Forces and controls the civilian government.
   ``We take this seriously,'' embassy spokesman Terence Kneebone
said in a telephone interview Thursday.
   ``Saying `Panamanians, these are your enemies,' and putting it
in a very shrill way in front of a public in which there are known
paramilitary groups is not a very wholesome thing to do. Combined
with the rhetoric, it is cause for concern,'' Kneebone added.
   Noriega has been indicted on drug-trafficking charges in the
United States and the Reagan administration has imposed severe
economic sanctions on Panama in an effort to make him resign.
   A 10-foot-high fence of iron bars surrounds the U.S. Embassy
grounds on seaside Balboa Avenue. The embassy building is about 25
yards from the fence, within easy reach of projectiles from the
street.
   The embassy's physical barriers are almost identical to those of
the U.S. consulate in Tegucigalpa, Honduras, which anti-American
protesters burned and sacked in April.
   The front page of the 36-page supplement published by Critica on
Thursday shows photos of the embassy building, U.S. Ambassador
Arthur Davis and John Maisto, deputy chief of mission. It says in
bold print: ``Panamanian: Know the Gringos who are starving us to
death.''
   A preface to the list of embassy personnel said: ``These are the
ones who think the walls of their embassy are impregnable, that
their computers are infallible.
   ``These are the ones who carry out the strategy of Elliott
Abrams, who wants to kill thousands of Panamanians in order to
impose a docile government that would hand the country over to
Washington.''
   Abrams, assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs,
has been a central figure in the Reagan administration's Panama
policy.
   Critica's list of embassy employees includes the names of 85
diplomats and and 64 dependents, most of them spouses. Following
the list are pages of photocopies of identity documents issued to
embassy personnel by the Panamanian government.
   These include photographs, but most are of such poor quality as
to be unrecognizable in newsprint reproduction.
   In all, the documents of 363 embassy personnel and dependents _
including children _ are reproduced, but many are outdated.
   According to Critica, the source of the list and documents was
The Committee for Panamanian Dignity and Sovereignty. It was the
first known public mention of the committee.
   The newspaper, which includes ranking military officers on its
board, said the committee obtained the information from an
``intelligence branch'' that had the cooperation of ``patriotic
Panamanians and North American friends.''
   It said it would provide addresses and telephone numbers of the
Americans in coming days, which Kneebone said would make the matter
``that much more serious.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SriLanka     05-20 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Official Slain, Sinhalese Extremists Blamed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese extremists with automatic
weapons fatally wounded a senior official of the governing United
National Party as he left his Colombo home today, police said.
   Two men opened fire with Chinese-made AK-47 rifles as Nandalal
Fernando was being driven to his office, said police inspector G.
Kalupahana. He said the gunmen and a third suspect escaped on a
motorcyle.
   Fernando was shot in the stomach and hand and died three hours
later at a hospital, police officials said, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   They said the attack was carried out by the People's Liberation
Front, a group of ultranationalist Sinhalese who have vowed to kill
anyone who supports President Junius R. Jayewardene's efforts to
make peace with the Tamil minority.
   Fernando held the fourth-highest post in Jayewardene's party as
secretary general. The party's chairman was assassinated last
December.
   The government has blamed the People's Liberation Front for the
killings of about 260 government officials and supporters since
July 29, when Sri Lanka and India signed a peace accord to end the
Tamil insurgency.
   Fernando, like Jayewardene, belongs to the Sinhalese ethnic
group that controls the government and comprises 75 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. Tamils, who account for 18 percent, say
they are discriminated against in jobs and education.
   Tamil militants have been waging a guerrilla war against the
government and Sinhalese civilians for nearly five years. The
rebels rejected the peace accord, which provides greater autonomy
in Tamil-populated areas if the guerrillas surrender their weapons.
   Sinhalese militants also reject the accord, saying it gives too
much to the Tamils.
   To enforce the accord, India has sent more than 50,000 soldiers
to Sri Lanka, an island off its southern coast, but Tamil militants
are now fighting the Indian troops.
   On May 10, the government lifted a five-year ban on the People's
Liberation Front's political activities after announcing it had
signed a peace agreement with the Sinhalese radicals.
   The group denied reaching such an agreement and has continued
attacks on Sinhalese politicians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
