<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusCrash-GasTank     05-20 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Crash-Gas Tank,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Marshal Says Caged Fuel Tank Would Not Have Helped in Bus
Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bus Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A protective cage like those required on
newer buses would not have prevented the fuel tank of a church bus
from being punctured in a fiery crash that claimed 27 lives, the
state fire marshal says.
   Fire Marshal Bill Martin said the location of a three-inch gash
on the front of the 60-gallon tank and pictures of the metal cages
required in newer buses had convinced him that whatever pierced the
tank probably would have passed between the bars of a cage.
   ``In this situation, the way this accident occurred, that cage
would have had little or no effect,'' Martin said in an interview
Thursday.
   The converted school bus owned by the Radcliff First Assembly of
God Church burst into flames after being hit head-on by a pickup
truck traveling the wrong way on Interstate 71 near Carrollton on
Saturday night.
   Twenty-seven of the 67 people on board died of smoke inhalation
in one of the nation's deadliest bus crashes. The driver, who was
allegedly drunk, has been charged with 27 counts of murder.
   Jean Fasone, head of the National Transportation Safety Board
team investigating the crash, said Martin's findings could prove
true. The NTSB team will continue trying to determine whether a
cage would have minimized damage to the fuel tank.
   Although his report will not be complete for several weeks,
Martin said the fuel tank probably was punctured by another piece
of the bus.
   In addition to the gash, NTSB investigators reported this week
that the fuel tank had been pushed back 26 inches and off one of
the two straps that fastened it to the bus.
   A protective cage might have held the tank in place, resulting
in an even larger hole, Martin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
