<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Hit Two Sections of the Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms swept across the northern and mid-Atlantic coastal
states as well as the Great Plains and parts of the Rockies today,
unleasing fierce winds, heavy rains and hail the size of tennis
balls.
   In Midland, Texas, the huge hail accumulated a foot deep,
stripping trees of branches and flooding streets. Early this
morning, a thunderstorm dropped two-thirds of an inch of rain in
less than an hour at Abilene, Texas.
   A tornado touched down in southeastern South Dakota, destroying
a machine shed on a farm. In Canton, S.D., a thunderstorm whipped
winds to 50 mph.
   Thunderstorms also struck parts of Nebraska, Kansas, eastern
Colorado, New Mexico and eastern Arizona.
   In the East, a possible tornado was reported just west of
Fayetteville, N.C. Strong thunderstorm winds in northeastern North
Carolina moved a barn 2 feet off its foundation and uprooted a
large pine tree.
   Recent heavy rains in parts of the East caused flooding of
streams and small rivers. Flooding was a danger in south-central
Pennsylvania, where the flood gates on the dam at Fort Ritchie were
opened.
   Flood watches were in effect in much of Pennsylvania, southern
New Jersey, northern Delaware, much of Maryland, northern Virginia
and northeastern West Virginia.
   Meanwhile, skies were clear this morning over the Gulf Coast
states and much of the Mississippi Valley, while the far West also
saw clear skies.
   Today's forecast called for showers in New York, eastern
Pennsylvania and lower Michigan; showers and thunderstorms from
Ohio and western Pennsylvania across the mid-Atlantic states to
North Carolina, also from Minnesota across the Great Plains to the
central and southern Rockies; widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms in southern Florida; and sunny skies over the rest of
the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 60s from New England to
the northern and central Appalachians; in the 50s or 60s from
northern Minnesota across the Dakotas, western portions of the
central Plains, Texas and the central Rockies to Utah and northern
Arizona; 90 in parts of the Southeast; in the 90s from the Rio
Grande Valley of Texas, the desert Southwest and much of
California; and in the 70s or 80s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 83 degrees at
Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 64 fair; Boston 51 rain; Buffalo 58 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 71 fair; Cincinnati 56 foggy; Cleveland 53 foggy;
Detroit 57 foggy; Miami 75 fair; New York 56 cloudy; Philadelphia
60 drizzle; Pittsburgh 54 foggy; Portland, Maine 55 rain;
Washington 61 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 58 cloudy; Chicago 56 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
75 partly cloudy; Denver 40 rain; Des Moines 65 fair; Indianapolis
57 fair; Kansas City 68 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 62 fair;
Nashville 60 fair; New Orleans 68 fair; St. Louis 66 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 55 partly cloudy; Anchorage 46 fair; Las
Vegas 70 fair; Los Angeles 64 fair; Phoenix 82 fair; Salt Lake City
52 fair; San Diego 63 fair; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 52 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 61 cloudy; Toronto 57 drizzle.
</TEXT>
