<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher Against Most Currencies, Gold Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against most currencies in
quiet European trading early today. Gold prices fell a bit in
lackluster trading.
   Dealers said foreign exchange markets were exceptionally quiet
ahead of a three-day weekend for many European countries because of
a holiday on Monday.
   ``It is as dead as a doornail,'' said one trader in Rome.
   One dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said Tuesday's release of
the surprisingly small U.S. trade deficit for March has lifted the
dollar's range a bit but hasn't changed the lackluster character of
the foreign exchange market.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose fractionally to a closing 124.82 yen from 124.80
yen late Thursday. Later, in London, it was quoted slightly higher
at 125.09 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates:
   --1.7046 West German marks, up from 1.6990
   --1.4215 Swiss francs, up from 1.4155
   --5.7725 French francs, up from 5.7542
   --1.9036 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9042
   --1,261.80 Italian lire, down from 1,262.00
   --1.2445 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2442
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.8635 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8665 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $457 a troy ounce, up
from late Thursday's $456.90. At midmorning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a lower recommended price of $456.50 .
   In Zurich, the bid price was $457, down from $458 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 45 cents to close at a bid
$458.01.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.65 a troy
ounce, down from late Thursday's $6.72.
</TEXT>
