<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Shrine     05-20 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Shrine,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guns, Ammunition Found Inside Temple, 20 More People Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for 1st Ld-Writethru to PM-India-Sikhs, a0466. LEADS
with 12 grafs to UPDATE with tour of temple, higher death toll,
other details. Pick up 8th graf pvs: `Sikh militants...' Edits
thereafter to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants left Chinese-made AK-47
rifles, grenades and ammunition inside the Golden Temple when they
surrendered to police following a 10-day siege, a tour of the
shrine showed today.
   Municipal work crews continued to clean debris from the temple
complex, and police reported 20 more people shot to death by Sikh
extremists overnight.
   Five of the victims killed Thursday night were Hindu migrant
workers who were lined up against a wall and shot.
   Reporters taken to the temple found that one of its windows had
been shattered during the confrontation between the extremists and
police. A bullet hole could be seen in the marble near the entrance
to the shrine.
   The weapons were on the floor above the inner sanctum of the
temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine. The siege ended Wednesday when
the last 46 Sikh extremists holed up inside the temple surrendered
to police.
   The Guru Granth Sahib, the holy book of the Sikhs, lay covered
under a cloth in the inner sanctum on the ground floor. There was a
burn mark across the cloth, which appeared to have been made by a
bullet passing close to its surface.
   In rooms around the pool surrounding the temple, reporters were
shown the militants' supply of tinned butter, wheat and lentils as
well as army uniforms the extremists apparently used to impersonate
servicemen in some of their raids.
   In Room No. 48, the office assigned to the militant All India
Sikh Students Federation, reporters saw files of threatening
letters that had been sent by the group and other militant factions
to Punjab residents. Some demanded money. In other rooms there were
blood-stained clothing, toiletries and medical kits.
   Police said the migrant workers killed Thursday were lined up
against a wall and shot by a gang of eight radicals, the United
News of India reported. The killings occurred in the village of
Chinna Karam Singh, about 18 miles northwest of the Sikh holy city
of Amritsar.
   It was the second attack on migrant workers this week,
suggesting that the estremists were trying to undercut the mainstay
of Punjab state's economy, which is agriculture. Overnight Tuesday,
Sikh gunmen killed more than 30 Hindu workers from Bihar and Orissa
as they slept at a camp near the state capital of Chandigarh.
   Other deaths reported overnight included six people killed in
Jalandhar district, six in Bhatinda district and three other shot
to death in separate incidents around the state.
   The killings raised to at least 1,108 the number of people
killed by Sikh extremists in Punjab since the start of the year. In
all of 1987, about 1,030 people died.
   Sikh militants have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982 for
more political autonomy or an independent homeland in Punjab, where
they are a majority. Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of India's
800 million people and claim they are discriminated against by the
nation's majority Hindus.
   State-run All India Radio today quoted an unidentified
government official in Amritsar as saying cleaning was nearly
complete at the Golden Temple and ``steps are being taken to
restore traditional rituals.''
   Police cordoned off the complex May 9 after radicals inside
fired on police officers conducting an inspection outside its
walls, wounding five of them.
   Rituals at the golden-domed temple include a continuous reading
of the Sikh holy book and the singing of hymns. Sikhism was founded
500 years ago as an alternative to Hinduism and Islam.
   Visitors to the inner sanctum of the temple often take a
ceremonial dip in the surrounding pool, which is considered sacred.
</TEXT>
