<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-wheel truck slammed into the side
of a moving train at a railway crossing today and hurled two
coaches into a deep irrigation canal, killing 27 people, officials
said.
   Hospital officials said another 22 people were injured, three
seriously, in the early morning crash in Takhli district of central
Nakhon Sawan province, 200 miles north of Bangkok.
   Chet Lumpeung, a local government official, earlier reported 20
people killed. He later said more bodies had been pulled out of the
canal.
   Chet said it wasn't clear what caused the crash, in which the
truck driver was killed instantly.
   The five-coach train operated by the State Railways of Thailand
was traveling north from Lopburi to Phitsanulok province.
