<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusAccidents     05-20 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Accidents,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scores Injured In Bus Accidents in Pennsylvania, Iowa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bus Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A school bus overturned on a sharp curve called ``Devil's
Elbow'' and plunged down an embankment in Pennsylvania, injuring 60
people, and another school bus flipped in Iowa, injuring 34
fifth-graders and others.
   Both accidents occurred Thursday afternoon.
   In the accident about 90 miles north of Harrisburg, Pa., the bus
went off the curve, fell about 20 feet and landed upside down,
police said.
   The bus, carrying 45 children and 15 adult chaperones from the
Walnut Street Christian School in Jersey Shore, was returning from
a field trip in Harrisburg.
   Sixteen children and eight adults were treated at Divine
Providence Hospital in Williamsport, nursing supervisor Margaret
Herz said. An adult passenger and a child were hospitalized in fair
condition today, but most of the other injuries were minor.
   Twenty-nine children and seven adults were treated at two other
area hospitals, mostly for bumps, scrapes and bruises, officials
said.
   State police said the driver was unfamiliar with the state road,
which he had taken to avoid a traffic tie-up, and said speed may
have contributed to the accident.
   ``He didn't know the turn was there,'' Trooper Allen Green said.
   In the Iowa crash, 63 people escaped serious injury when their
bus overturned on a county road south of Albion. Thirty-four
passengers were treated at hospitals in Marshalltown and Waterloo
for minor lacerations, bruises and fractures, then released,
officials said.
   The bus was carrying 58 students, two parent chaperones, two
teachers and a driver from Living History Farms near Des Moines
when it slipped off the pavement onto a muddy shoulder.
   The bus flipped on its side and skidded about 40 feet before
stopping on the edge of an embankment.
   ``We were turning the corner and the bus driver started yelling
and the back tires went off the road. Everybody started hollering
and we ran out the back,'' said Quentin Bolden, who said he was
sitting six rows from the front.
   Lowell Elementary School principal Bill Dodd traveled to Albion
to calm the youngsters.
   ``We're taking some of them home in vans because they're afraid
to ride the bus,'' Dodd said.
</TEXT>
