<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NIreland-Blast     05-20 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Blast,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Claims Responsiblity For Fairground Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlawed Irish Republican
Army today claimed responsibility for an explosion that ripped
through a police recruitment stand at a packed agricultural fair,
injuring 14 people.
   Seven police officers were among those injured in the blast
Thursday evening at the Balmoral Show Grounds, where thousands of
people were attending the annual Royal Ulster Agricultural Show.
   One policeman remained hospitalized today with burns, but the
others, including four children, were released after treatment,
police said.
   The explosion set off a fire in the police recruitment stand,
sending the crowds fleeing in fear.
   In a statement to Belfast news media, the IRA said the explosion
was caused by a 7-pound bomb placed under an office adjacent to the
police stand.
   Initial press reports said police believed the explosion was
caused not by a bomb but by a leak in a malfunctioning gas cylinder.
   But a police spokesman, Inspector Jim Robinson, said police were
not ruling out the possibility of a bombing. He said forensic
experts were still examining debris.
   The IRA accused the Royal Ulster Constabulary, the province's
mainly Protestant police force, of ``attempting to cover their
acute embarrassment (over not detecting the bomb) by releasing
disinformation to the media'' about the cause of the explosion.
   The IRA said it carried out the attack because the agricultural
fair _ the province's biggest such attraction of the year _ ``is
one of the jewels in the crown of Britain's normalization policy
and is protected by a massive Crown police force ... ''
   The province's security forces are the main targets of the IRA
in its guerrilla campaign to oust the British from Northern Ireland
and unite the Protestant-dominated province with the mainly Roman
Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
