<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoPhones     05-20 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No Phones,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cellular Phone Sales Boom After Service Disruption</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cellular telephone companies are enjoying a
``fire sale'' boom because of a blaze at an Illinois Bell switching
center that disrupted phone service for thousands of customers in
Chicago's western suburbs.
   ``It's been a hectic time, but we did enjoy some pretty good
business out of it,'' said Jerry Greenberg, president of Leader
Communications Inc. of Bellwood. ``Cellular telephones were a
lifesaver for many people ... who were not content to sit dead in
the water and had to have some communications.''
   Greenberg estimated sales have doubled since the May 8 fire that
ravaged a key Illinois Bell facility in Hinsdale.
   He said his company couldn't have operated without its own
cellular phones and portable facsimile machines, which were used to
place equipment orders when regular long-distance service was
interrupted.
   An Illinois Bell spokesman said all 35,000 customers in six
western suburbs where customers' phones went dead after the fire
should have some local phone service by Saturday, but will still
have difficulty calling outside their communities.
   As of Thursday, Bell workers had restored limited service to
31,000 of the subscribers, said company spokesman Tim Bannon.
   Bell expects that regional and long-distance lines and special
business lines transmitting computer data that were routed through
the Hinsdale center should be functioning almost normally by
Saturday, Bannon said.
   John Prescott, sales manager for the Cellular Communications
Corp. of Naperville, said cellular phone sales had tripled to 150
per week and profits had doubled since the fire.
   His customers included panic-stricken business people as well as
fence-sitters who moved up plans to buy cellular portable or car
phones.
   ``We probably did three times the business in a week that we
normally do ... and had to add on four workers,'' Prescott said.
   Pat Graham, marketing manager for Ameritech Mobile
Communications Service in Schaumburg said the phone outage boosted
an already booming market for cellular phones.
   ``Sales are better now than they've ever been in the company's
four-year history,'' said Ms. Graham. So far, sales over the first
two weeks of May in the Chicago area have already exceeded the
company's forecast for the entire month, she said.
</TEXT>
