<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusJoyride     05-20 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Joyride,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joyriding Youngster Leaves Neighborhood In Shambles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALINA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 9-year-old boy stole the keys to his
father's bus and went on a careening joyride through his
neighborhood, smashing into cars, a tree and a house as startled
residents tried to stop him.
   The bus finally came to rest in a trailer park. The boy and a
10-year-old friend were treated for minor injuries, but noone else
was hurt.
   ``He took the keys out of his mother's purse and just went for a
joyride,'' said Shelley Hanchett, who works with the boy's mother.
The boy's father drives a 23-passenger bus used to transport
special education students; the bus was severely damaged in the
incident Wednesday.
   ``I heard tires squealing and saw it coming down the street and
it sideswiped my car. It then turned the corner ... on two wheels
and disappeared. I tried to get the license plate number, but it
was going too fast,'' said Reaba Collins.
   The bus sideswiped two parked cars. It turned north, then east
and hit a pickup truck. Then it crossed a street and ripped limbs
from a tree in the front yard of a house.
   ``I saw it hit the tree so I ran out of the house toward the bus
to open its door,'' said Joyce Davis, who was visiting in the
house. ``It backed up and came toward me, so I ran. It then hit the
house. His eyes were wide open. He looked scared.''
   Richard Edwards said he ran out of his house after watching the
bus hit a street sign.
   ``I ran out and tried to reach in the window to stop the kid,
but he started changing gears and sped off,'' said Edwards, adding
that the boy locked the doors when another man tried to reach in
the window.
   Steve Goodwin said he was painting his house when he saw the bus
coming down the street.
   ``The bus finally came to a stop after he hit the last car. He
just let go of the steering wheel and stood up,'' Goodwin said.
   The 10-year-old had been hiding under a seat, Goodwin said. The
two boys then wandered around the bus because they couldn't get out
of the jammed doors, he said.
   ``The driver kept saying, `I can't let my mom catch me now,''
Goodwin said.
</TEXT>
