<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Violence 1stLd-Writethru a0525 05-20 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0525,0793</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amal Claims Hezbollah Tried to Swap Hostage for Weapons</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Amal saying it blocked attempt
to swap hostage for weapons. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mainstream Amal militia said today
that it blocked an attempt by the rival pro-Iranian Hezbollah to
swap a foreign hostage for weapons and ammunition from Christian
militias.
   ``Amal has thwarted an attempt by Hezbollah to turn over a
foreign hostage to the (Christian) Lebanese Forces (militia) in
return for ammunition and weapons for Hezbollah's besieged base in
Hajjaj Street,'' said Atif Aoun, a member of Amal's politburo.
   Aoun told about 10,000 supporters of the Syrian-backed Shiite
Moslem Amal militia in the southern town of Zahrani that Amal
foiled the alleged swap ``after we found out about the contacts
between Hezbollah and the Lebanese Forces.'' He did not elaborate.
   Groups affiliated with Hezbollah, or Party of God, are believed
to hold most of the 18 foreign hostages, including nine Americans,
in Lebanon.
   Aoun did not say whether one particular hostage or nationality
was involved in the alleged deal.
   Hezbollah's base is in Hajjaj Street, in south Beirut's Shiyah
district.
   Positions of the Lebanese Forces Christian militia are in the
district of Ein Rummaneh, east of Hajjaj Street.
   The two districts have been separated by a 25-yard-deep
no-man's-land since the Lebanese civil war broke out in 1975.
   There was no way to verify the report independently, and neither
the Lebanese Forces nor Hezbollah had any immediate comment.
   Aoun made the charge as Amal, Arabic for hope, and Hezbollah
battled for a 15th day in the slums of south Beirut, where the
Western hostages are believed held.
   Syrian forces, massed around the disputed area since Saturday,
were threatening to move in and stop the fighting.
   A representative of a Seattle-based human rights group arrived
in Lebanon to try to meet with a Shiite Moslem religious leader and
deliver a petition that calls for the release of foreign hostages.
   In addition, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Vernon
Walters, arrived in the Syrian capital of Damascus today to try to
secure the release of the American hostages.
   Walters, speaking to reporters Thursday in Jerusalem, said his
Middle East mission was prompted by concerns about the hostages'
safety in the face of the intense Amal-Hezbollah fighting. He
refused to elaborate.
   Police said seven people were killed and 38 wounded in today's
exchanges. That raises the toll to at least 251 people killed and
810 wounded since May 6, when the battles broke out.
   On Thursday, Amal leader Nabih Berri, who is also Lebanon's
justice minister, announced a sweeping purge of the militia's
military command. Amal said in a statement that Berri fired the
militia's top military commander, Akel Hamieh, and five senior
aides.
   The statement did not give a reason. However, a ranking Amal
official who spoke on condition of anonymity said the six were
fired for ``conspiring with Hezbollah in south Beirut.
   Syria deployed 7,500 troops and 500 tanks on the southern,
western and northern edges of south Beirut over the weekend after
Hezbollah seized about 90 precent of the enclave from Amal.
   Syrian officers have said they were delaying a decision to move
into south Beirut until diplomatic efforts have been exhausted.
   Clashes persisted despite efforts by Iran's acting foreign
minister, Ali Mohammed Besharati, to arrange a truce.
   Besharati on Thursday softened his earlier opposition to Syrian
military intervention.
   ``If the entry of the Syrian forces to the suburbs guarantees
security, we will not object,'' Besharati told reporters after
meeting with Lebanese Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, is Iran's principal
Arab ally in the Persian Gulf war against Iraq. However, Damascus
has become increasingly alarmed by Iran's efforts to dominate
Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites, the largest single sect.
   Ray Barnett, a Protestant clergyman from Canada representing the
Seattle-based Friends in the West, a Christian human rights group,
arrived in the port of Jounieh today.
   Barnett said he hoped to meet with Sheik Mohammed Hussein
Fadlallah, spiritual guide of Hezbollah, to deliver a petition
bearing 40,000 signatures from the United States and Britain.
   In the United States, former hostage David Jacobsen said
Wednesday the petition was expected to be delivered this weekend.
Jacobsen said the petition reads:
   ``As believers in Almighty God we have faith that prayer is more
powerful than armies or contingents of diplomats. Because of this
we respectfully ask you to pray with us and to do whatever you can
to intercede on behalf of all these hostages and captives.''

</TEXT>
