<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--PurpleCop     05-20 0182</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Purple Cop,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beautician Error Led to Suspension of Officer, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer who was suspended after she
reported to work with purple hair and a matching purple dress is
trying to get paid for the five days she missed and have the
incident washed off her record.
   Nancy Murphy was charged with willfully disobeying an order _ to
change the color of her hair.
   Covering the purple top with a wig was insufficient, especially
because Murphy did that two days after the order, a police hearing
attorney said.
   Donald Stolberg, an attorney for members of the Detroit Police
Officers Association, said Murphy was blameless in the August 1985
incident.
   ``She didn't order her beautician to turn her hair purple,''
Stolberg said. ``Rather, it was a catastrophe; she was mortified.''
   Stolberg said Murphy tried to comply with the order, but Lt. Joe
McCarroll, representing the Police Department, said Murphy ``had
purple hair and wore a purple dress and came to work like that.''
   There was no immediate decision on Murphy's appeal to the police
hearing board.
</TEXT>
