<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Sofaer     05-20 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Sofaer,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Investigate Alleged Removal of Arifacts by U.S. Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli official said Abraham Sofaer, the
U.S. State Department legal adviser, took archaeological artifacts
out of Israel without a required government permit.
   Uri Dahari, head of the archeological robbery prevention section
at Israel's Department of Antiquities, said on Thursday that Sofaer
bought the artifacts from an underground dealer and took them out
of the country without a special permit required from the Israeli
agency.
   The Education Ministry said Sofaer was being investigated but
did not give further details.
   A senior Israeli official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said investigators would contact Sofaer but as far as he knew, the
U.S. official would not be prosecuted.
   ``What is clear to us is that Abraham Sofaer violated the law,''
Dahari told Israel army radio Thursday.
   The U.S. State Department said Thursday night that the Israeli
government was not pursuing any investigation. Spokesman Dennis
Harter said Israel has announced ``there is nothing to the
allegation which warrants any action.''
   Sofaer could not be reached for comment, a secretary in his
Washington office said.
   Dahari said his department would view the return of the
artifacts as the end of the incident.
   The Israeli newspaper Haaretz quoted an unidentified aide to
Sofaer as saying the U.S. official purchased arifacts only from
licensed dealers and was willing to return any artifacts found to
have been removed illegally.
   Sofaer was in Israel recently to help settle an Israeli-Egyptian
border dispute.
   David Matnai, minister-counselor for political affairs at the
Israeli Embassy in Washington, said the investigation was over and
that the matter ``was blown out of proportion. I think it was
something minor.''
   Dahari said the activity came to light in an investigation of
several people who were allegedly raiding archeological sites.
   One of those under investigation claimed he sold coins and other
artifacts to Sofaer, Dahari said.
</TEXT>
