<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SheriffCharged     05-20 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sheriff Charged,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sheriff Charged With Interfering With Prisoner's Medical Care</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The county sheriff went into an ailing
prisoner's hospital room, disconnected his oxygen tube and took him
to court even though doctors said he shouldn't be moved, a federal
indictment charges.
   Wyandotte County Sheriff John Quinn was charged with violating a
prisoner's civil rights by interfering with his medical care in an
indictment handed up Thursday. A doctor said the prisoner had to be
put into intensive care after he was returned to the hospital.
   Quinn, who faces up to a year in prison and a $1,000 fine if
convicted, said Thursday he had no comment.
   He was accused of disconnecting Damone Lee Cribbs' intravenous
pump and oxygen supply line and taking Cribbs from Bethany Hospital
to a court appearance on July 2, 1986.
   Early that day Cribbs, who had asthma, had complained of
breathing difficulties, and he was taken from jail to Bethany at
about noon.
   At about 3:30 p.m. Cribbs, 19, was taken from the hospital to
the Wyandotte County Courthouse to be sentenced on a misdemeanor
theft charge. He was returned to the hospital about 45 minutes
later.
   By then, Cribbs' condition had worsened and he had to be put in
intensive care, said Dr. John Gamble, physician at the Wyandotte
County Jail. He was hospitalized for several days, Gamble said.
   Cribbs received a year's probation for stealing a wallet from a
woman's purse.
</TEXT>
