<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Chief,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tribal Chief Who Remembered Arrival of White Settlers Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BULAWAYO, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tribal chief who witnessed the
arrival of some of the first white settlers a century ago has died
at age 109, it was reported Friday.
   Chief Wavela Mazetese, from the Mwenezi district of Matabeleland
province in western Zimbabwe, died in his village Sunday after a
short illness, the state-owned Chronicle newspaper said.
   Mazetese, in a 1984 newspaper interview, said he was a boy
tending his father's cattle when the first whites he had seen
appeared on horses and in wagons led by oxen.
   Historians said the whites were probably among the first
settlers to arrive in the former British colony of Rhodesia in the
1890s.
   The colony won its independence as a black-governed nation in
1980 following a guerrilla war. It was renamed Zimbabwe, after an
ancient gold-rich African kingdom.
   Mazetese is survived by a wife and 20 children.
</TEXT>
