<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kuwait-Explosion     05-20 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait-Explosion,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Men Killed in Blast Portrayed as Pious, But Misled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Kuwaiti men killed when their bomb-laden car
blew up before reaching its intended target were pious Moslems who
were duped by criminals, it was reported Friday.
   The newspaper Al-Qabas also said that fighting terrorism should
include ``immunizing citizens against falling easy prey to
protagonists of crime and deepening sentiments of patriotism with
the youth.''
   The paper warned that more terrrorism should be expected.
   Interior Ministry officials said the two men were planning to
park the car in front of the Kuwait Airways building in downtown
Kuwait on Wednesday, but the explosives apparently went off
prematurely.
   The blast was the third in this northern Persian Gulf country in
less than a month. In December 1983, a car bomb exploded at the
U.S. and French embassies, and in 1985, an attempt was made on the
life of the emir, Sheik Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah.
   Last month, a Kuwait Airways jetliner was hijacked for 16 days
and two Kuwaitis aboard were killed by the gunmen, who have been
described as pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem fundamentalists.
   ``We have to shoulder our historic responsibility ... because
confining our attitude to condemation of crimes and counting
casualties will be without avail if we want our country to live in
peace and security,'' Al-Qabas said.
   The two young Kuwaitis, who have been identified as Nasser
Mohammed Ali Hassan Ahmed, 22, and Walid Abdel-Nabi Mohammed Mousa
Al-Mousa, 23, were killed when the car they were traveling in
exploded near the airline's head office.
   Al-Qabas quoted a sister of Ahmed as saying that her family was
surprised to learn about the incident. She described her brother as
``a fervent Moslem who strictly performs his religious obligations
and leads a normal life. We did not discern anything abnormal in
his day-to-day behavior.''
   She said he was a teacher at an elementary school, unmarried and
owned the car that exploded. Her family did not know the companion
killed with him, she said.
   Al-Qabas said Al-Mousa was a geography student at Kuwait
University, and was married with no children.
   The paper quoted Al-Mousa's brother, Adnan, as saying his
brother was ``a very committed Moslem.'' His brother recently
traveled to Turkey and Greece, he said.
</TEXT>
