<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Leak,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Flight Developed Leak, Made Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Airlines jet bound for
Puerto Rico made an emergency landing in Bermuda last week after a
leak began spewing fuel into the Atlantic Ocean, officials said
today.
   No injuries were reported when the twin-engine jet, a new
wide-body Airbus A300-600R, landed after losing fuel through a
crack in the right engine, American spokesman Steve McGregor said.
   The flight was en route to San Juan, Puerto Rico, from New
York's John F. Kennedy Airport on Tuesday, May 10, when a pump
casing split, he said.
   The pilot attempted to stop fuel from flowing to the damaged
engine pump, but the shut-off valve was beyond the crack.
   He then released fire-extinguisher bottles inside the engine to
shut it down and diverted to Bermuda, McGregor said.
   The spokesman said he didn't know how much fuel was left on
landing and added that authorities have not yet determined the
cause of the split.
</TEXT>
