<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MapleProduction     05-20 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maple Production,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maple Sugaring Season Better Than Last</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maple syrup production was up by 225,000
gallons this year, but producers didn't have the banner year they
had been hoping for this spring.
   According to the U.S. Department of Agriculture, New England and
New York state produced 805,000 gallons in 1988, with a gallon of
syrup costing an average $34.72 in New England and $25 in New York.
   Vermont again led the nation in production, with 370,000
gallons. New York followed with 310,000 gallons, while New
Hampshire produced 74,000 gallons, Massachusetts produced 44,000
gallons and Maine produced 7,000 gallons.
   In addition, 69,000 gallons of syrup were produced in northern
Maine, on land owned by paper companies near the Canadian border.
   In 1987, the 1987 yield was 580,000 gallons, the worst in 16
years.
   ``The season was a short one, I think _ 28 days,'' said John
Ketcham of the USDA's New England Agricultural Statistics Service.
``A good share of the producers only got one good run, especially
in northern Vermont.''
   If the yield wasn't superior, the quality was.
   ``As far as color this year, it was great, mostly medium to
light and there was a lot of light. It was good quality syrup,''
Ketcham said.
   ``The percentage of the crop that was in the top grades is
high,'' said Everett Willard, maple marketing specialist for the
Vermont Department of Agriculture.
   The sugaring industry was worth $17.188 million in New England
and $7.75 million in New York, up from $11.078 million last year in
New England and up from $5.243 million in New York.
</TEXT>
