<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chess     05-20 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chess,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kasparov Ahead In Dutch Tournament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet world chess champion Gary
Kasparov has taken the lead in a four-player spectacular that pits
him against arch-rival Anatoly Karpov in their first meeting since
the championship last year.
   Halfway through the tournament, Kasparov topped the standings
Thursday with four points for an unbeaten performance of two wins
and four draws from the six rounds played so far in the event.
   Karpov, also from the Soviet Union, was running a close second,
lagging half a point behind the champion.
   Kasparov beat Karpov in 1985 to become world champion and
retained his title last year in Seville, Spain.
   In their first match since Seville, the two drew. In the second
match, Kasparov came out on top in a fantastic win.
   That game, in which Kasparov played white against his arch
enemy's pet Caro-Kann defense, was one of the wildest and most
exciting in recent tournament play at the grandmaster level,
according to visiting British grandmaster Tony Miles.
   After the ``great K's'', as they have become known, drew their
first encounter since last year's world title match in Seville,
Spain, experts were predicting the same result in Wednesday's match.
   But Kasparov sprung a surprise on Karpov and on the all-knowing
experts.
   After just 16 moves, he sacrificed a knight and followed up with
an all-out attack on the black King's side that grandmaster Miles
said was ``a perfect example of pure fighting chess.''
   Experts in the press room were at a loss to explain Kasparov's
daring play and the one-hundred strong audience in the tournament
hall were standing on their seats to miss nothing of the
hair-raising duel.
   Karpov initially weathered the onslaught, capturing a second
piece and countering with a mating threat of his own.
   But problems arose as he ran into time trouble.
   On the 25th move, he missed a chance to win in one move. On the
39th, he exceeded the time limit where he was one move short of the
control in a position that the experts afterwards said was probably
a draw.
   Against Holland's John van der Wiel in Thursday's sixth round,
Karpov was his old self again, coolly making the most of his slim
advantage in a Queen's Indian, gradually increasing the pressure
against black's weakened center and clinching victory on the 39th
move.
   Kasparov's encounter with Dutchman Jan Timman, ranked third on
the world rating list, was more of an anticlimax.
   The world champion, playing white, refrained from taking the
initiative against his theoretically weaker opponent.
   Visiting grandmaster Miles hypothesized that Kasparov was still
``somewhat dizzy'' from his victory over Karpov.
   Early on, Timman had some trouble in stopping white's attack,
but eventually evened out around his 40th to sign the peace five
moves later.
   The tournament, with a World Chess Federation category 17 and an
average rating of 2,674 points _ the strongest ever held _ will
continue Sunday with Kasparov facing Van der Wiel and Karpov
playing Timman in seventh-round action.
   After six rounds, Kasparov had 4 points; Karpov 3{; Timman 3;
and Van der Wiel 1{.
</TEXT>
