<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Olympics     05-20 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Olympics,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kim Proposes Political Talks With North Korea On Olympics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung on
Friday proposed that South Korea and North Korea hold talks on
being co-hosts for the Olympic Games opening in Seoul in September.
   Kim, head of the largest opposition Party for Peace and
Democracy, made the proposal at a meeting of 71 party members who
were recently elected to the National Assembly.
   ``If possible, we need to explore ways to co-host the Olympics
through talks between political parties of the two sides,'' he said.
   Kim, 62, said he believes North Korea is less enthusiastic about
taking part in the Olympics but South Korea should persuade them to
attend.
   The opposition leader said he would inform the government of his
idea when he visits the Seoul Olympic Organizing Committee on
Saturday.
   Kim said if the issue of being co-hosts is solved, South Korea
would benefit by ensuring the security of the Olympics and forcing
North Korea to open its closed society, thereby promoting chances
of national unification.
   Roh's governing Democratic Justice Party denoucned Kim's
statement as ``a irresponsible political maneuvering'' that may
compound the Olympic and other inter-Korea issues.
   Democratic Justice Party spokesman Kim Jung-wee said although
all South Korean people are free to debate the Olympics matter, it
is necessary that the government should serve as a ``unified''
channel of dialogue with North Korea.
   The nation's two other opposition groups, Kim Young-sam's
Reunification Democratic Party and Kim Jong-pil's New Democratic
Republican Party, reacted with skepticism to Kim Dae-jung's
proposal.
   Reunification Democratic Party spokesman Suh Chung-won quoted
his party leader, Kim Young-sam, as saying, ``The proposal is
impossible to be be put into practice.''
   New Democratic spokesman Cho Yong-jik said, ``All
unification-related debate should be open, but it is desirable that
dialogue with North Korea should be conducted through concerned
government authorities.''
   North Korea has said it will boycott the Olympics in Seoul
unless it is made a co-host. Despite its threat to organize a
Communist-bloc boycott, a record 161 nations, including the Soviet
Union and China, have said they would send athletes to Seoul.
   The International Olympic Committee said any idea of having both
nations serve as hosts would be a violation of the Olympic charter.
</TEXT>
