<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-US     05-20 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-US,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Disperse Anti-U.S. March; Aquino Urged to Take Stand on
Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police wielding riot sticks dispersed
about 300 demonstrators Friday who marched near the U.S. Embassy
and demanded removal of American military bases in the Philippines.
   Vice President Salvador Laurel urged President Corazon Aquino to
notify the United States immediately if she doesn't plan to extend
the lease on the six bases.
   A crowd of anti-nuclear activists chanting anti-American slogans
marched to within 20 yards of the U.S. Embassy. Police moved in
after the protesters refused to stop the march.
   Reporters said some demonstrators sat on the ground and were
dragged away by police. At least 11 demonstrators were taken to a
nearby precinct, but police said they didn't make any arrests.
   Laurel told a civic group that Mrs. Aquino should take a public
position on the issue, the subject of talks between the United
States and the Philippines.
   The president has pledged to allow the bases to remain here
until their lease expires in 1991, but she has refused to say
whether she would agree to an extension.
   ``You cannot keep your options open until 1991, because one year
before 1991 you must already give notice of your intention to
terminate,'' Laurel said.
   In related development, Sen. Rene Saguisag filed a bill Friday
banning the use of ``futuristic'' weapons in the country. The
proposal supplements earlier congressional bills outlawing the use
of any part of the Philippines for storage of nuclear weapons.
   ``It is hereby declared illegal for any part of the Philippine
territory to be used for assembly, storage, deployment, transit, or
any other use of any futuristic weapons like laser beams, laser
rays and particle beam generators,'' the bill said.
   The bill would make it illegal for a person to bring into the
country even components of such weapons. Violators could face 10
years to life in prison.
   The bill proposes that foreigners found to have violated the ban
be deported after serving the full prison sentence.
</TEXT>
