<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BurningPiano     05-20 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burning Piano,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Pinging' Piano Alerts Owner To Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LENOIR, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pop of a burning piano's strings was
sweet music to its owner, who credits the noise with awakening him
in time to escape a fire that destroyed his home.
   ``I was awakened by a ping, ping, ping,'' said Bennie Conner,
41. ``It sounded like someone playing it, but it was a high, shrill
sound.''
   Thursday's fire, apparently sparked by a faulty electrical
heater in the basement, quickly enveloped the two-story wood house
in this western North Carolina town, fire officials said.
   Conner's wife and a son had already left for work and school
when the fire spread and the sound of the piano woke Conner. Flames
caused the piano's strings to snap, creating the ``pinging'' sound.
   Conner said he opened his eyes to see smoke curling under the
door of the bedroom. He grabbed his clothes and made his way
through thick, black smoke to the front door, he said.
   Conner said he and his wife bought the piano for their younger
son to practice on. An older son no longer lives at home.
   ``I'm just thankful we had the piano,'' Conner said. ``I'm not
sure I would have awoke if it hadn't been for it.''
</TEXT>
