<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Roles Bjt   05-20 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Roles, Bjt,0756</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women and Children First _ Into Battle</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen-year-old Niveen
Dahman does the housework for her family now that her mother is in
jail. She cooks and cleans, and when clashes with Israeli soldiers
erupt, she runs to the streets to help youngsters choking on tear
gas.
   ``I am doing the same as my mother. It's my duty,'' said Niveen,
sitting in her family's cement block house in the Shati refugee
camp. In the next room was a box full of chickens that the family
is raising to eat as the Arab uprising persists, bringing with it
worsening economic conditions.
   A new role for Moslem children and women, both held under strict
rule in the traditional religious society, is one of the changes
spawned by the nearly six-month rebellion against Israel's
occupation of the Gaza Strip and West Bank.
   According to U.N. figures through April, a quarter of the 4,344
Palestinians in Gaza injured in the revolt were under 16.
   Israeli authorities complain that their soldiers are
increasingly facing women and children rioters.
   ``Now we are the leaders,'' said 19-year-old Rafat, sitting on
the floor of another cement block house down the street from Niveen
Dahman's home.
   ``Youth are leading, burning tires, stoning soldiers,'' said
Rafat, who would not give his last name. ``Women try to help the
boys who are arrested or try to stop arrests. They go to the kids
when soldiers throw tear gas.''
   Niveen Dahman's mother, Widad, was arrested this month as an
``inciter'' along with two other women in Shati. They were the
first women to be jailed in the Gaza Strip under administrative
detention laws, where no trials or specific charges are required.
Each was given six months in prison.
   Palestinian activitist Mary Khas says the arrests showed that
Israel has recognized the new power of women in the uprising.
Women, allowed out during curfew, became messengers and lookouts,
she said.
   ``Women found their authority and strength and started
organizing,'' said Ms. Khas, who runs a kindergarten program
throughout the Gaza Strip.
   As for Palestinian youth, Ms. Khas said, ``They did what
youngsters do _ try to change things. It was a spontaneous mass
revolt.''
   The Palestine Liberation Organization and fundamentalist Moslem
groups are behind the rebellion, but Ms. Khas said it was the
young, ``the grassroots leadership,'' that kept the uprising going.
   She pointed out that Israel had arrested many traditional
leaders active in PLO-organized committees of lawyers, doctors and
other professionals, but still the revolt persists.
   ``They're all the time arresting what they call the leadership,
but they haven't gotten the leaders,'' she said.
   Riad Al Agha, a former president of Gaza Islamic University,
said the stifling life of the refugee camps has spawned young
leaders who do not have their parents' fear of Israeli soldiers.
   ``The uprising right now is led by youth age 15 to 25. Most live
in the refugee camps around the strip and the West Bank,'' he said.
``They will never listen to the older generation.''
   Agha described the revolt this way: ``Most of the men go to work
in Israel and leave their sons at home to throw stones.'' He said
sons sometimes stop fathers from going to work, but not forever.
   Agha, who has a Ph.D. from the University of Kansas, said many
of the youth in Gaza have taken up the hard-line ideas of the
Islamic Jihad, or Holy War, a radical fundamentalist group that
wants an Islamic state including all of what is now Israel.
   He said if the revolt persists with no Israeli concessions,
youth will emerge as political leaders and replace so-called
moderates who would be satisfied with a Palestinian state alongside
Israel.
   The young men on the streets think they are winning, since they
have faced Israel's might with only rocks and painted slogans.
   One day last week, a group of boys and young men set a tire
ablaze at the entrance to Gaza City. They were waiting by the road
with stones in hand.
   Hamad, who said he was 15 but looked years younger, said they
wanted revenge for Arabs beaten earlier, and they hoped Israeli
soldiers would come by. They also were targeting cars taking
workers to Israel, he said.
   ``I don't go to Israel,'' Hamad said. ``My work is here _
throwing stones.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
