<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmCredit     05-20 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Credit,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kentucky Land Bank To Receive $90 Million Under New Farm Credit
Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About $90 million in federal aid has been
approved for the Federal Land Bank of Louisville, Ky., the Farm
Credit System Assistance Board announced Friday.
   Eric P. Thor, the board's chief executive officer, said the
Louisville bank will receive assistance through the sale of up to
$90 million in preferred stock to the Financial Assistance Corp.,
which will raise funds for that investment by selling 15-year bonds.
   The board and corporation were created by last year's
Agricultural Credit Act to help bail out the financially distressed
Farm Credit System, a network of cooperatively owned farm banks and
associations.
   Thor said the Louisville bank, which serves borrowers in Ohio,
Indiana, Kentucky and Tennessee, applied to the board for financial
help in February. He said the board and the bank have ``reached
agreement on a number of steps which will continue to strengthen''
the institution's financial management.
   Although the Louisville bank had presented ``a well-thought-out,
workable plan for financial recovery,'' its stock had dropped to 65
percent of par value and was unable to implement the plan without
federal help, he said.
   ``The bank has made substantial progress in resolving its own
financial problems over the past two years,'' Thor said.
   Programs included an asset-liability management program in 1986
to control interest rate risks and reduce costs, and a market-based
loan pricing system in 1987 to provide competitive rates to
borrowers. Also, he said, the bank ``reduced its non-performing
loans and inventory of acquired property by 30 percent, and
projects a similar reduction this year.''
   Jeanne Kling, a spokewoman for the board, said the $90 million
for the Louisville bank was ``the first full-blown'' assistance
designated under the new law.
   Earlier this year, the board approved $25 million in ``limited
purpose'' assistance in short-term funding to help the Federal Land
Bank of Jackson, Miss., stay in business. And $20.5 million was
provided to retire stock in six financially troubled production
credit associations in the Omaha, Neb., and Spokane, Wash.,
districts.
   ``But this is the first one that we've done under the general
context of helping the bank'' in general, Ms. Kling said.

</TEXT>
