<2ND_LINE>AM-Morse Code Winner,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High School Senior Taps Out Winning Essay In Morse Code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took Kimberly Estes eight painstaking
hours to tap out the essay that won her first place and $2,000 in a
contest.
   Miss Estes, who suffers from cerebral palsy, wrote her essay in
Morse code.
   She can't walk, talk or move her arms well. But the 18-year-old
high school senior earned a 4.0 average at McGavock High School and
was the top French student at Apollo Middle School.
   Miss Estes plans to attend David Lipscomb College this fall,
where she may major in biochemistry.
   She communicates with Morse code, using a computer system her
father and a friend devised. At home, she communicates by gesturing
and nodding her head.
   ``She loves to write, and she has a lot to say,'' her father,
Wayne Estes, said. ``Even now, she says a great deal with her eyes.
She is very expressive.''
   Miss Estes was stricken at birth with cerebral palsy, a disorder
of the central nervous system that results from brain damage. It is
characterized by paralysis and difficulty with motor movement.
   She tries to control her tremors and spasms by concentrating on
relaxing, using an electrode to measure her heart rate.
   The theme of Miss Estes' essay was doing one's best.
   The assigned topic was the media's role in reporting on the
politicians' private lives. Miss Estes criticized Sen. Joseph Biden
of Delaware, the Democratic presidential candidate who admitted
plagiarizing part of a speech.
   Her essay began, ``For many years, the American people have been
producing shoddy manufactured products; their children have been
socially promoted and have received diplomas without really being
educated or appreciating the value of education.''
   Miss Estes plans to donate part of her prize money from the
annual Metro Public School Essay Contest to a shelter for the
homeless and use the rest for a trip to Hawaii.
</TEXT>
