<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1441EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BayQuakes     05-20 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bay Quakes,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Study: Another Great Quake Unlikely Soon In San Francisco</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cambodians-Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Devastating earthquakes have occurred
only every 200 to 400 years on the northern San Andreas Fault, says
a study that provides some comfort for San Franciscans worried
about a repeat of the deadly 1906 quake.
   California Institute of Technology geologist Carol S. Prentice,
who presented her study of earthquake frequency Friday at the
American Geophysical Union's spring meeting in Baltimore, said she
found evidence of six great quakes in the last 2,000 years along a
260-mile stretch of the fault. The last was the 1906 shaker that
killed at least 2,500 people.
   At this interval, it would mean that the San Francisco Bay area
is unlikely to have a devastating quake within the next 100 years
and possiby much longer, said Prentice's professor and co-author,
geologist Kerry Sieh.
   However, Sieh cautioned the study is preliminary, so while ``one
is tempted to conclude (with certainty) that a great earthquake is
not likely in the near future in Northern California, that would be
a premature conclusion at this point.''
   The study involved only the northern San Andreas. The Hayward
Fault and other faults in Northern California also pose a threat,
and the state Office of Emergency Services says the probability of
a damaging earthquake in the Bay area in the next 30 years is about
50 percent.
   So ``people shouldn't get too complacent'' because of the new
study, Prentice said Thursday in a telephone interview from
Washington.
   Prentice made excavations across the San Andreas near Point
Arena about 160 miles north of San Francisco and found evidence of
at least six large quakes in the last 2,000 years, suggesting an
occurrence of every 300 to 400 years.
   However, the study also found evidence the fault is building up
strain at a rate that suggests the interval between large quakes
might be only 200 years, Sieh said.
   The 1906 quake ruptured a stretch of fault that starts just
south of Cape Mendocino, then runs south through Point Arena, Marin
County and the San Francisco Peninsula to San Juan Bautista.
   Federal emergency officials have estimated a repeat of the quake
would kill up to 11,000 people, seriously injure up to 44,000 and
cause $38 billion in damage.
   For Southern California, forecasts of a great quake's advent are
grimmer. Based on other studies, including work by Sieh, the state
Office of Emergency Services says another major devastating quake
in Southern California is more than 50 percent likely within the
next 25 years.
   Federal officials have projected that a great quake on the
southern San Andreas would kill up to 14,000 people, injure up to
55,000 and cause $17 billion in damage.
   Sieh's research on the southern San Andreas Fault suggests great
quakes occur an average of every 140 years on the section from
Tejon Pass, northwest of Los Angeles, to Cajon Pass, north of San
Bernardino. The last such quake occurred in 1857.
   He also found the next segment to the southeast, from Cajon Pass
through Palm Springs to the Salton Sea, breaks in a great or major
quake an average of every 200 to 250 years, with the last such
quake more than 300 years ago, suggesting the segment is overdue
for a big quake.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0146 </DOCNO>
