<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Prostitute-AIDS     05-20 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prostitute-AIDS,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Jail Release of Prostitute with AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prostitute arrested on charges of
attempted manslaughter for selling sex while carrying AIDS has been
sent home because of her failing health.
   Elizabeth Kay Sherouse, 24, was released from jail and placed
under house arrest.
   Ms. Sherouse was arrested five months ago after investigators
said she twice had sex with men knowing she carried the deadly
virus. The charges were later dismissed for lack of evidence, but
she remained in jail while the prosecution appealed the dismissal.
   On Thursday, Circuit Judge Michael Cycmanick reduced her bail
from $14,000 to $1,000 because of her declining health and a
doctor's prognosis that she had less than three years to live.
   ``There is no way this girl will physically be able to get on
the streets again,'' her attorney, William Sheaffer, said at the
hearing. ``I believe her last days should be spent with some degree
of dignity. We shouldn't allow her to die like we wouldn't allow
some animals to die.''
   The AIDS virus triggered severe infections in most of her vital
organs last month, said her doctor, Phillip Sanchez. She had
surgery, a seizure and almost died twice of heart failure, he said.
   ``I feel real great about going home,'' said Ms. Sherouse, frail
but smiling as she left the Orange County Jail. She was steadied by
her attorney.
   Sanchez wrote the judge that he counseled Ms. Sherouse about the
possibilities of transmitting the acquired immune deficiency
syndrome virus through sex, but added, ``The ability to understand
the gravity of the situation was found to be uninterpretable by the
patient.''
   Prosecutor Rick Bogle argued that her release could endanger the
public, noting she had ignored previous counseling against having
sex because she carried the AIDS virus.
   Her mother, Jeanette Sherouse, burst into tears when asked by
Sheaffer if her daughter's grave condition would make her watch her
daughter more closely. Mrs. Sherouse, a nurse's aide, said she and
her son would supervise her daughter.
</TEXT>
