<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Cuba     05-20 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Cuba,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Assures Cuban-Americans Freedom in Cuba Is `Non-Negotiable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan told a cheering audience of
Cuban-Americans on Friday that he considers the freedom of Cuba ``a
non-negotiable issue.''
   Reagan spoke to a small gathering in the White House Roosevelt
Room at a ceremony marking the 86th anniversary of the
establishment of the Cuban republic.
   The walls of the room are adorned with pictures and other
memorabilia of Theodore Roosevelt, who led a detachment of
volunteer cavalry known as the Rough Riders in action in Cuba
during the Spanish-American war in 1898.
   Vice President George Bush stood by the president's side as he
spoke.
   The audience frequently interrupted, standing to applaud and cry
out ``bravo.''
   Reagan ended his speech ``Viva Cuba libre,'' or ``Long live free
Cuba.''
   ``Cuban-Americans have demonstrated that free people can come
together unencumbered by tyranny, and I am confident the time will
come when the spirit of freedom will reign in Cuba itself,'' he
said.
   ``Having suffered personally the evils of communism, you have an
acute understanding of the danger that communist expansion poses to
this hemisphere,'' Reagan told the Cuban-Americans. ``You have
stood in support of people everywhere who seek freedom, such as the
people of Nicaragua.''
   ``Let me assure you, as far as this administration is concerned,
the freedom of Cuba is a non-negotiable issue.''
   ``We will never, ever negotiate away the dream of every
Cuban-American, a dream that I too hold in my heart, that Cuba will
again join the family of free and democratic nations,'' the
president said.
   ``Only 90 miles of ocean separate the island of Cuba from the
United States, but between our governments is an unbridgeable
gulf.''
</TEXT>
