<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FantasyMurder     05-20 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fantasy Murder,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Pleads Guilty Before Retrial In Fantasy Game Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager charged with killing a
playmate during a ``Dungeons and Dragons'' game three years ago
pleaded guilty as jury selection in his retrial was to begin.
   ``I just wish this never happened,'' David K. Ventiquattro, 17,
of Herrings said Thursday before pleading guilty to the Nov. 12,
1985, shotgun slaying of 11-year-old Martin Howland.
   Ventiquattro was preparing to stand trial in Jefferson County
Court a second time in the slaying. His 1986 conviction was
overturned for shooting Howland, whom he testified had to be killed
because he had become an evil character in the fantasy game, which
involves medieval monsters.
   The Appellate Division of the state Supreme Court ruled in March
that the youth's confession was inadmissible because he was
isolated from his parents and attorney during eight hours of
questioning by state police.
   Onondaga County Judge J. Kevin Mulroy sentenced the teen-ager to
five years-to-life at the Brookwood Center, a youth detention
facility in Claverack, where he already has served 2{ years.
   Defense attorney William J. McClusky said Ventiquattro pleaded
guilty in hopes of avoiding incarceration at a maximum-security
prison for adults. Ventiquattro also waived his right to appeal.
</TEXT>
