<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Helicopter     05-20 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Helicopter,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Reverses Decision, Will Recover Helicopter Wreckage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Navy has decided to recover the
wreckage of a helicopter gunship that went down in the Persian
Gulf, rather than blowing it up on the seabed, a military official
said Friday.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the Navy
reversed its decision ``to better enable investigators to determine
the cause of the crash,'' specifically whether the Marine Corps
AH-1 Cobra was lost to gunfire or missiles.
   The helicopter vanished on a night reconnaissance mission April
18, a few hours after U.S. and Iranian naval forces had fought a
series of day-long clashes in the southern gulf.
   It went down about 15 miles southeast of Abu Musa island, where
the Iranians have a military base.
   Tehran later claimed that its forces shot down the helicopter.
The Iranians said they had recovered the wreckage, but offered no
evidence.
   U.S. officials have said the Cobra's pilots reported in their
last message that they were being tracked by hostile radar.
   There were no reports or indications of weapons being fired in
the area afterward, the officials said.
   The Navy announced several days ago that the wreckage, in
several pieces about 130 feet deep off the United Arab Emirates
coast, would be ``destroyed in place'' by underwater demolition
divers.
   But Friday's statement said that ``in order to facilitate
further investigation, given the condition of the wreckage, the
decision was made to recover the aircraft wreckage except for the
ordnance.'' The weapons would be ``destroyed separately,'' it said.
   The debris will be lifted by a seagoing crane that has been at
the crash site for the past week with two salvage tugboats.
   The U.S. official also said the bodies of the two pilots,
recovered earlier, will be flown to Dover Air Base in Dover, Del.,
on Friday.
   The two Marines, Capt. Kenneth Hill, 33 and Capt. Stephen
Leslie, 30, based at New River, N.C., have been declared ``Killed
in Action,'' although the cause of the crash has yet to be
estabished.
   Navy officers said that ruling could be made even if the
aircraft was not actually shot down, but crashed while trying to
evade hostile fire.
   The pilots were the only U.S. casualties in the April 18
clashes, and raised to 46 the number of Americans killed in
military operations related to the gulf in the past year.
   The biggest single casualty toll was 37 sailors killed aboard
the U.S. frigate Stark May 17 last year when the warship came under
a missile attack by an Iraqi warplane.
   Baghdad said the pilot had mistaken the Stark for an Iranian
warship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
