<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--BraidwoodNuclear     05-20 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Braidwood Nuclear,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC OKs Full-Power License for Illinois Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission voted
unanimously Friday to approve a full-power license to Commonwealth
Edison Co. for the second reactor at its Braidwood nuclear power
plant near Chicago.
   The decision came five months after the commission granted the
utility a low-power license for the reactor, NRC spokesman Frank
Ingram said.
   The reactor will be brought up to full power gradually and is
expected to be fully operational by fall, generating 1.1 kilowatts
of electricity, the company said.
   The first of Braidwood's two reactors was licensed for
full-power operation on July 2, 1987, Ingram said.
   The NRC action brought to 12 the number of fully licensed
reactors Edison operates at six Illinois plants and marked the
completion of a nuclear-plant construction program it began in the
early 1970s, the utility said.
</TEXT>
