<HEAD>Authorities Report One Dead, One Hurt in Building Collapse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with identities, details on the accident
and the project, no one believed trapped. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wall of dirt collapsed at an building
renovation project today, killing one person and injuring another,
police said.
   A father-son team was working with two other men on a two-car
underground garage and elevator shaft at the four-story apartment
house, digging by hand when the accident occurred, according to
officials and witnesses.
   Marcelino Herrejon, 48, said his 20-year-old son, Pedro Herrejon
Velasquez, was killed in the accident in the city's Russian Hill
neighborhood.
   A 33-year-old man whose name was not immediately released was in
good condition at San Francisco General Hospital Mission Emergency,
said spokeswoman Ruth Rankin.
   Herrejon said he was outside the building when he heard the dirt
give way.
   ``I told them to run, but they didn't all get out,'' he said.
