<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teen-agePlot     05-20 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teen-age Plot,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Teens Who Stole Blasting Caps Planned to Blow Up
Bridges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three teen-agers arrested late last week had
planned to blow up Illinois River bridges using 2,400 stolen
blasting caps, police said Friday.
   ``The kids who stole the dynamite caps were telling other kids
about it and they made comments about their plans to blow up
bridges,'' Peoria County Sheriff's Lt. Jerry Sample said. ``I
didn't take it as a joke at the time. And they certainly didn't
tell us it was a joke during interrogation.''
   Police arrested Kenneth Johnson, Tyrone Gayton and Christopher
Caho, all 17, in the May 9 theft of 2,400 explosive blasting caps.
   The caps are owned by a mining equipment and supply company.
Some are fused caps, which are extremely sensitive to shock, and
others are electric caps that can be detonated by radio
transmissions, police said.
   The suspects were jailed on felony burglary and theft charges.
Their bond ranges from $5,000 to $10,000.
   In an interview from jail, Johnson told the Peoria Journal Star
he was joking when he told friends he might blow up a bridge.
   ``Most of the things we did were just spur-of-the-moment
ideas,'' Johnson said. He added he planned to sell the caps.
   Sample said it's unclear whether the blasting caps would have
been powerful enough to blow up the highway bridges.
   ``The experts ... said that if you take 1,000 caps and put them
together, you can make a 10-foot crater in the ground,'' Sample
said. ``Whether they would hurt a steel bridge, we don't know.''
   He said all but about 60 of the stolen caps have been recovered.
</TEXT>
