<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     05-20 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenians Demand Trials Be Opened To Observers And TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators converged on the Soviet Supreme
Court building Friday to demand that the trials of those charged in
ethnic rioting that killed 32 people be opened to television
cameras and Armenian observers.
   An Armenian activist said in a telephone interview from the
republic's capital, Yerevan, that the city was quiet after two
large public gatherings earlier in the week.
   The demonstration by about 30 Armenians across the street from
the downtown Supreme Court building indicated continuing skepticism
about the prosecution of those suspected of involvement in three
days of ethnic rioting that began Feb. 28 in the Azerbaijani city
of Sumgait.
   Twenty-six Armenians and six Azerbaijanis were killed in the
violence, which was touched off by a dispute between the two
southern Soviet republics over control of the mountainous
Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan.
   Most residents of Nagorno-Karabakh are ethnic Armenians, and
they began agitating in February to be annexed to Armenia. That
touched off large demonstrations in Yerevan in support of their
demand.
   Uniformed and plainclothes police lined the sidewalk in front of
the six-story Supreme Court, but did not interfere with the protest.
   Armenian painter Koryun Nagapityan, 60, said he would present a
declaration to the Supreme Court from unions representing Armenian
artists, writers and other creative workers calling for ``full
openness'' in criminal proceedings against more than 80 people
charged in the rioting.
   Nagapityan read the declaration demanding several Armenians be
allowed to attend the Sumgait trials as observers, that proceedings
not be left in the hands of Azerbaijan authorities, that the names
of the dead and missing in Sumgait be published, and that the
trials be carried live on state-run TV.
   Demonstrators unrolled paper signs reading, ``Recognize the fact
of Armenian genocide in Sumgait,'' ``Strictly punish the organizers
of the Sumgait slaughter,'' and ``We know the names of 50 victims
of the Sumgait slaughter.''
   On Monday, an Azerbaijani metalworker, Talekh Salekh Ogli
Ismailov, was found guilty of premeditated murder in the rioting,
and given the maximum sentence of 15 years. Ismailov was the first
person convicted for taking part in the unrest.
   But Armenian sources said about 150,000 people gathered the next
day in Yerevan to stress that conviction of people involved in the
rioting did not meet their demands for solving the region's
problems.
   They said several thousand people also gathered in Stepanakert,
the main city of Nagorno-Karabakh on Tuesday, and that the
atmosphere in Nagorno-Karabakh was tense.
   Armenian activist Rafael Popoyan said in a telephone
conversation from Yerevan on Thursday that thousands more gathered
that evening in a main city square.
   Contacted Friday, he said the Thursday gathering apparently
broke up after about four hours with nothing happening, and that
the city was quiet on Friday.
   Demonstrators in Moscow differed over the sentence given
Ismailov. One Armenian who refused to give his name said: ``15
years is not the issue. The issue is bringing those who organized
the butchery to trial.''
   But Nagapityan shouted ``Why does the person who committed such
a crime have the right to live?''
   One middle-aged Russian woman who said she was married to an
Azeri argued briefly with the demonstrators, saying she disagreed
with their version of the events in Sumgait, but she soon left.
   The Soviet government rejected the demand to change jurisdiction
over Nagorno-Karabakh, opting instead for a long, expensive program
of social and economic development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
