<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Media     05-20 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Media,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says It Won't Act Against CBS For Documentary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday backed
down from previous threats to act against the CBS television
network for a documentary about apartheid, but it warned of a
larger crackdown on the media.
   Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha told Parliament he was
considering the establishment of a government disciplinary body to
monitor the press and criticized what he called ``media
terrorists.''
   In December, Botha had said he might take unspecified actions
against the CBS News bureau in Johannesburg following the broadcast
in the United States of the documentary, ``Children of Apartheid.''
   The government had described the documentary, narrated by Walter
Cronkite, as ``blatant distortion.''
   Botha said Friday that the president of CBS News, Howard
Stringer, had issued a statement and that no action would be taken.
   The program consisted largely of interviews with young people in
South Africa, both black and white. Among those interviewed were
the daughters of President P.W. Botha and Nelson Mandela, the
jailed leader of the African National Congress.
   The government complained about the way the film was made as
well as the content. Botha said Cronkite and CBS producer Brian
Ellis had misled the government about the project and had failed to
obtain work permits.
   On Friday, Botha quoted CBS as saying that ``the circumstances
surrounding the making of the program were such as to give grounds
for objection by the South Africa government and (CBS) regretted
that it has not been meticulous in complying with South African
procedures regarding foreign media.''
   A CBS spokesman in New York said the network acknowledged that
South Africa has complex procedures and requirements that must be
followed.
   ``We're proud that the documentary was broadcast,'' said the
spokesman, Tom Goodman.
   Botha also said that the Media Council, an independent body
established by newspapers in 1983 to monitor the news industry, had
failed to act against publications that allegedly promoted
revolutionary causes.
   ``Freedom of expression in South Africa will not be allowed to
such an extent that it fosters chaos and revolt in the country,''
Botha said.
   Botha suggested that the government body would be aimed at
``media terrorists.''
   ``Media terrorists (are) people who do not have the guts to be
terrorists themselves,'' Botha said. ``I've heard it said it's an
ego trip by dropouts from other fields of endeavor.''
   South Africa already has extensive press restrictions. State of
emergency regulations in effect since June 1986 restrict reporting
on unrest, security force actions and many types of anti-government
protests.
   Two anti-apartheid newspapers have been suspended by the
government for publishing purported subversive material and several
others have been warned that they could face action.
   By South African law and custom, apartheid establishes a
racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no
vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy
and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0172 </DOCNO>
