<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-US     05-20 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-US,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Leader Says Base Negotiations Likely to Continue Into 1989</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Andreas Papandreou was quoted
Friday as saying he expects negotiations for a new agreement on
U.S. military bases in Greece to run into 1989.
   In an interview published in the satirical left-wing weekly
Pontiki, Papandreou said he did not think ``that we can easily
finish in 1988.''
   Under the present accord, the four American bases would have to
close down 17 months after it expires Dec. 31, 1988. A shutdown
notice has to be issued five months earlier.
   ``We'll denounce the agreement ... Therefore the bases won't
exist de jure (legally) after January 1989,'' Papandreou was quoted
as saying.
   Four U.S. military bases have been operating in Greece since the
early 1950s _ two near Athens and two on the southern island of
Crete.
   But Papandreou described the negotiations as ``very serious''
and said they could lead to an agreement.
   In Washington this week, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State
Rozanne Ridgway also said the United States was expecting Greece to
issue the shutdown notice.
   Greece wants a new agreement to be linked with progress on its
``national interests,'' a reference to longstanding regional
disputes with Turkey.
   U.S. officials want to avoid mixing regional politics in the
negotiations.
   Greece and Turkey are NATO allies but have differences over
Aegean airspace and seabed mineral rights as well as the military
status of some Greek islands.
   They also have disputes over the divided island of Cyprus, where
the Turkish army invaded in 1974 after a short-lived coup by Greek
Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
   Turkish Cypriots declared the northern third of the island an
independent state in 1983.
</TEXT>
