<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DemocraticChairmen     05-20 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Chairmen,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demo Chief Blasts Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic National Chairman Paul Kirk unveiled
the party line against Republican nominee-in-waiting George Bush on
Friday, calling him ``a quintessential elitist establishment
Republican country-clubber'' and a do-nothing public official.
   Kirk's broadside came during a meeting of the Association of
Democratic State Chairs, which drew party leaders from throughout
the country to review arrangements for the Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta this summer.
   Kirk said Bush ``has neither the toughness to govern nor the
compassion to care. ... It's debutante balls and `deep doo-doo'
when he speaks for himself. But when his image-makers tell him what
to do, it's `kick a little ass' and climb aboard an 18-wheeler.''
   The phrase ``deep doo-doo'' has been attributed to the vice
president, and after his debate with Democratic vice presidential
candidate Geraldine Ferraro in 1984 he said he had ``kicked ass.''
   Kirk said the challenge for Democrats this fall is to ``make
sure that when people go to the polls in November, George Bush will
have a rendezvous with his own record.''
   The Democratic chairman noted that Bush was given responsibility
for a task force to stop drugs at the U.S. borders.
   ``Isn't it fair,'' Kirk said, ``for voters to ask of the person
entrusted with that special responsibility not only why are we
losing the war against drugs, but also ... how could you not have
known about drug thug Noriega dealing drugs and laundering money
and running guns?''
   Kirk also noted that in March 1986, Bush released the report of
the anti-terrorism task force, in which he said this country would
offer no concessions to terrorists. Just one week earlier, the
White House completed the first delivery of missiles to the
Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran.
   Bush has maintained that he had reservations about the
Iran-Contra dealings and was excluded from decision-making on the
matter.
   After Kirk's address, which anticipated the general election
campaign in the fall, state party leaders were reminded by Jesse
Jackson's campaign that the contest for the Democratic nomination
isn't over yet.
   Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, a Jackson supporter, said
Democrats can win the election in November only if they are unified
after leaving the convention. And that could depend on not writing
off Jackson too soon, he said.
   ``You don't have to be a professional politician to know that
this type of thinking will allow you to win the nomination and lose
the election,'' Rangel said.
   A somewhat different view came from Robert A. Farmer, treasurer
of front-runner Michael Dukakis' campaign:
   ``History suggests that where a party has been able to identify
a candidate early, he has a stronger chance of success in the
fall,'' he said. ``And I think we don't want to appear arrogant and
we don't want to appear cocky, but we're very pleased the way
things are going. And if we can ... identify the nominee early, I
think we can all begin to work together.''
   Outside the meeting room, there was scattered talk of a vice
presidential running mate for Dukakis.
   Georgia party chairman John Henry Anderson said he'd heard home
state Sen. Sam Nunn's name mentioned frequently. As proof, he
steered reporters to Alabama party chairman John Baker.
   Baker commented, ``I personally think that the best ticket from
the Alabama standpoint is the Dukakis-Nunn ticket. I think Dukakis
stands a chance to carry Alabama, maybe with some other people
(than Nunn), but I believe that would be by far the strongest
ticket.''
   Ohio chairman Jim Ruvolo said he is pushing Ohio Sen. John
Glenn, who sought the party's presidential nomination in 1984.
   ``We think Glenn balances the ticket in terms of his strength as
someone experienced in defense issues, foreign policy issues,
someone who's viewed as a moderate,'' he said. ``And certainly his
record on important issues like civil rights is right there in the
mainstream of the party.''
</TEXT>
