<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru a0643 05-20 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0643,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Bomb U.S. Embassy, Anti-U.S. Protests Enter Fourth Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 10th graf, ``The placard ...'' to ADD
State Dept. comment. Picks up 11th graf pvs, ``National police
...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students on Friday scaled the
walls of the U.S. Embassy, tossed homemade bombs at its buildings
and shouted ``Yankee go home!'' in protests called to mark a bloody
demonstration eight years ago.
   Witnesses said two people were injured in the attack which broke
out shortly before noon. Seven attackers were arrested.
   U.S. Embassy officials said the bombs didn't damage the
buildings and no Americans were hurt.
   Witnesses said students, some of them armed with steel bars,
hurled six homemade bombs at police and over the embassy walls
topped with barbed wires.
   Four of the devices, made from crude chemical explosives packed
in soft drink cans, exploded with big bangs, sending about 100
people waiting for visa applications running for cover, witnesses
said.
   A police officer was hospitalized with blast wounds on his neck
and hands, they said. A student was also injured when he was hit by
a policeman armed with an iron bar.
   Five students carrying one South Korean and two U.S. flags
climbed over the 6-foot-high fence and ran around the embassy
compound for several minutes, scattering leaflets.
   One student draped a South Korean national flag over his
shoulder while other students tried to destroy two U.S. flags
before being overpowered by police, the witnesses said.
   The students also tried to unfurl a placard which read, ``Drive
out America, culprit of the Kwangju massacre,'' they said.
   The placard refered to an anti-government uprising in Kwangju on
May 18, 1980, during which hundreds were killed. Friday's protests
and others earlier this week were called to commemorate the
bloodshed in that southern city.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said
the embassy incident lasted only about five minutes. Redman said
five policemen and one student were injured.
   He added, ``There's no excuse for this kind of behavior. There
is a political system now in Korea that provides for the expression
of political views and participation in the political process.''
   National police remained on full alert to cope with the
demonstrations.
   Radical groups called for another march in Seoul on Saturday to
denounce the government. Opposition church groups also called for
peaceful protests.
   In other parts of Seoul and two provincial cities, hundreds of
students staged demonstrations and marches, demanding the fall of
the government of President Roh Tae-woo and the withdrawal of
41,000 U.S. troops stationed here under a mutual defense treaty.
   Many of the protests were peaceful but some turned into battles
with riot police who retaliated with tear gas. In Kwangju, 400
students clashed with police, hurling firebombs and rocks.
   Eight students were arrested in Suwon, 25 miles south of Seoul,
when they stormed an office of the governing Democratic Justice
Party with firebombs and sticks. Riot police overpowered the
attackers.
   Protesters have denounced the United States in demonstrations
this week, charging that Washington supports military dictatorship
in South Korea.
   Demonstrators broke windows and hurled firebombs Thursday at the
Seoul office of the U.S. Information Service. The center was seized
by radicals in February who exploded several bombs that caused
minor damage.
   Radical groups call for the overthrow of the Roh government
which they consider a continuation of its predecessor ``military
dictatorship'' led by former President Chun Doo-hwan.
   Roh is distrusted by many Koreans because of the role he played
in Chun's government. Roh narrowly won presidential elections in
December after two opposition candidates ran and split the
opposition ticket.
   On Friday, Roh's government and the opposition failed to break a
stalemate over clearing the way for talks between the president and
opposition leaders.
   Both sides have called for negotiations between the two camps
after last month's legislative elections in which the opposition
took control of the National Assembly.
   Officials of the rival parties have met several times during the
past week, but failed to work out details on opening the assembly.
   One major stumbling block has been Roh's plan to include the
head of his Democratic Justice Party in the summit with Kim
Dae-jung and the two other main opposition party leaders, Kim
Young-sam and Kim Jong-pil.
   The opposition leaders want only Roh to meet with the opposition
chiefs.
   Chun used to include the chairman of his ruling party in
summits, but opposition leaders, emboldened by their election
victory last month, now object to the idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
