<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--JournalistsStrike     05-20 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Journalists Strike,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Italy, No News Means There's a Journalists' Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nationwide strike by journalists left Italians
without their Friday morning and evening news broadcasts and no
weekend newspapers.
   Journalists at the two major national news agencies AGI and ANSA
joined their colleagues at RAI state television and radio offices
as well as private broadcast disputes in the dispute.
   Newspapers won't appear Saturday or Sunday.
   The strikers have announced which days they will stay off the
job this month, with newspapers scheduled to appear on Monday
before disappearing again later that week for a few days before
resuming publication.
   The ``newsless'' days are the latest in a series of protests led
by the National Press Federation to protest a breakdown in talks
for a new contract.
   Italian publishers claim their labor costs would increase 70
percent in three years and that many newspapers would have to fold
if they met the union demands. The unions dispute the figures,
saying costs would rise 40 percent.
   Unions also want a clause that would prevent newspaper chains
from using one central newsroom to provide national and
international news for the group.
</TEXT>
