<HEAD>Hooks: Blacks Could Be Decisive In '88 Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the NAACP said Friday that
if the fall presidential race is as close as he thinks it will be,
blacks could swing the election either way.
   ``Black participation could be awesome in terms of its effect on
the race,'' said Benjamin L. Hooks, executive director of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   ``Based on what I've seen, this will be a very close race and 8
percent to 10 percent can be decisive,'' said Hooks. ``The black
vote will be large and it will be predominantly Democratic.''
   Still, Hooks said, blacks must not appear ``the captive of one
party. For if that becomes the fact, then we will be ignored by the
Democratic Party and overlooked by the other party and we become of
no consequence.''
   He said Democrat Jesse Jackson now appeared to have little
chance of becoming his party's presidential nominee, but added, ``I
think he'll be running for president for the next 20 years and
maybe one of these years he'll make it.''
