<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Ethiopia-Aid     05-20 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ethiopia-Aid,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Emergency Supplies to Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Disaster Relief Organization and a U.S.
government assistance office will send 250 tons of emergency aid to
Ethiopia in case the number of displaced people increases, an U.N.
spokesman said Friday.
   The spokesman, Mohammad Khatib, said the aid, including tents,
blankets, kitchen utensils and building materials, would be sent to
Asmara on Wednesday.
   The U.N. organization is contributing 100 tons and the Office of
U.S. Foreign Disaster Assistance, part of the U.S. Agency for
International Development, is sending 150 tons, he said, adding
that the two agencies are cooperating to save costs.
   The equipment is being sent as a precautionary measure, to be
used if there is a mass displacement of people in northern Ethiopia
because of the food shortage there, Khatib said. The supplies could
help 150,000 people.
   Khatib said there are about 40,000 displaced people in the
north, but that they continue to move from place to place.
   He said officials wanted to avoid a repeat of the 1984-85
drought and famine, when many people left their villages and camped
out near food distribution centers.
</TEXT>
