<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2151EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teacher-Retire     05-20 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher-Retire,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honored, Popular Gifted Teacher Told She Must Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman honored recently as the Bay Area
Gifted Teacher of the Year has been told by school officials she
must retire next month so the district can save money.
   ``I feel they are dishonoring the teacher of the year,'' said
Flossie Lewis, 63, a teacher for 37 years. ``I understand the
bureaucratic mentality. But what are we in education for? To treat
people like robots?''
   The San Francisco Unified School District has said Lewis must
retire, although a state law would allow her to continue with the
district's permission.
   Rod Hong, district personnel director, said the system has about
550 teachers over age 59 earning top pay. The system is seeking
their retirements to cut costs.
   Hong also noted that Lewis' five years are up on a statewide
reduced workload program that allows her to work half a year and
receive half her $40,000 salary, yet still get full retirement
benefits.
   Previous state law required teachers to retire after five years
in the program, but last year the law was changed to permit school
districts to extend the program to 10 years.
   Chris Karlen, executive director of the San Francisco Classroom
Teachers Association, said he asked officials to permit the
extension for Lewis, but they refused. However, schools
Superintendent Ramon Cortines indicated Wednesday the district
would be willing to negotiate.
   While most teachers use the reduced workload program as a way to
ease into retirement, Lewis, a published author of fiction, essays
and literary criticism, has started working on a doctorate in
English at the University of California at Berkeley.
   Hong said Friday he doesn't have a figure on how much money the
district would save if all the teachers eligible to resign or
participate in reduced workload program _ like Lewis _ did so. He
did say at least 25 teachers are in the reduced workload plan.
   Still, Hong said he will not make an exception for Lewis.
   ``It's not that we're trying to be mean or cruel to her,'' he
said. ``She's just one teacher. We have to treat all district
employees equally. She wants her cake, and she wants to be able to
eat it, too.''
</TEXT>
