<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hamadi     05-20 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Of Suspected TWA Hijacker To Start On July 5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Lebanese Shiite Moslem charged
with murder and air piracy in the 1985 TWA hijacking is expected to
go to trial in juvenile court in July, a court spokesman said
Friday.
   The Frankfurt trial of Mohammed Ali Hamadi is expected to begin
July 5 and continue at least two months, said spokesman Falk Thomas.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport on Jan. 13, 1987,
carrying liquid explosives and false documents. He was charged Feb.
8.
   The air piracy and murder charges are in connection with the
June 14, 1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner to Beirut, Lebanon, in
which U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed. The hijackers held
39 Americans captive for 17 days.
   Hamadi was indicted in the United States on air piracy and
murder charges but West Germany refused to extradite him.
   Hamadi will be tried before a juvenile chamber of the Frankfurt
state court, although he could be treated as an adult and receive
the maximum sentence of life imprisonment if convicted.
   The court will first try to determine if Hamadi was under 21
years old during the hijacking. He first told investigators he was
born June 13, 1964, but later said he was two years younger.
   Under West German law, juvenile courts can handle cases of
defendents under 21.
   A juvenile court can impose a life sentence on an adolescent
despite the age.
   Hamadi's brother, Abbas, was found guilty by a Duesseldorf court
last month of organizing the kidnapping of two West Germans in
Lebanon to force the West German government to release his brother.
Abbas Hamadi was sentenced to 13 years in prison.
   The two West Germans were abducted within a week of Mohammed
Hamadi's arrest. Alfred Schmidt was released in September. Rudolf
Cordes remains a hostage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
