<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cajuns-Soviets     05-20 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cajuns-Soviets,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cajun Chef, Artist Will Display Their Work In Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is about to get a taste
of Cajun-style diplomacy as chef John Folse carries his fiery
recipes abroad and artist George Rodrigue introduces a new audience
to his haunting portraits of Acadiana.
   The two left New Orleans on Friday for a 10-day trip to the
U.S.S.R. that will overlap summit talks between President Reagan
and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
   Seeds for the trip were planted in August, according to
Rodrigue, when a Soviet delegation of scientists and public
officials visited Folse's restaurant, Lafitte's Landing, in
Donaldsonville.
   It was, Rodrigue said, the delegation's first glimpse of rural
culture in America.
   ``This was not part of their typical American concept. We were
the people living off the land,'' the artist said in a telephone
interview as he prepared for his departure.
   The Soviets met Folse and sampled his food. ``I doubt the
Soviets ever ate a better meal,'' Folse said later.
   The Soviets also met Rodrigue and saw his art. ``I told them I
paint the people of the land,'' he said.
   Rodrigue's portraits of Acadians, often posed against the
backdrop of moss-draped oak trees on bayou shores, captured the
imagination of the Soviets.
   Soviet officials commissioned a Gorbachev portrait and Rodrigue
painted him in a yellow suit ``because yellow is a color of
peace.'' Gorbachev is depicted in front of the Kremlin, with a
bright sun shining and smaller figures of himself as a child,
standing with his parents, in the background.
   The Gorbachev portrait, and one of Reagan, will make the trip to
the Soviet Union, along with about 20 Rodrigue paintings depicting
Cajun life.
   ``I tried to pick things that were kind of universal, one is a
horse race, one is a story of a church in the aftermath of a
hurricane, one is of a dog, my dog ... one is my little boy with
the saying `Kiss me, I'm Cajun' on his T-shirt,'' said the artist.
   Rodrigue credits Folse with arranging the trip. Folse got help
from the Louisiana congressional delegation. Earlier this week, he
said he had raised more than half the $130,000 he needed to cover
the costs of food and expenses.
   He said, he won't keep any of the money, however.
   ``The Soviets will keep every nickel of revenue,'' he said. ``I
hope Reagan makes a better deal than I did.''
   Rodrigue said he hopes both world leaders will visit the
temporary Cajun restaurant, Lafitte's Landing East, where he and
Folse will display their artistry.
   ``We're pretty sure about Gorbachev (paying a visit to the
restaurant),'' Rodrigue said. ``The president, we don't know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0186 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ScienceOlympiad     05-20 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Science Olympiad,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Scientists Arrive for National Competition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's future Galileos and Einsteins
arrived Friday for the National Science Olympiad, testing
brainpower and ingenuity in events from egg dropping to rocket
firing.
   Delaware State College is playing host to nearly 1,300 junior
and senior high school students, representing 36 states, for the
competition Saturday. Winners receive scholarships, trophies,
medals and other awards.
   The competition, sponsored by the Army Reserve Officer Training
Corps, consists of 22 events for junior high students and 23 for
high school.
   The students have already competed at the local, state and
regional levels, said John C. Cairns, event coordinator and science
supervisor for the Delaware Department of Public Instruction.
   The competition involves chemistry and physics, and tests
student' laboratory skills and the application of scientific
principles.
   Among the events will be an egg drop, which will require
students to make a device to safely catch a raw egg dropped from a
given height. The smallest device that can keep the egg from
breaking will win the event. The purpose is to test students'
knowledge of physics and the strength of materials.
   The U.S. Forestry Service has flown in about 40 seedlings from
across the country for the tree identification competition.
   This is the fourth national contest, which is modeled on
competition begun in Delaware 12 years ago.
   The event became a nationwide competition after Cairns helped
the Macomb County Intermediate School District in Michigan put
together its own contest.
   Cairns and Gerard J. Putz, science consultant for the Michigan
district, were discussing a competition between the two states
during a science conference in Boston.
   ``We were talking about it in front of an Army recruiting booth
... and the Army guy said the Army was looking for something
hi-tech to associate its name with. It went national the following
year,'' Cairns said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
