<DOCNO> AP880520-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1648EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-StarWarsReport     05-20 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Star Wars Report,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Advisory Panel Calls for Slower Star Wars Deployment Schedule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon should take a slower, more
measured approach to the deployment of a Star Wars anti-missile
defense system, a scientific advisory panel said in a report
released Friday.
   The panel, a special task force of the Defense Science Board,
said the administration's plan of setting up even an interim
``Phase 1'' system all at once is too ambitious.
   ``In view of the technical, budgetary, political and arms
control uncertainties surrounding the ballistic missile defense
program, the panel recommends planning a number of steps in the
technical development and deployment of a system ... rather than a
single major action,'' the report said.
   The task force suggested the Defense Department start by
deploying 100 ground-based interceptor rockets as allowed under the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, either outside Washington,
D.C., or at Grand Forks Air Force Base, N.D.
   The next step, it said, should be deployment of a new generation
of ``space surveillance systems to improve our early warning
detection and assessment of a ballistic missile attack ....''
   That could be followed by deployment of new, short-range
interceptor missiles around Washington, with the next phase
consisting of ``additional bases and ground-based interceptors and
improved sensors to cope with counter-measures.''
   Only then would a move be made to deploy defensive weapons in
space, the panel said, with the final step being the addition of
ground- or space-based lasers.
   ``This approach would allow for more confident decisions and
more flexibility in the face of uncertainties and would probably
not require any more time in the long run,'' the task force
contended.
   The science board task force was asked to take a fresh look at
the Star Wars program early this year by Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci. Its report was dated April 13 but was not cleared for
unclassified release until Friday.
   The Pentagon, in finally releasing the study, stressed the
findings were ``solely those of the authors and the submission of
the report to the secretary in no way signals a change in U.S.
policy with respect to the (Star Wars) program.''
   The Star Wars program, known formally as the Strategic Defense
Initiative, is an effort to develop lasers and other exotic weapons
that could be deployed either in space or on the ground to
automatically shoot down enemy nuclear missiles.
   Last September, then-Defense Secretary Caspar W. Weinberger
selected five Star Wars technologies for concentrated research,
saying they would form the heart of an initial Phase 1 system.
Among the five were some space-based as well as ground-based rocket
systems.
   Ever since then, the Pentagon has suggested the research results
involving all five technologies would be evaluated sometime in the
early 1990s and a decision made on constructing an initial system.
   ``We believe that the difficulty of supporting such a large
decision all at once and of bringing all system elements to a
satisfactory stage at the same time make the all-at-once plan very
risky,'' the task force said.
   ``The stepped plan allows much more confident decisions and much
more flexibility in the face of uncertainties.''
   The Pentagon also should consider giving the highest priority to
development ``of the sensors, processing and communications
necessary'' to detect a nuclear attack and track and target
incoming missiles, it said.
   Moreover, it said, the Defense Department and Congress must
resolve their dispute over what research the ABM Treaty allows.
``There is not a force acting on the SDI program that is more
damaging or more insidious ...,'' the 11-member group wrote.
   ``Because the Soviets exploit ambiguities to the limit, a U.S.
policy that restricts us to activities that are unambiguously
permitted by the treaty could seriously impair our security,'' the
panel said.
   ``We believe the Defense Department should define a technically
optimum testing and deployment program and should then adhere to
that program except when treaty constraints unambiguously require
it to do otherwise.''
   The assessment requested by Carlucci comes at a time when the
defense secretary has been studying changes to the Star Wars
research schedule caused by congressional budget cuts.
   Carlucci said earlier this month he would recommend a budget
veto if the Star Wars request of $4.55 billion in fiscal 1989 was
cut too deeply.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
