<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-20 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Accuse Pakistan of Violating Geneva Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry on Friday accused Pakistan of
shipping arms and military hardware to Afghan rebels and violating
the agreement under which Soviet soldiers are leaving Afghanistan.
   The official news agency Tass quoted ministry officials as
saying Pakistan was not living up to the April 14 Geneva agreement
that prohibits it from assisting Afghan anti-government forces.
   In a separate commentary, Tass criticized Pakistani Foreign
Minister Zain Noorani for allegedly inciting the rebels to military
action.
   According to Soviet media reports, the Afghan Foreign Ministry
has complained twice this week to U.N. observers that Pakistan is
helping arm the Afghan rebels.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry officials said ``the shipping of arms
and ammunition from Pakistan into the territory of the Republic of
Afghanistan is an obvious violation of the Geneva agreements which
entered into force on May 5,'' Tass reported.
   Terms of the Geneva agreement mean Pakistan ``should discontinue
the entire range of actions and activities to interfere in the
affairs of Afghanistan,'' it said.
   Pakistan has officially denied helping ship arms to the
guerrillas but Noorani said Thursday that his country will observe
the policy of ``symmetry,'' in which the guerrillas receive U.S.
aid as long as the Soviet Union arms the Marxist government.
   Soviet soldiers began withdrawing May 15 and the first convoy to
leave Afghanistan crossed the border Wednesday. According to the
agreement, all of the estimated 115,000 Soviet soldiers must be
withdrawn within nine months.
   A Soviet journalist indicated Thursday that between 12,000 and
15,000 Soviet soldiers had been killed in fighting since Soviet
troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979.
   In its commentary, Tass said Noorani promised Soviet officials
on a recent trip to Moscow that his country would abide by the
Geneva agreement, but said on his return home Thursday that
Pakistan will continue to help the United States aid the rebels.
   commentator Valery Vavilov said.
   The Afghan peace process requires strict observance of all its
terms, and ``any deviations, and `free' and `broad' interpretations
of separate articles and clauses of the accords are intolerable,''
said commentator Valery Vavilov said.
   He quoted Western press reports as saying unprecedented arms
shipments were en route to the border of Pakistan and Afghanistan,
where the Afghan insurgents have their bases.
</TEXT>
