<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CoxObit     05-20 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cox Obit,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Newsman Dies of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   G. William Cox, who resigned as managing editor
of the Honolulu Star-Bulletin in 1986 after revealing he was
suffering from AIDS, died Friday at his home in Manhattan Beach,
Calif. He was 39.
   Cox resigned from the Star-Bulletin on Sept. 2, 1986, saying he
was unable to continue working because he was suffering from
Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome.
   ``As a journalist, I have spent my career trying to shed light
in dark corners,'' he wrote in revealing his illness in an
editorial page article on the day of his resignation. ``AIDS is
surely one of our darkest corners. It can use some light.
   ``By writing about AIDS, I am following a tradition of
journalists who have written about their illnesses to help educate
and, if blessed by finding the right words, to help others with the
disease feel less alone,'' he wrote.
   ``Most of all, I am writing to say if we don't want to be
treated as a pariah, we have to stop acting like one,'' he said.
   During his tenure at the Star-Bulletin, Cox fought for
reporters' access to government records and meetings so they could
keep the public informed.
   He served as president of the Hawaii chapter of Sigma Delta Chi,
the Society of Professional Journalists, and as chairman of its
Freedom of Information Committee.
   Cox joined the Star-Bulletin in January 1984 after serving five
years as city editor of The Courier-Journal in Louisvlle, Ky. He
was a 1971 graduate of the University of Missouri School of
Journalism.
   He is survived by his parents, Homer and Ann Cox of Louisville.
   Services will be held in Louisville.
</TEXT>
