<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     05-20 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peres Says Peace Process Alive, But Differences With Soviets
Persist</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Roles, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI C. RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres said
Friday the Soviet Union has agreed to join an international peace
conference on the Middle East and reiterated his belief that peace
would come to Israel.
   However, Peres, who returned home from a 13-day trip, said many
problems remained with the Soviet Union.
   Also Friday, Israel radio reported that President Chaim Herzog
commuted the sentences of three Jewish underground members from
life in prison to 15 years for staging a deadly gun and grenade
attack at Hebron Islamic College in 1983.
   Three Palestinians were killed and 33 were wounded in the attack.
   The three convicted men _ Menachem Livni, Shaul Nir and Uzi
Sharbaf _ were among 25 Jews arrested in 1984 and charged with
planning or carrying out attacks against Arab targets.
   In other developments:
   _Israeli troops shot and wounded a 15-year-old Palestinian
during a demonstration in Jabaliya refugee camp, officials at Shifa
hospital in Gaza City said. The youth was shot in the hand after
protesters threw stones at Israeli troops.
   _The army command said a border policemen was slightly injured
by a knife-wielding Palestinian woman in Nablus in the West Bank.
   _The army confirmed that 1,770 Palestinians are being held in
administrative detention but the chief military attorney, Brig.
Gen. Amnon Shtresnov, denied the arrests without trial were a
violation of human rights.
   During his trip, Peres visited Hungary; Spain, where he attended
the Socialist International, and the United States.
   He met with key Soviet officials in Madrid and Washington,
including Moscow's ambassador to the United States, Anatoly Dubinin.
   In an interview at Ben Gurion International Airport, Peres told
The Associated Press the Soviets agreed to an international peace
conference which would not have the power to impose an agreement on
the parties.
   However, he said, ``the argument with the Soviet Union has not
reached a conclusion.''
   One major disagreement concerns Moscow's insistence on the right
of the Palestinians to self-determination. Both Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir and Peres reject establishment of an independent
Palestinian state in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Peres told a group of supporters at the airport that Israel
would always insist on three points: defensible borders; refusal to
talk to the PLO and refusal to give up all of the territories
occupied in the 1967 Middle East war.
   He said that during his travels, he tried to improve Israel's
image abroad.
   ``Our situation is very difficult, especially with the Socialist
International and the European Economic Community,'' Peres said.
``I tried to present a balanced picture of Israel in front of the
world.''
   An Arab uprising broke out in the occupied territories on Dec.
8, and Israel's strong measures to quash the insurrection drew
world criticism.
   Shtresnov said on Israel television in reporting on the
detainment of Palestinians that the army closely examined each
suspect before making the arrest and gave detainees the right to
appeal. He said the detentions ``are in accordance with Israeli and
international law.''
   He denied charges that the military justice system had collapsed
under the weight of the mass arrests which took place after the
uprising began.
   Shtresnov conceded that there were problems initially in
locating and identifying detainees, but said these were quickly
solved and that computers were now being used to keep track of
jailed Palestinians.
   Lea Zemel, an Israeli lawyer who represents Palestinian
prisoners, described the situation as ``a big mess.''
   According to estimates by left-wing legislator Deddi Zucker,
8,100 Palestinans are in jail after trial or pending trial, in
addition to 1,900 other detainees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
