<1ST_LINE>r i AM-People-GarciaMarquez     05-20 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Garcia Marquez,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Garcia Marquez Recovers From Car Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Gabriel Garcia Marquez
bruised four ribs in a car accident, but the Colombian-born writer
is recovering nicely in a Caracas clinic, the newspaper El Diario
de Caracas reported Thursday.
   ``By a hair I didn't stay forever in Venezuela _ can you
imagine?'' Garcia Marquez joked in an interview, the newspaper said.
   The writer, winner of the 1982 Nobel Prize for Literature, was
injured Saturday in a collision between a bus and the car in which
he was riding. He was being driven to Maiquetia International
Airport outside Caracas, where he expected to take a plane to Cuba.
   Initial press reports said Garcia bruised one rib.
   Garcia was in Venezuela to research the life of South American
liberator Simon Bolivar (1783-1830) for a novel, tentatively titled
``The General in His Labyrinth.''
   His latest novel, ``Love in the Time of Cholera,'' was recently
released in an English translation.
</TEXT>
