<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Noriega     05-20 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Noriega,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>US and Panamanian Negotiators Agree on a Noriega Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Panamanian negotiators have
tentatively agreed on a deal that calls for Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega to leave Panama next August and stay away until May 1989
and gives him a role in setting up a transition government
beforehand, an administration official said Friday.
   In return for Noriega's departure, the United States would agree
to drop federal drug smuggling indictments against him, said the
official, who has followed the negotiations but insisted on
anonymity.
   The agreement, subject to final approval by both governments,
allows Noriega to return to Panama for holidays and to go back
permanently after presidential elections set for May 1989, said the
official, who described himself as opposed to the arrangement.
   He said Vice President George Bush has expressed reservations.
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, said Friday that the vice
president Bush opposes negotiating with Noriega over the conditions
under which Noriega might surrender power.
   ``The administration sources who have suggested that the vice
president favors ending the negotiations and bringing the envoy
back to Washington are essentially correct,'' Fuller said.
   Bush had lunch with President Reagan Friday, but the vice
president's aides would not say whether they discussed the Noriega
negotiations.
   The official who discussed the tentative deal also said Bush has
recommended that the State Department recall deputy assistant
secretary Michael G. Kozak from Panama. Kozak has spent virtually
all of May in Panama trying to work out an agreement.
   The official who disclosed the tentative agreement to an
Associated Press reporter said, ``If it gets accepted, it gives
Noriega everything he wants.''
   The official said there were no assurances that Noriega was
negotiating seriously and he raised the possibility that the
defense chief has no intention of resigning his post, as the
agreement specifies.
   If the deal receives final approval, the official said Noriega
would be in a position to leave his associates in positions of
authority because he will be able to influence the formation of the
transition government.
   Late Friday, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
Kozak was returning to Washington for consulations.
   He said Kozak's return does not mean any change in the process.
   ``The process continues,'' Redman said, declining further
comment.
   Associates of Noriega have said in recent weeks that Noriega
sees Aug. 12 as an appropriate time to resign because that is the
fifth anniversary of his accession as commander of the Defense
Forces.
</TEXT>
