<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpoletoUSA     05-20 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spoleto USA,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Artsfest Opens 17-Day Run With Samba, Brass Fanfare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The staccato beat of a samba band
sounded in front of City Hall on Friday as this old Southern port
unveiled the 12th edition of its Spoleto Festival U.S.A. arts
showcase.
   About 1,000 people looked on as schoolchildren sent dozens of
colored balloons lofting into a pale blue sky.
   Then the musicians, in white slacks and metallic silver shirts,
played a variety of drums and tambourines as they spun and danced
on a platform stage.
   An hour later, the strains of a chamber music concert sounded at
the nearby Dock Street Theater, the first of dozens of performances
indoors and out throughout Charleston over 17 days.
   The festival was founded by composer Gian Carlo Menotti and is
named after the similar festival he founded in Spoleto, Italy.
   Friday's opening ceremonies also kicked off four days of events
celebrating the bicentennial of South Carolina's ratification of
the Constitution.
   Charles Way Jr., the chairman of the Spoleto board, noted people
sometimes take the Constitution for granted and, in the same way,
he would like to see the day when folks take the festival for
granted.
   ``Right now, after 12 years, we are still a very fragile
organization. We're still a fragile dream that becomes a reality
for 17 marvelous days,'' he said.
   Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. called the festival
Charleston's ``great contribution to the nation and the world,''
adding ``we make this gift proudly and happily.''
   But he said the festival ``is not given to this city. It is
earned. And each year we must strive to earn it anew.''
   During the course of the festival there will be 700 performances
by 2,000 performers, including productions staged in Piccolo
Spoleto, the city's companion arts festival, Riley said.
   Alex Sanders Jr., the chief judge of the South Carolina Court of
Appeals, spoke briefly about the Constitution, saying that when the
American experiment is measured against the ideals of its framers,
it may have fallen short.
   ``But when you measure the United States against the other
nations of the world, one cannot but be amazed at how well it has
worked,'' he said.
   The samba band was part of the cast of ``The Warrior Ant,'' a
work by director Lee Bruer and composer Bob Telson which features
over 50 dancers, musicians and actors and which will have its
premiere during Spoleto.
   The festival's major opera, Dvorak's ``Rusalka,'' which is
seldom performed in this country, was to open Friday evening.
   Menotti said later he feels the Spoleto production, splashed
with special effects, will be well received.
   ``It is beautiful work, very melodic ... the story has magic,''
he said. ``It is done very simply like a Japanese play. I think
people will come from all over the country to see our production.''
   Festival General Manager Nigel Redden said that over $1 million
in tickets had been sold by the opening of the festival. The
festival has a $3.7 million budget and about half that total is
generated through earned income, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
