<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cuban-Fast     05-20 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban-Fast,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge's Ruling Allows Force-Feeding Of Hunger Striker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLADEGA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Cuban prisoner who lost 21{ pounds
while fasting for three weeks to protest his possible deportation
is being force-fed, officials said.
   Esteban Manzo-Mart ``offered no resistance,'' said Brian Ross, a
spokesman for the Talladega federal correctional institution.
``He's being fed liquids intravenously.''
   The feeding began Thursday following an order that day by U.S.
District Judge James H. Hancock at Birmingham.
   Hancock acted after the chief of health programs at the
hospital, Dr. Roger Stanmore, said Manzo-Mart was ``increasingly
dehydrated, and was experiencing progressive decline in his blood
pressure.'' The doctor said the prisoner showed ``every sign of
approaching a life-threatening situation.''
   Manzo-Mart was one of 14 Cubans served with deportation papers
at Talladega April 29. He began the hunger strike two days earlier
and was joined by another Cuban prisoner, although the second man
later halted his fast.
   Manzo-Mart has appealed his deportation.
   Ten other Cubans have been served with deportation papers since
Manzo-Mart and the others were notified last month.
   Ross said there are 77 Cuban detainees at Talladega, all of whom
were in prisons in Atlanta and Oakdale, La., when rioting over
deportation orders began last November.
</TEXT>
