<HEAD>LaserPhotos, CX9-12, LaserGraphic NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINNETKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman carrying at least two handguns
opened fire in an elementary school Friday, killing one child and
critically wounding five others. She then fled to a nearby home and
shot a seventh person, police said.
   ``There was blood all over the classroom and desks knocked
over'' as the children panicked and attempted to flee or hid under
desks, said Glencoe Patrolman John Ceglieski.
   Police believe the woman had set fire earlier in the day to
another home eight blocks away where she worked as a housekeeper in
this affluent North Shore suburb of Chicago, according to Sgt.
Michael Geier of the Wilmette police. He was assisting in the arson
investigation.
   Joe Sumner, director of operations for Winnetka police,
identified the woman as Lori Dann, 30. The FBI said it had ``an
investigative interest'' in her and Madison, Wis., Police Lt.
William Sprague said she had been arrested there March 14 on a
charge of retail theft. He gave no further details.
   More than five hours after the initial shooting, the woman
remained barricaded inside the home along a tree-lined
neighborhood. Heavily armed police encircled the dwelling and a
hostage-negotiating team was on the scene, but had not established
contact with the woman.
   ``It's extremely scary. She's just an ordinary citizen and she
went through and set all this up. She isn't exactly stable,'' said
Northbrook Police Commander Randy Walters, who was assisting local
police at the barricade site.
   ``The idea is to go in and take custody, not to kill her,'' he
said. ``If you go storming in, there's going to be a gunfight and
somebody might get shot _either her or one of our officers.''
   Winnetka Police Chief Herbert Timm said the woman walked into
the one-story, red-brick Hubbard Woods Elementary School, shot one
boy in a bathroom, then entered a second-grade class, ``went past
the teacher who was there, indicated the gun was real and began
firing at random.''
   Police recovered a .32-caliber handgun from the school bathroom
and the woman was believed to also have carried a .22-caliber gun
and a third, unidentified weapon, according to Sumner.
   Sumner said the woman then ran through the woods from the school
and entered the home, where four members of a family and their maid
were present.
   ``Apparently, she just walked in and confronted the
homeowners,'' Sumner said. ``The mother came running out and said,
`There's a woman in my home with a gun.'
   ``Then we heard a shot. The son came out, holding a gun, and
fell over in the driveway,'' Sumner said.
   The son apparently struggled with the suspect, grabbed one of
her weapons, and was shot in the chest, Sumner said.
   The father, maid and grandfather fled by side door, leaving the
suspect alone inside, Sumner said.
   He said he believed the woman had three weapons and police had
recovered two of them.
   Geier said the suspect was believed to have set fire to the home
where she worked while a mother and her children were in the
basement doing laundry.
   ``This woman set a fire in the house, trapping the people in the
basement,'' he said. ``They escaped, got out, apparently without
serious injury.''
   The shooting erupted at about 10:45 a.m. CST and police said it
lasted 15 minutes.
   An 8-year-old boy died at Highland Park Hospital, said
spokeswoman Sue Masaracchia.
   Another 8-year-old boy and the 22-year-old man shot at his home
were in critical condition at the hospital, she said.
   The four children at Evanston Hospital were reported in critical
but stable condition with gunshot wounds following surgery, said
spokeswoman Mary Ash.
   They were identified as Mark Teborek, 8, who suffered a gunshot
wound to the neck; Lindsay Clark-Fisher, 8, wounded in the chest
and stomach; Kathryn Ann Miller, wounded in the wrist and chest;
and Robert Trossman, 6, wounded in the chest.
   At the school, meanwhile, parents clustered in groups, consoling
each other and attempting to make sense of the incident.
   ``I ran here all the way from downtown (Winnetka),'' said
Benjamin Randall, waiting outside the school later Thursday for his
son to be released.
   ``I guess we're all vulnerable,'' he added. ``It' a sad
commentary on society.''
   Village Manager Robert Buechner said children were released in
small groups throughout the afternoon to ensure their safety.
   ``We're trying to keep the children calm and safely inside. We
will release them, but not until it's entirely safe to do so,''
said Buechner.
</TEXT>
