<2ND_LINE>AM-911 Arrest,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Reverses Itself, Removes Beaten Boy From Father's Custody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old boy allegedly beaten by his father
while an emergency dispatcher listened was taken into protective
custody by child welfare officials who earlier decided to let him
stay with his family.
   Police on Thursday criticized the Harris County Children's
Protective Services' decision to let the boy go home despite a
tape-recording rescue officials had of the alleged attack.
   Hours later, the boy was taken into protective custody.
   An emergency dispatcher received a telephone call May 12 from
the boy, who thought his father was having a heart attack. But the
dispatcher soon heard the boy crying out and being beaten, police
said.
   Calls to the 911 emergency line routinely are recorded.
   The boy's father, John Thomas Whiddon, 40, has been charged with
felony injury to a child and is free on bond. The boy was not
seriously injured.
   After authorities went to the home where the call was made, the
boy was taken away. But hours later, he was returned to his family,
Children's Protective Services' officials said.
   The boy's initial return to his father came after a worker
determined he would not be in a ``life-threatening situation,''
spokeswoman Judy Hay said. The worker did not listen to the
recording before making the decision, she said.
