<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Astrologer-PhoneTaps     05-20 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Astrologer-Phone Taps,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Dismisses Report Soviets Tap Mrs. Reagan's Astrology
Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House dismissed as ``foolish'' a
report Friday that the administration is trying to determine
whether telephone calls between first lady Nancy Reagan and her San
Francisco astrologer had been intercepted by Soviet spies.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said, ``If the Soviets
wanted to monitor White House phone calls to get information on the
president, there are thousands of calls a day from White House
staff of more significance (than Mrs. Reagan's).
   ``The most definitive information they're likely to get (from
Mrs. Reagan's calls) is how many pizzas are ordered by the first
family,'' he joked. He said the column ``seems foolish to me.''
   On a more serious note, he said Mrs. Reagan does not have or use
a secure telephone, designed to prevent conversations from being
overheard.
   Elaine Crispen, the first lady's press secretary, said Mrs.
Reagan routinely places her calls through the White House
switchboard.
   In addition, Mrs. Crispen said Mrs. Reagan has paid the
astrologer an undisclosed amount of money out of her own pocket.
   Fitzwater's comments came in response to a column by Jack
Anderson and Dale Van Atta that said a White House official had
been asked to quietly find out whether Mrs. Reagan had a secure
line to astrologer Joan Quigley.
   The Soviet consulate in San Francisco can listen in on
long-distance microwave-transmitted telephone calls coming into
that city, the column said.
   The Soviets would, however, have to recognize and select the
calls from an immense volume of telephone traffic.
   Unnamed sources in the White House, CIA and National Security
Council said they have been asked to conduct the investigation
without telling President Reagan for fear of offending him,
according to the column.
</TEXT>
