<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1741EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua     05-20 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Talks Falter Between Sandinistas And Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-backed Contra rebels have still
not responded to a government proposal to extend the civil war
cease-fire past the May 30 deadline, Deputy Foreign Minister Victor
Hugo Tinico said Friday.
   ``They still haven't answered a government proposal to call off
for another month offensive operations,'' he said at a breakfast
meeting with foreign correspondents.
   The leftist government and the U.S.-supplied rebels known as
Contras have been exchanging charges on who's responsible for the
faltering peace plan to end more than six years of war.
   Almost two months after the two sides signed the pact, they
agree only on the desire to end the fighting. The government has
warned it will stage the largest offensive to date if the
cease-fire is not extended after May 30 or if no progress is made.
   The Contras, meanwhile, are suffering from infighting, a move
that favors the ruling Sandinistas. From the government's point of
view, the best way for the war to end would be for the enemy to
self-destruct.
   Pro-Sandinista newspapers were giving widespread coverage to the
Contra bickering. At the same time, the government last weekend
cautioned private radio station directors against broadcasting news
that violates the public order law and warned of permanent
suspension.
   Radio station directors called the warning a ``direct threat''
and described it as self-censorship that replaces the harsh media
restrictions withdrawn by the government to comply with last
August's regional peace plan.
   The problems surrounding the cease-fire plan appear to have
started almost immediately after the March 23 signing. All of the
meetings held since then have been marked by mutual distrust.
   The government announced on Wednesday a tentative agreement for
a new round of peace talks to be held May 25-28, but the Contras
immediately disagreed.
   The years of civil war have left deep scars in this nation of 3
million. Families are divided; sons have gone off to fight with one
side or the other.
   If all had gone according to plan, the war would just about be
over and Nicaragua would be well on its way to full democracy.
   A state security officer argued recently that Nicaragua already
was a democracy. His comments came minutes after police hauled off
several opposition political leaders who spoke to journalists near
a building where workers staged a hunger strike.
   Because the cease-fire plan has not moved forward, the
Sandinistas have not freed more than 3,000 political prisoners nor
permitted the Contras to have a say in internal politics.
   Talks with the internal opposition political parties stand at an
impasse. The meetings were suspended by the opposition as a show of
support for the strikers. The government responded by saying it
would consider whether future talks would be held.
   According to the cease-fire plan, the first measures should have
been completed by April 15. In exchange, the Contra rebels would
have gathered in agreed upon cease-fire zones and been permitted to
receive humanitarian aid through a neutral organization.
   The Sandinistas have said the insurgents could now receive food,
medicine and clothes distributed by the International Red Cross.
But the Contras rejected that, saying the organization sympathizes
with the government.
   ``The tactics used at the last meeting were almost to torpedo
the agreement,'' Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros said in a recent
interview. ``They put into question everything we had agreed upon.''
   Meanwhile, thousands of rebel troops, according to sources,
moved toward the northern border. The U.S. Agency for International
Development is providing supplies to the Contras through Honduras.
   A group of rebellious Contras has demanded the ouster of the top
Contra military officer, Col. Enrique Bermudez, a former officer
under the ousted dictator Anastasio Somoza.
   Matamoros, the Contra's main spokesman, said recently the talk
of divisions was exaggerated.
   Nicaraguan Vice President Sergio Ramirez said Sunday that the
Contra infighting puts into doubt future cease-fire negotiations.
   ``In Honduras the mercenary forces (the Contras) are on the
verge of civil war,'' he said. ``The political heads that come here
to negotiate have very little influence.''
   The people, meanwhile, are war weary. The Sandinistas continue
to draft youths into the military. The economy is in shambles. And
farmers who fled the war zones in the northern mountains cannot yet
go home to plant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
