<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WorkerDisplacement     05-20 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Worker Displacement,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate GOP Group Says Displaced Workers Getting Inadequate
Assistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's displaced workers are not
receiving adequate job search assistance, training, counseling or
benefits, a study group for Senate Republicans reported Friday.
   The report by a task force of the Senate Republican Conference
said that of the more than 1 million American workers displaced
annually due to plant closings or layoffs, more than one-third of
them have extended periods of unemployment while some never return
to the workforce.
   Of those who do return, almost one-half take pay cuts and more
than one-third earn less than four-fifths of what they previously
had earned, according to the study group which was chaired by John
H. Chafee, R-I.
   The group recommended that Congress enact a $980 million Reagan
administration proposal which would consolidate two current
education and job training programs _ the Job Training Partnership
Act and the Trade Adjustment Assistance Act.
   The new worker adjustment program is designed to serve an
estimated 700,000 workers and would seek to eliminate costly
duplication of effort. It would also provide substantially greater
emphasis on actual retraining.
   The 69-page report said that poor publicity, a general lack of
coordination among different federal assistance programs and a
``slow response rate'' when the programs have actually have been
implemented ``have plagued the delivery and quality of assistance''
to displaced workers.
   Projections for the next 15 years, it said, indicate that
millions of Americans are not only ill-prepared for existing jobs
but will have even more difficulty finding and holding jobs in the
future ``unless the work force is retrained and continuously
prepared for marketplace change.''
   The United States ``is faced with the creation of a growing
underclass, increasingly made up of former manufacturing and
industrial workers without the skills to enter (the work place),''
the report said.
   The GOP conference is an organization made of all 46 Republican
senators.
   In addition to Chafee, Sens. Dave Durenburger of Minnesota,
Orrin Hatch and Robert Stafford of Vermont were members of the task
force which held three field hearings of March and April of last
year and conducted interviews with dislocated workers, union and
business representatives, service providers and program directors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GeorgiaGOP     05-20 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Georgia GOP,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Disrupt Opening Of Georgia GOP Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disgruntled Republicans, upset over the
disqualification of 968 would-be delegates, disrupted Friday's
opening session of the Georgia GOP convention by chanting ``no, no,
no'' and parading around the hall carrying placards.
   Many of the protesters were supporters of Pat Robertson's
presidential candidacy, but there were also supporters of Vice
President George Bush, Rep. Jack Kemp of New York and Sen. Bob Dole
of Kansas.
   Meanwhile, party officials refused to register any of the
estimated 1,600 people attending the convention at the Albany Civic
Center.
   State Republican Chairman John Stuckey told the crowd the party
was barred from officially seating any delegates until the
credentials committee had issued its report on the disqualified
delegates.
   ``I can't proceed with registration until I know who is a
delegate,'' he said. ``I am acting on the advice of counsel. I
don't intend to register anybody.''
   The credentials committee began the court-ordered review process
Friday morning, just hours before the convention opened. Supporters
of Pat Robertson's presidential candidacy boycotted the review
process, however, saying they would attempt to seat their own
delegates.
   Stuckey called the convention to order about 2 p.m. amid boos.
On two occasions when party leaders were speaking, many of those on
the floor of the convention hall stood up and shouted.
   The dispute was over a May 11 letter sent by the credentials
committee to 968 of the delegates elected at county conventions,
informing them they had been disqualified as delegates to the state
convention.
   Most were rejected because local party officials had not
provided evidence that the county conventions were advertised in
newspapers. Many of the disqualified delegates charged that that
technicality had never been used before.
   A major order of business at the two-day convention is the
election of the final 18 of the state's 48 delegates to the
Republican National Convention in New Orleans. All 48 are committed
to vote for Bush on the first two ballots at the August convention
because the vice president swept Georgia's GOP presidential
primary. But Robertson supporters are seeking to attend, hoping
they can influence selection of the vice presidential candidate and
the party platform.
</TEXT>
