<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0707,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amal Says It Thwarted Arms-For-Hostage Deal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with fighting spreading to
Chatilla camp, casualty report. Picks up 3rd graf, `They said .. .'
Minor editing</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEI4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Syrian-backed Amal militia claimed
Friday it had foiled an attempt by guerrillas of the pro-Iran
Hezbollah group to trade a Western hostage for arms from a
Christian militia.
   The claim came as Amal and Hezbollah, or Party of God, battled
for the 15th day for control of south Beirut's slums. Police said
rival Palestinian factions fought house-to-house in nearby Bourj
el-Barajneh and Chatilla refugee camps.
   In the Palestinian fighting, police said one guerrilla was
killed and 36 people were wounded in combat that first flared in
Bourj el-Barajneh and then spread to Chatilla.
   They said guerrillas of PLO chairman Yasser Arafat's Fatah
faction flushed out Syrian-supported dissidents of Col. Saeed
Mousa's Fatah-Uprising group from their five bases in the sprawling
shantytown near Beirut airport.
   The dissidents shelled the camp with long-range artillery in the
mountains overlooking Beirut in a bid to blunt the assault by
Arafat's loyalists, police said. They was no immediate report of
casualties.
   Amal politburo member Atif Aoun told 10,000 Shiites in the south
Lebanon town of Zahrani that Hezbollah had worked out an
arms-for-hostage deal with the Lebanese Forces, the Christians'
main militia.
   Amal foiled the alleged swap ``after we found out about contacts
between Hezbollah and the Lebanese Forces,'' he said without
elaboration.
   Most of the 18 Western hostages held by Shiite factions allied
with Hezbollah are believed held in the embattled southern slums.
   Militia officials declined to identify the hostage or say how
the reported trade was thwarted.
   Hezbollah and the Lebanese Forces denied the Amal claim.
   ``It's an attempt to distort Hezbollah's image,'' said a
Hezbollah spokesman, who refused to be identified.
   George Adwan, the Lebanese Forces political head, said: ``Atif
Aoun's baseless accusations constitutes a cheap attempt to cover up
Amal's military losses in south Beirut.''
   The U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, Vernon Walters,
arrived in Damascus on Friday, but told reporters his visit was
``not specifically for the hostages.''
   The Syrians have been helpful in the past in securing the
release of foreign hostages, ``but I don't want to be in the
position of telling the Syrians what to do,'' he stressed.
   Hezbollah and the right-wing Lebanese forces are bitter foes in
Lebanon's 13-year-old civil war. The only thing they have in common
is that both oppose Syrian efforts to control Lebanon.
   Hezbollah has seized control of most of south Beirut in recent
fighting. But the Iranian-backed fundamentalists are penned up in
the slums by the Syrians on three sides and the Christians to the
east and apparently unable to get weapons and ammunition in.
   Amal remains entrenched in the Shiyah district on the northern
edge of the shantytown, where they have surrounded a Hezbollah base
in Hajjaj Street.
   A senior Amal official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the arms-for-hostage exchange was to have taken place there.
   The Lebanese Forces hold the Christian district of Ein Rummaneh,
east of Hajjaj street. The two districts have been separated by a
25-yard-wide no-man's land since the civil war broke out in 1975.
   Police said the two factions fought with howitzers and mortars
Friday.
   Nine people were killed and 42 wounded in the fighting. That
raised the toll since May 6 to 253 killed and 814 wounded.
   The Syrians have deployed 7,500 troops and 500 tanks along the
southern, western and northern edges of south Beirut since Sunday,
but have made no move yet to push into the labyrinthine slums to
end the fighting and aid Amal, its battered proxy.
   Syrian officers have said this was to give political efforts a
chance to end the fighting, but those efforts have failed.
   In Paris, Le Monde reported that Brig. Gen. Ghazi Kanaan, the
Syrian intelligence chief in Lebanon, said Syria's entry ``into the
southern suburbs is inevitable.''
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, is Iran's principal
Arab ally in its war against Iraq.
   But Damascus has been alarmed by Iranian efforts, through
Hezbollah, to dominate Lebanon's 1.2 million Shiites, the country's
largest Moslem sect.
   In a change of stance, Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah,
Hezbollah's spiritual guide, voiced cautious approval of a Syrian
deployment.
   ``The entry of Syrian troops is a possibility. No one is
thinking of confronting the Syrians,'' he said.
   A Canadian Protestant clergyman arrived Friday seeking to
deliver a petition from a Christian human rights group to Hezbollah.
   The Rev. Ray Barnett, representative of the Seattle-based
Friends in the West, said he hoped to hand the petition signed by
40,000 people from various countries to Fadlallah.
   Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, is the longest-held hostage. He was kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
