<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Drugs     05-20 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Drugs,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Aide Questioned About Bush-Briggs Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top aide to Vice President George Bush
invoked executive privilege Thursday when asked what was said about
narcotics when Bush met with the U.S. ambassador to Panama in 1985
in Bush's office.
   During a three-hour deposition, Col. Samuel J. Watson III,
deputy national security adviser to Bush, did answer some questions
posed by Lewis Pitts, the attorney for a group of plaintiffs in a
private civil lawsuit.
   Watson said he had prepared a memorandum to set up Bush's Dec.
16, 1985 meeting with Ambassador Everett Briggs. Briggs wanted to
discuss a situation involving Nicholas Barletta, who had been
ousted as Panama's president by military leader Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, and the subject of narcotics, Watson said.
   Watson testified in the sworn deposition that he was present at
the meeting along with Bush's top national security aide, Donald
Gregg, and an official from the State Department.
   But when asked what Briggs told Bush on the subject of
narcotics, Watson's lawyer, Richard Stearns, objected and
instructed his client not to answer on grounds of executive
privilege. Stearns later said the privilege applies because it
covers conversations of the president and vice president.
   Pitts then asked Watson whether narcotics was discussed at all
in the meeting.
   ``I don't recall specifically whether they were or not. I could
make that assumption, but I will not state it as a certainty,'' he
said. Watson said he had since searched for any memorandum
summarizing the meeting, but could find no such document.
   Watson said he had only a vague knowledge of narcotics issues
involving Panama at that time. ``There were vague, unsubstantiated
rumors around that ... people in the PDF (Panamanian Defense
Forces) were facilitating trafficking of drugs,'' Watson said.
   The New York Times reported May 8, citing administration sources
it did not identify, that Briggs briefed Bush at the 1985 meeting
on allegations that Noriega was involved in the drug trade. Briggs
has since denied that he could have given clear indications of
Noreiga's drug involvement at that meeting, saying he himself did
not have any solid evidence at the time.
   Bush has repeatedly denied that he was aware of any clear
evidence of such involvement by Noriega before this February, when
the Panamanian general was indicted by two grand juries in Florida
on drug charges. His Democratic opponents in the presidential
campaign have questioned how much Bush knew about Noriega's alleged
drug involvement.
   Watson's statements came during a deposition for a $24 million
damage and racketeering lawsuit charging that a group of defendants
_ including some involved in the Iran-Contra affair _ supplied the
Nicaraguan Contra rebels with weapons in trade for cocaine. The
suit also accuses the group of planning the May 1984 bombing that
injured maverick rebel leader Eden Pastora in Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
