<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PresidentialMoney     05-20 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Money,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Fights In Money Big League</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's once-poor presidential
campaign raised and spent as much as front-runner Michael Dukakis
as they battled in last month's crucial Democratic primaries,
records filed Friday showed.
   With the expensive races in California and New Jersey still
ahead, Dukakis and Jackson each entered the month of May with $1
million-plus bank accounts.
   Jackson actually spent more than Dukakis during April, but a
good chunk of his spending _ $804,570 _ went to pay off loans,
according to the financial disclosure report he filed with the
Federal Election Commission.
   Jackson reported spending $4 million during the month, while
Dukakis spent $3.7 million as they dueled across such expensive
states as New York and Pennsylvania. Dukakis, the best financed
Democrat throughout the campaign, has borrowed no money.
   Jackson took out another $624,000 in loans in April, for a total
of $1.4 million in loans since the beginning of the year. Spokesman
Tom Schade said the loans borrowed and repaid last month reflected
a rotating line of credit the campaign has for operating expenses.
   Jackson ended the month with $1.1 million in cash on hand and
$548,741 in debts, his report showed. Dukakis had $1.4 million on
hand, and $699,906 in obligations.
   On the Republican side, certain nominee George Bush ended April
with $4 million in cash on hand after raising $2 million for the
month, including $1.2 million in matching funds, and spending $1.7
million. Bush also reported taking out a $20,000 loan for general
election campaign start-up costs.
   Television evangelist Pat Robertson, who suspended his campaign
last week, showed a debt of $1.4 million at the start of this
month, after raising $1.1 million, with $341,523 of that in federal
matching funds, and spending $1.1 million during April. Robertson
had only $29,473 in the bank.
   Jackson continued his steady upswing in fund-raising, with total
receipts of $4.2 million, including the loan and $1.7 in federal
matching funds, while Dukakis took in $3.4 million, including $1.1
million in matching funds.
   In receipts from contributors, the two remaining Democratic
contenders were almost dead even, each taking in about $1.9
million. While Dukakis has had many high-dollar months and has
proven a consistent fund-raising power, the April numbers reflect
the sophistication of Jackson's fund-raising arm.
   During the first half of April, Jackson was riding high on the
success he had achieved with his upset Michigan victory and wins in
other states. But he subsequently suffered heavy losses to Dukakis
in state after state.
   Dukakis' campaign said he has raised $23.6 million from the
start of his campaign through the end of April, including $6.8
million in matching funds, which are based on the amount a
candidate raises on his own. Jackson's campaign total through April
was $11.7 million.
   Dukakis' campaign is penny-pinching these days so it can spend
enough on the expensive June 7 California primary and still have
enough money for the summer convention operations without
surpassing the $27 million maximum set by federal law.
   The rules say candidates who receive federal matching funds can
spend no more than $23 million on their primary campaigns, plus
another $4 million for fund-raising costs.
   Dukakis through April had spent $18 million against the $23
million cap. But current spending is budgeted ``to the dime'' so
the campaign will leave itself with money to spend on the party
convention in Atlanta this July, said campaign spokesman Steve Akey.
   Dukakis treasurer Robert Farmer said in a statement that the
campaign has received money from 80,000 individuals whose
contributions averaged $170 each. He said his candidate's
fund-raising success reflects an ``excitement and enthusiasm
Americans feel'' toward Dukakis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2223EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Singapore     05-20 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singapore,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singapore To Elect Future Presidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singapore plans to convert its largely
ceremonial presidency into an elected post with executive powers
and Lee Kuan Yew seems likely to seek that role after he retires as
prime minister.
   Confirmation that an elected president is in the works was made
in parliament Thursday.
   Legislation described as ``only a very preliminary draft which
needs considerable revision and improvements,'' has been prepared,
said Phua Bah Lee, a senior parliamentary secretary.
   Phua's brief statement was a written reply to a question
submited by Chaim See Tong, the only opposition member of
parliament. It ended four years of speculation that basic changes
were planned in the way this bustling island republic is governed.
   The president is now named by Parliament to a four-year term.
Wee Kim Wee, 72, a former diplomat and journalist, has been
president since 1985.
   In his national day address in 1984, Lee said the constitution
might be changed to prevent any future government from squandering
Singapore's ample reserves. He said an elected president with veto
power over access to these assets might be the answer.
   Lee has for years said he would like to follow the example of
many U.S. corporate leaders and step down at 65. He reaches that
age on Sept. 16.
   Goh Chok Tong, 46, who was named first deputy prime minister
after the 1984 elections, is positioned to succeed Lee. The prime
minister's eldest son, Trade and Industry Minister Lee Hsien Loong,
36, is also regarded as eventual prime ministerial material. A
retired army general, he entered politics less than four years ago.
   Observers here say the elder Lee would be a natural candidate
for the presidential post.
   A Cambridge-educated lawyer, Lee became prime minister in 1959
on a wave of anti-colonialism and with the help of Communists, whom
he later purged. But steady economic growth has endeared Lee to a
population of 2.6 million that enjoys one of the highest living
standards in Asia.
   On Friday, the island republic's Home Affairs Ministry said a
prominent Singapore lawyer arrested for plotting subversive
activities admitted he had links with a recently expelled U.S.
diplomat.
   The arrested lawyer, 59-year-old Francis Seow, was taken into
custody earlier this month under Singapore's tough Internal
Security Act for questioning into possible foreign interference in
domestic affairs.
   At the time, Singapore also ordered E. Mason Hendrickson, a
first secretary in the U.S. Embassy's political section, out of the
country for allegedly urging people to run for public office
against the governing People's Action Party.
   ``I found Hank (Hendrickson) to be a pleasant person. I
maintained cordial relations with him as he had been supportive of
my political intentions, which I found most encouraging,'' Seow
said in a sworn declaration made public by the Home Affairs
Ministry on Friday.
   The government also called on Washington to reprimand two of
Hendrickson's State Department superiors, who were not publicly
named.
   The United States denied the allegations and expelled Robert
Chua, a first secretary at the Singapore Embassy in Washington, on
May 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
