<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0645 05-20 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0645,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hits Reagan, Bush on Noriega Dealing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Dukakis on Noriega, new budget trimming,
hecklers at rally in top 14 grafs, picking up in 2nd graf pvs, ``We
meet</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential front-runner
Michael Dukakis said Friday the Reagan administration ``owes the
American people an explanation'' of why it was doing business with
Panamanian Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   At a news conference at the Sacramento airport, Dukakis said,
``I and the American people want an explanation. ... Unless and
until we have that explanation, I'm not going to be satisfied.''
   Dukakis said President Reagan or Vice President George Bush or
``somebody in the administration'' should tell the American people
``who it was who thought it was in the interests of the American
people and this country that we do business with somebody who was a
known drug peddler and who was suspected of murder.''
   Meanwhile, in Washington, an administration official said U.S.
and Panamanian negotiators have tentatively agreed on a deal that
calls for Noriega to leave Panama by August and stay away until
next May.
   In return, the United States would agree to drop federal drug
indictments against him, said the official, who has followed the
negotiations. He commented only on condition he not be named.
   On another subject, Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis' administration
and finance secretary, Frank Keefe, announced new proposed spending
cuts, efficiency steps and revenue plans designed to improve the
bottom line of Dukakis' $11.9 billion state budget proposal for
next year by $217 million.
   Faced with a shortfall in tax collections, Dukakis is proposing
to cut $92 million from expansions he had previously proposed in
dozens of individual programs. He also signed off on a hoped-for
$47 million in savings through improved government operations. He
also hopes to raise millions more through bottle deposits and a
higher tax on cigarettes.
   In Sacramento, Dukakis addressed a rally in a plaza in front of
the Cathedral of the Blessed Sacrament as hecklers stood on the
steps of the church holding signs denouncing his stance in favor of
a right to abortion.
   ``Real Greeks don't kill babies,'' read one sign.
   As he spoke, hecklers chanted, ``Baby killer, baby killer.'' But
the chants were largely drowned out by the loudspeaker system.
   Asked about his position on abortion at the news conference,
Dukakis said, ``I don't favor abortion. I don't think it's a good
thing. I don't know anybody who does.''
   However, he said that he believes it is a matter of an
individual woman's choice, to be made according to the dictates of
her conscience.
   He said he understood people who had a different view but wished
``they could keep the decibel level down.''
   Earlier Friday, in Los Angeles, Dukakis said he expects to hold
regular meetings with rival Jesse Jackson, who has stepped up his
criticism of party rules as his presidential hopes dimmed.
   ``We meet,'' Dukakis said after an appearance at an East Los
Angeles high school. ``We met Sunday, we'll be meeting regularly.''
   Jackson has been pressing Democratic Party leaders to give him a
greater share of the votes of so-called ``super delegates,'' the
party and elected officials given automatic delegate status at the
nominating convention in Juy.
   Most of those delegates have been falling in line behind the
Dukakis candidacy, prompting Jackson to complain that he is
receiving a disproportionately small number compared to his primary
and caucus showings.
   Jackson said Thursday he expected to meet soon with Dukakis to
discuss strategy and issues.
   Dukakis campaigned in Los Angeles, Sacramento and San Francisco
with less than three weeks before the June 7 California primary,
one of four that day. Dukakis expects to collect enough delegates
on the final primary day to put him over the 2,081 delegates needed
for a convention majority.
   When Dukakis took questions from the predominantly black student
body of the George Washington Preparatory High School, the very
first was, ``Is this a token visit?''
   When the Massachusetts governor appeared puzzled by the
question, the student said she wanted to know if his visit was a
rare appearance in a black neighborhood.
   Dukakis, who has made few appearances in black communities and
has largely conceded the black vote to Jackson, replied, ``I've
been in black schools for years. ... I'm here because this is a
very, very special place with a great reputation.''
   One student asked Dukakis if he was interested in running for
vice president on a ticket heaed by Jackson.
   Dukakis grinned and said, ``I'm not interested in the vice
presidency.''
   Dukakis' wife, Kitty, told the students how she became dependent
on diet pills and urged them to use her example to stay away from
drugs and alcohol.
   After the question-and-answer session, students had Dukakis don
a baseball-style jacket and then led him and his wife onto a stage,
which was set up for a performance of the musical ``Grease.''
Dukakis and his wife sat on stools at center stage while students
performed ``Summer Loving,'' a song from the show.
   The students tried to get Dukakis to wear sunglasses. At first,
he pushed them back on his forehead, then finally took them off and
handed them back.
</TEXT>
