<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AtomicVets 1stLd-Writethru a0799 05-20 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atomic Vets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0799,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WWII Vets No Longer Need Prove Atomic Radiation Caused Illnesses</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 3 grafs to show how many veterans affected and at
what cost. Picks up 4th graf pvs, The legislation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed legislation Friday
making it easier for hundreds of thousands veterans to receive
disability benefits for exposure to radiation from the World War II
atomic blasts in Japan or from nuclear test explosions.
   Ordinarily, veterans claiming disability benefits must prove the
disability was connected with their military service. The bill
bypasses this requirement for a limited group of veterans with
respect to specified diseases.
   It applies primarily to cancer of various organs. The Office of
Management and Budget said more than 300,000 veterans would be
affected by the legislation, and the first-year cost was estimated
at $65.6 million.
   The legislation affects veterans who served with U.S. forces
occupying Hiroshima or Nagasaki, Japan. It covers the period from
Aug. 6, 1945, when the atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima,
through July 1, 1946.
   Also covered are veterans held as prisoners of war in Japan
during World War II, or who served on active duty in Japan
immediately following such internment if they were subject to
exposure to radioactivity comparable to that of the veterans who
served at Hiroshima and Nagasaki.
   The bill also applies to veterans who participated in tests
involving atmospheric detonation of a nuclear device.
   Norman Solomon, Washington spokesman for the Alliance of Atomic
Veterans, called the new law ``a long overdue step toward taking
care of a very large and serious problem.''
   ``Deadly legacies of radiation exposure hang heavily over every
American community,'' Solomon said.
   The legislation would apply only to ailments that manifest
themselves within 40 years after the veteran's last possible
exposure to the specified sources of radiation or, in the case of
leukemia, 30 years afterward. This period already has passed for
veterans who served in Hiroshima and Nagasaki or were prisoners of
war in Japan.
   ``Enactment of this legislation does not represent a judgment
that service-related radiation exposure of veterans covered by the
act in fact caused any disease, nor does it represent endorsement
of a principle of permitting veterans to receive benefits funded
through veterans programs which bear no relationship to their
former military service,'' Reagan said.
   ``Instead, this act gives due recognition for the unusual
service rendered by Americans who participated in military
activities involving exposure to radiation generated by the
detonation of atomic explosives. The nation is grateful for their
special service, and ... (this bill) makes clear the nation's
continuing concern for their welfare.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
