<DOCNO> AP880520-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1833EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0657 05-20 0845</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0657,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aide Says Panamanian President Told Bush of Drug Allegations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS top 2 grafs to put time element in lead; INSERTS 2
grafs after 6th graf bgng, `Bush has,' to include objections from
Gregg's lawyer; SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `When Gregg,' to DELETE 2nd
full reference to Withey; INSERTS 3 grafs after 9th graf pvs bgng,
`I think,' with additional Gregg comment; DELETES last graf pvs,
now redundant</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Panama told Vice President
George Bush in December 1983 of allegations that officials in his
country were connected to drug trafficking, but he also told Bush
the charges were untrue, a top Bush aide present at the meeting
said Friday.
   Bush's national security adviser, Donald Gregg, said that
then-Panamanian President Ricardo de la Espriella mentioned the
allegations at the end of a meeting in Panama. Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, now the de facto ruler of Panama, attended the meeting,
Gregg said.
   ``The vice president said he had not been aware (of the charges)
or he would have raised them'' with de la Espriella, Gregg
testified in a sworn deposition for a private civil lawsuit.
   ``We did nothing to follow that up'' after returning to
Washington, Gregg said. Bush was then chairman of the South Florida
Drug Interdiction Task Force.
   Gregg also testified that he was aware at the time that the
government of Panama had been helpful to the United States in
getting military supplies to Nicaragua's Contra rebels.
   Bush has said he had no reliable information connecting Noriega
to the drug trade until Noriega was indicted in February on drug
charges by two Florida grand juries.
   Gregg's testimony came during a day-long deposition as part of a
$24 million suit by the Christic Institute, a liberal policy group,
charging that a list of defendants, some of whom were involved in
the Iran-Contra affair, supplied the Contras with weapons in trade
for cocaine, and conspired in a failed attempt to assassinate a
maverick Contra field commander, Eden Pastora.
   Gregg's Justice Department attorney, Richard Stearns, voiced
repeated objections throughout the day to the questioning, charging
that it ranged far from the subject matter of the suit and was
being done for political purposes. ``I think it's quite clear you
have some other agenda in mind,'' he said at one point to Michael
Withey, an attorney for the plaintiffs.
   On Thursday, another Bush aide, Col. Samuel J. Watson, invoked
executive privilege and declined to answer when asked during a
similar deposition what Bush and the U.S. ambassador to Panama,
Everett Briggs, discussed about narcotics at a Dec. 16, 1985,
meeting.
   When Withey asked Gregg about the same meeting on Friday, he
agreed to discuss it but said his recollection was not specific.
   ``I think we came away from the meeting with Ambassador Briggs
with the sense that Noriega was a growing problem _ politically,
militarily and possibly in the drug area,'' Gregg testified. But he
said any drug problems involving Noriega ``were not highlighted''
by Briggs.
   Later in the day, Withey asked Gregg: ``The fact that General
Noriega may have had some involvement in the narcotics problem,
that was coming out of the December '85 meeting at that time, isn't
that correct?''
   Gregg responded: ``It would have been part of the general
picture of Noriega as a political problem, as corruption, and as a
general policy problem, yes.''
   But talking with reporters later, Gregg said he did not recall
any discussion of Noriega's involvement in drug trafficking. ``I am
saying that narcotics as a problem in Panama was part of the agenda
of the meeting. ... There was no discussion of any direct
connection between that and Noriega.''
   Earlier this month, Briggs denied a published report that he had
briefed Bush on allegations that Noriega was involved in the drug
trade.
   By the time of that meeting, Gregg said, Bush was chairman of
the president's anti-narcotics task force.
   It was ``certainly in the realm of the possible'' that Gregg was
aware of charges that Noriega was linked to drugs, Gregg said, in
part because he knew of similar charges that had been made against
a brother of Noriega's predecessor, Gen. Omar Torrijos, during
Senate debate over the Panama Canal treaties in 1978.
   ``Noriega was now in power, and it was possible to conjecture
that he'd become involved in some of that,'' Gregg said.
   Gregg also testified that a State Department briefing paper
would have been prepared for Bush's meeting with Briggs outlining
the background of the ambassador's concerns, and that the paper
would have been placed in Bush's briefing book to prepare him for
the meeting.
   That document is among papers sought by the plaintiffs in the
suit, but which have not been turned over by the government.
   After Noriega's indictment, Gregg said, the vice president's
office searched for documents relating to past Bush-Noriega
dealings.
   The search turned up ``a couple'' of documents from the CIA and
a State Department cable prepared after the 1983 meeting in Panama,
he said.
</TEXT>
