<1ST_LINE>u a AM-LehderCartel 1stLd-Writethru a0695 05-20 0838</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Cartel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,0856</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Say Lehder Conviction Chops One Head from Cocaine
Hydra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, `Cocaine shipments ..., with 3 grafs to
update with jury action in Jacksonville; picks up 6th graf pvs,
`We'd all ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cocaine-smuggling conviction of Carlos Lehder
Rivas has heartened the front line in the drug war, but officials
acknowledged Friday they are far from destroying the violent
Medellin drug cartel.
   In the past month alone, drug agents have seized 3.7 tons of
cocaine in a single shipment of lumber, taken two tons from a
speedboat making a run into the Keys, and confiscated two tons more
hidden in food shipments.
   That dwarfs the 3.3 tons Lehder was convicted of smuggling into
the country from 1978 to 1980, though he is considered responsible
for much more.
   ``You've got an awful lot of heads on the Hydra you have to cut
off,'' Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr Jim Simpson said Friday, referring to
the multiheaded creature of Greek mythology. ``Lehder was one of
them.''
   In Jacksonville on Friday, the jury that convicted Lehder
decided the government can confiscate millions of dollars in real
estate on a Bahamian island, as well as several planes and other
items owned by Lehder. The issue of property forfeiture has to be
considered separately under federal law.
   According to Internal Revenue Service figures, Lehder earned an
estimated $250 million in the cocaine business. But it remained
uncertain how the government could take control of property in the
Bahamas.
   During the year Lehder has been in U.S. custody, cocaine
shipments into the country actually increased, and the absence of a
current U.S.-Colombia extradition treaty clouds future anti-drug
efforts, said Drug Enforcement Administration spokesman Jack Hook.
   ``We'd all be pretty silly if we thought that the arrest and
conviction of one man would stop drug trafficking,'' he said.
``It's very positive news, but it's just one small battle.''
   Simpson and other South Florida officials emphasize their
efforts to block drug imports are continuing.
   The Customs Service's ``Blue Lightning'' speed boat task force
released its 1987 statistics Friday, showing it helped arrest 255
people and intercepted almost seven tons of cocaine, along with
more than 200 tons of marijuana.
   The Colombia-based Medellin Cartel still ships up to 80 percent
of the cocaine that makes its way into the United States. The DEA
considered Lehder one of the four managers of the cartel until his
arrest early last year. The others have evaded _ and sometimes
defied _ Colombian and U.S. justice.
   The reputed top leader, Jorge Luis Ochoa Vasquez, has twice been
seized by Colombian authorities, and twice succeeded in slipping
from their hands. Another of Lehder's reputed co-leaders, Pablo
Emilio Escobar Gaviria, has been sighted frequently in Colombia but
never caught.
   The cartel has turned to violence to intimidate Colombian
authorities into abandoning cooperation with U.S. anti-drug
efforts, Hook said.
   In 1984, Justice Minister Rodrigo Lara Bonilla was assassinated
by traffickers, and in January, Colombia's crusading Attorney
General Carlos Mauro Hoyos was gunned down. The successful
anti-drug candidate for mayor of Bogota was briefly kidnapped
during this year's campaign. And many believe the 1985 guerrilla
attack that killed many Colombian supreme court justices was
coordinated with the traffickers.
   Whether because of the violence or not, the U.S.-Colombia
extradition treaty has been invalidated by Colombia's supreme court
since Lehder's capture, and the issue is now on hold.
   ``The extradition treaty was the only tool the drug-trafficking
kingpins ever feared,'' said Hook, adding he hopes the conviction
will encourage Colombia to renew it.
   The lack of a treaty and the continued cocaine trafficking
doesn't mean Lehder's prosecution was a meaningless gesture, law
enforcement officials said.
   ``It shows this country does very well mean business when we
have a drug trafficker anywhere in the world,'' said Gerald
Hochman, director of a federal task force on the south Florida drug
trade. ``There is no way out _ if he's committed the crime, he's
going to pay the price.''
   The conviction was a boost to front-line officers combating drug
traffickers on a daily basis, especially those who have become
discouraged by talk of a deal to drop the drug indictment against
Panama's ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, officials said.
   ``We're delighted,'' the Coast Guard's Simpson said. ``One of
the complaints peope have been lodging for many years is that you
always get the small fry. This time we got one of the big guys.''
   U.S. Attorney Robert Merkle, who prosecuted Lehder in
Jacksonville, said the conviction is a psychological boost to all
agencies fighting drug trafficking.
   ``Every war in history has seen battles which have practical
consequences byeond the immediate consequence of the battlefied,''
he said. ``By that, I mean that they serve to catalyze national
will to win the war, or serve as a pyschological defeat for the
other side.''
   In that sense, Lehder's conviction was ``a very real, tangible
victory for the American people and for Colombia,'' Merkle said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
