<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-20 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Kill Party Official, Four Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese assassins shot and killed
the general secretary of the governing United National Party in
Colombo on Friday and fellow extremists killed four other people in
southern Sri Lanka, police said.
   Police Sub-inspector G. Kalupahana said two men opened fire with
AK-47 automatic rifles as Nandalal Fernando was being driven to his
office. Kalupahana said the killers and a third man escaped on a
motorcyle.
   Fernando was shot in the stomach and hand and died three hours
later at a hospital, according to police officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   They blamed the attack on the People's Liberation Front, a group
of ultra-nationalist Sinhalese who vowed to kill anyone who
supports President Junius R. Jayewardene's peace efforts with the
Tamil minority.
   General secretary is the fourth-highest post in Jayewardene's
political party. The party chairman was assassinated in December.
   Military officials said other Front gunmen killed a postal
officer in Kotegoda town in an attempt to disrupt the delivery of
postal ballots for provincial elections early next month. The
victim's name was not disclosed.
   In a similar attack at Hakmana, also in the south, Front gunmen
tried to kill a mailman. He escaped unhurt, but his wife and two
neighbors were killed.
   The Front opposes the elections which are to be held as part of
the peace accord to halt bloodshed in this Indian Ocean island
nation.
   The government has blamed the People's Liberation Front in the
deaths of about 260 government officials and supporters since July
29, 1987, when the Tamil peace accord was signed.
   Fernando, like Jayewardene, belongs to the Sinhalese ethnic
group that controls the government and makes up 75 percent of the
nation's 16 million people. Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of the
population, say they are discriminated against in jobs and
education.
   Tamil rebels have fought a guerrilla war for nearly five years
for a separate homeland on Sri Lanka. They rejected the 1987
accord, which provides greater autonomy in Tamil-populated areas if
the rebels give up their weapons.
   India sent more than 50,000 soldiers to Sri Lanka, just off
south India, to enforce the accord, but the Tamils are now fighting
the Indians.
   On May 10, the government lifted a 5-year ban on political
activities by the People's Liberation Front after announcing it
signed a peace agreement with the Sinhalese radicals. The Front
denied reaching any agreement and pressed its attacks against
Sinhalese politicians.
</TEXT>
