<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmallKidnapping     05-20 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Small Kidnapping,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widow Testifies About Small Kidnapping; Prosecution Rests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two days before he was found dead,
businessman Stephen Small taped a message to his wife said he was
buried alive ``inside some ... box'' and would die unless a $1
million ranson was paid.
   Tapes made by Small were played by the prosecutors Friday in the
trial of Daniel J. Edwards, 31, of Bourbonnais, who is charged with
kidnapping and murdering Small, a member of a prominent media
family.
   Small's widow, Nancy, was the final prosecution witness in the
5-day-old trial. She told jurors that her husband's comments were
on a recording played to her during a telephone call made early
last Sept. 2, shortly after he was lured from their home and
kidnapped.
   ``I'm inside some, I guess, a box,'' Small says on the tape.
``It's under a couple of feet of sand or something, like
underground ... and I want you to get $1 million.''
   The kidnapper spoke first, warning her not to call the police
but to raise the money quickly or ``he would never tell me where my
husband was buried,'' Mrs. Small said.
   Mrs. Small said her husband assured her it was not a joke, and
that the kidnapper wanted the ransom in 50- and 100-dollar bills.
   ``He said he hd enough air for 48 hours,'' Mrs. Small said,
recalling her husband's final words in that 3:30 a.m. telephone
call.
   Police unearthed Small's body two days later, buried in rural
Kankakee County in a homemade wooden box in which he suffocated.
   More than 100 people, including members of the Small family,
packed the Kankakee County courtroom to hear Mrs. Small's testimony
and to listen to the recordings.
   The defense was expected to begin its case Saturday.
   The first tape of Small and his kidnapper was found along a
road, and was reconstructed by the FBI. It was difficult to
understand at times, but the jury was given a transcript.
   Another call at about 11:30 p.m. Sept. 2 includes a recording of
Small reading instructions to his wife for delivery of the cash.
   The money was raised and the family was prepared to pay the
ransom, said Mrs. Small, but the quality of the recording was so
poor she could not understand all the instructions for delivery.
   ``I could hear another voice in the background swearing,'' Mrs.
Small testified. ``Then I realized it was Steve's voice. He was
giving me instructions ... where to take the money.''
   Small told his wife that after the cash was delivered and
counted, a map would be mailed to her giving directions to the
burial site.
   Mrs. Small said the kidnapper's voice came on the telephone and
she tried to get clarification of the delivery orders, but soon
``he just hung up the phone.''
   Small was lured by a telephone call from the family's Victorian
home near the Kankakee River shortly after midnight Sept. 2, 1987.
   Previous testimony has linked Edwards to the coffin-sized box,
which witnesses said they saw him building, and to a public
telephone at about the time a ransom call was being recorded by the
FBI.
   The woman with whom Edwards lived, Nancy D. Rish, 26, also was
charged with murder and kidnapping and was awaiting trial.
</TEXT>
