<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Papua New Guinea,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Era Ends as Opposition Leader Quits in Papua New Guinea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Somare, known to
this South Pacific nation as the father of its independence,
stepped down Friday as opposition leader.
   Australian officials called it the end of an era in Pacific
politics.
   Somare, 52, told reporters he was ``calling it a day'' after
handing over duties as leader of the Pangu Party to his deputy,
Rabbi Namaliu. He gave no specific reason for his action.
   He is known as ``the chief'' in this Melanesian island nation of
3.3 million people. He led it to independence from Australia in
1975 and was twice elected prime minister.
   There was no immediate comment from the government of Prime
Minister Paias Wingti, who replaced Somare in 1985.
</TEXT>
