<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BusCrash     05-20 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mahoney Pleads Innocent To All Counts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE EMBRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The driver of the pickup truck that
slammed into a church bus last week pleaded innocent to 27 counts
of murder on Friday, one count for each person killed in the fiery
crash.
   Larry W. Mahoney, 34, of Worthville in Carroll County, was taken
to the psychiatric unit at the Kentucky State Reformatory in
LaGrange, where doctors will determine whether he is competent to
stand trial.
   The pickup was traveling in the wrong direction on Interstate 71
Saturday night when it plowed head-on into a bus from the First
Assembly of God Church in Radcliff. The bus was carrying 67 people,
mostly teen-agers, on their way home from an outing at an amusement
park near Cincinnati.
   The pleas were entered by Mahoney's attorney, Gary Sergent.
   Meanwhile, funerals were being held Friday in three states for
15 of the 27 crash victims, including an evening service for nine
youths and one adult at the church that owned the bus, Radcliff
First Assembly of God.
   In Bardstown, the funeral Mass for Sandy Brewer, 12, at St.
Monica Catholic Church ``just got terribly emotional,'' said the
Rev. Jim Graf.
   Family, clergymen and choir joined hands and wept in front of
the altar, he said, calling it ``a moment when the whole church
just let go together.''
   Mahoney, who police said was legally drunk at the time of the
crash, kept his head bowed or his eyes lowered throughout the
18-minute arraignment. He did not say anything.
   Earlier in the day, Mahoney had been released from Humana
Hospital-University of Louisville, where he had been treated since
the accident.
   That left 13 people injured in the crash still hospitalized
Friday, five of them in critical condition.
   After the hearing, State Attorney General Fred Cowan announced
that former Jefferson County Commonwealth's Attorney Paul
Richwalsky was named special prosecutor for the case to replace
Carroll Commonwealth's Attorney John L. Ackman Jr., who suffered a
heart attack Wednesday.
   Cowan said prosecutors still intend to seek the death penalty in
the case, and it was too early to consider a plea-bargain.
   ``We'll be going to the grand jury directly,'' Cowan said, ``and
the case will proceed from there.''
   Richwalsky said he believed the case was the first time in
Kentucky that the death penalty would be sought in a vehicular
homicide case.
   When asked how difficult the case would be to prosecute,
Richwalsky said: ``I can't answer that. You can't forecast what a
jury might do in a particular case.''
   Mahoney's mother, Mary, wept occasionally during the hearing,
while his father, John, also had to wipe tears from his eyes.
   About 50 people _ some of them Mahoney's friends _ gathered
outside the courthouse door as Mahoney was led to a state police
cruiser, some shouting ``Larry, we're with you'' and ``Hang in
there, Larry.''
   ``Larry loves kids and he would never have done this on
purpose,'' said a friend, Juanita White.
   ``He's a loving, caring person,'' she said. ``I don't think he
needs the death penalty. I think he's got enough to live with this
(the 27 deaths).''
   Billingsley set a bond hearing for May 25 and a preliminary
hearing for June 2 in Carroll District Court.
</TEXT>
