<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HongKong-Refugees     05-20 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hong Kong-Refugees,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 280 Vietnamese Refugees Sail Into Hong Kong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 280 Vietnamese refugees sailed into
Hong Kong Friday aboard 14 boats, a government spokesman reported.
   The spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
refguees were intercepted by marine police throughout the day.
   He said no other details of the refugees were available.
   According to the spokesman, the latest arrivals brought to 2,107
the number of Vietname refugees who arrived in this British colony
this month.
   At present, there are more than 12,000 Vietnamese boat people in
Hong Kong awaiting resettlement overseas.
   More than 9,000 of them are housed in closed camps because they
arrived here after the government introduced a tough new policy in
1982 to deter the refugee influx.
   The others live in open camps, where they have freedom of
movement and are allowed to take jobs in the British colony.
   The Hong Kong government is currently considering whether to
scrap the policy of offering Vietnamese refugees temporary asylum
in the colony in order to stop the influx from Vietnam.
</TEXT>
