<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BrownArrest     05-20 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brown Arrest,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Adrienne Brown Arrested on New Drug Charge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AIKEN, S.C.-date story listed on AM-News Advisory</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legal problems of soul singer James
Brown and his wife, Adrienne, continued Friday with Mrs. Brown
arrested for the third time in a little over a month and charged
with possession of the drug PCP, police said.
   Mrs. Brown's arrest came two days after her husband was arrested
on drug and weapons charges, assaulting his wife and resisting
arrest.
   Brown, 55, denied he has a drug problem when he posted bail
Thursday, and his lawyer said he would petition the court to let
the man known as ``The Godfather of Soul'' leave the country for a
European concert tour.
   Mrs. Brown, 38, of Beech Island, S.C., was arrested at the
airport in nearby Augusta on Friday afternoon after arriving on a
flight from New York. Police acted on a tip that she would be
carrying drugs, said Ron Maher of the Augusta Police vice and
narcotics unit.
   Narcotics investigators stopped Mrs. Brown in the Bush Field
parking lot and confiscated a wet, leafy substance believed to
contain PCP. She was taken to the Richmond County-Augusta Law
Enforcement Center, where police said a search turned up a further
two vials suspected to contain PCP hidden in her blouse. She was
charged with possession of PCP.
   PCP, also known as ``angel dust,'' is a powerful psychedelic
drug.
   On May 10, Mrs. Brown was arrested in Bedford, N.H., after a
small fire in her hotel room and later charged with possession of
PCP, criminal mischief and arson. Bedford Police Chief Richard
Audette said Mrs. Brown is due to appear in Bedford District Court
on Wednesday.
   She also was arrested in Augusta on April 9 and charged with
possessing PCP. She claimed at the time that she had been set up by
a friend of her husband's.
   On Thursday, Brown posted $24,218 bond and was released from
Aiken County jail on condition that he not leave South Carolina,
Magistrate Max Meeks said.
   He was arrested near his home Wednesday after his wife called
police and said he was abusing her. Brown was charged with
possession of PCP, resisting arrest, illegal possession of a
pistol, failure to stop for a police car and simple assault and
battery.
   The arrest was his third in six months.
   ``It's getting to the point where we're spending a lot of time
investigating Mr. Brown's domestic problems,'' said Capt. James
Whitehurst of the Aiken County Sheriff's Department.
   Brown said Thursday his wife planted the drugs on him and that
he was working ``to keep the city and the world clean'' of drugs.
   ``I don't have a drug problem,'' he said.
   Brown's attorney, Bill Weeks, said he expects to ask that Brown
be allowed to go on the tour.
   ``That's how (Brown) earns his livelihood,'' Weeks said.
   Brown was allowed to tour in Brazil in April after posting bond
on charges of assault with intent to kill his wife and with assault
and battery of a high and aggravated nature.
   Mrs. Brown has filed for divorce, and her husband said he plans
to do the same.
</TEXT>
