<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CommencementsRdp     05-20 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commencements Rdp,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blacks Could Swing Presidential Election to Democrats, Hooks Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks could provide the crucial votes that swing this fall's
presidential election to the Democrats even though Jesse Jackson is
not likely to be the party's nominee, Benjamin L. Hooks, head of
the NAACP, said Friday.
   Hooks talked about the presidential campaign at a news
conference before making a commencement address at Central
Connecticut State University in New Britain, Conn.
   The head of the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People forecast that the black vote ``will be predominantly
Democratic,'' but he said he hoped that ``both parties will look at
this black vote, which can constitute 10 to 12 percent of the
general electorate vote, as a vote that ought to be pursued
diligently.''
   He said blacks should make efforts not to appear to be the
captives of one party. ``If that becomes the fact, then we will be
ignored by the Democratic Party and overlooked by the other party
and we become of no consequence,'' he said.
   Hooks said Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis appears to have
locked up the Democratic presidential nomination. Jackson will have
a hard time deciding whether to accept the vice presidential
nomination, if it is offered, he added.
   ``The only thing you could give (Jackson) that would be bigger
than what he has would be the presidency and it appears at this
point he won't get it,'' Hooks said. ``He's a young man and I think
he'll be running for president for the next 20 years and maybe one
of these years he'll make it.''
   In his address, Hooks urged 2,015 graduates to vote and noted
that fewer than 60 percent of eligible voters cast ballots in the
1984 presidential election.
   In Charleston, S.C., former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger
urged graduates of the Medical University of South Carolina to
combat the use of illegal drugs and said exporting health care will
help friendly democracies take hold overseas.
   ``Only healthy people have the strength really needed to win
freedom and maintain it against all manner of tyranny,'' Weinberger
told a commencement audience of about 4,000, including 554
graduates.
   Some graduates circulated a statement during the ceremonies
protesting Weinberger's selection as speaker and the university's
proposed involvement in research and health at the Savannah River
Plant, the nation's only plant making weapons-grade plutonium.
   In New Haven, Conn., actress Susan Saint James received an
honorary doctor of humane letters degree from Southern Connecticut
State University Friday for her contributions to the international
Special Olympics.
   The Connecticut resident is vice president of the state's
Special Olympics and chairwoman for national affairs for the
national organization.
</TEXT>
