<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AIDS-Gregory     05-20 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Gregory,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Rehires Clerk With AIDS-Related Complex on Part-Time Basis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Justice Department employee fired because he
has AIDS-related complex is being reinstated in his old job on a
part-time basis, the department said Friday.
   Mark W. Gregory, a clerk-typist in the department's community
relations service, will return to work Monday and work 4{ hours a
day five days a week, department spokesman Patrick Korten said.
   Gregory was dismissed April 11 because he was absent for 30 days
during the nine months he worked for the service.
   He said a supervisor suggested he take 10 days leave without pay
after he was diagnosed as having AIDS-related complex, a less
severe form of acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Gregory said he
took 14 days' leave without pay to participate in an experimental
treatment program at the National Institutes of Health.
   After his dismissal was publicized this month, the Justice
Department offered to rehire him in a temporary one-year post.
Gregory rejected that offer this week, saying he wanted to be
reinstated in his old job because it was a permanent position
carrying more protections and benefits.
   Korten said the department reached the latest decision to
reinstate him after considering new conditions relating to his
health, including a stabilization of his physical condition. Korten
said the department also wanted to conclude the matter in a fair
and humane manner.
   ARC is a contagious condition that indicates a victim has been
exposed to the AIDS virus. ARC patients don't necessarily develop
AIDS, however.
</TEXT>
