<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RadarReaders     05-20 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Radar Readers,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Men Who Tracked Pearl Harbor Attack Gather For Reunion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE FITZHENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINTHICUM, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Japanese planes headed toward Pearl
Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941, Pfc. Joseph Lockhard tracked mysterious
blips on his radar screen on the island of Oahu.
   ``We picked up a huge indication on the scope of something. We
had no idea what it was,'' he said Friday. ``We didn't know if it
was a bird, Superman or a plane.''
   He and another young serviceman were alone in the radar room,
watching the pulsing signal move steadily toward the island.
   Lockhard relayed the information by telephone to a lieutenant,
who brushed aside the concerns of the 19-year-old Army Signal Corps
radarman, noting that it was probably a squadron of B-17s en route
from California.
   ``We continued to plot it and track it and called back again. I
was more insistent. But nothing was done,'' he said. ``We plotted
it to within 20 miles of the island, and at that point, the signal
became lost in the terrain.''
   Moments later, ``We had been attacked. You could see the smoke
rising. We immediately knew what we had seen.''
   About 3,700 American servicemen and civilians were killed in the
attack.
   Friday, Lockhard and other members of the Signal Company, Air
Warning, Hawaii, met in Baltimore for the first time in 47 years,
and a visit to the Historical Electronics Museum Inc. in this
suburb, where a model of the SCR-270 radar is on display. The
device was built by Westinghouse Defense in Baltimore.
   The SCR-270, which tracked the approach of the planes, was ``the
Model T of radar,'' said Lockhard, a retired project manager at AMP
Inc. in Harrisburg, Pa., a maker of electrical connections.
   ``Many people had faith in it, but there were also a lot of
doubting Thomases. A lot of military people looked on it as a
toy,'' he said. ``They didn't believe in it enough to believe it
was the valuable tool that it was.''
   Six radar units had been delivered to the island about three
months earlier, he said.
   ``It was a brand new animal,'' Lockhard said. ``We had no idea
it was an enemy attack, other than we thought something was wrong
with the equipment. I ran it through a series of checks.
   ``The feeling was more like incredulity. It was phenomenal. It's
one of the footnotes to history. You can play out all sorts of
`what if' games.
   ``The real value to the whole thing, I've always felt, was it
gave credibility to the equipment. Everybody recognized the
potential, where some didn't before.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
