<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SenateDisclosure 1stLd-Writethru a0735 05-20 0946</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate Disclosure, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Financially Well-Off Senators Talk Liberally, Invest
Conservatively</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 5th graf pvs, bgng: Although it, to change `likely' to
`possible' millionaires; SUBS grafs 7-8 pvs, Some other, with 1
graf to DELETE Boschwitz from list of millionaires and add others;
SUBS 11th graf pvs, Senators are, to clarify 1987 salary figure;
other minor editing throughout to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators gave the public a peek at their
personal finances Friday, disclosing a generally well-to-do group
that loves to talk for money, collects interesting gifts and leans
toward conservative investments.
   Release of the financial disclosure forms, required annually,
showed there are far more millionaires in the Senate than are found
in most other 100-member groups. Some, although not many, of the
senators are not doing nearly so well, including Joseph R. Biden
Jr., D-Del., the former presidential candidate, and Robert W.
Kasten, R-Wis.
   Biden's assets, not including the family home, total only
$21,000 and his liabilities are at least $260,000. But he earned
more than $110,000 last year, including his $87,483 Senate salary.
   Kasten reported assets of $21,000 to $45,000 and liabilities of
$20,000 to $30,000.
   Although it is possible that as many as three-dozen senators are
millionaires, it is difficult to determine real financial worth
from reading the disclosure reports. Senators are required to
report income, assets and liabilities only within a broad range;
for example, a $10 million investment need be reported only as
exceeding $250,000.
   On that basis, John D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va., the Standard Oil
heir who could be the Senate's richest member, is shown as having
assets of at least $882,000 and income of at least $390,000.
Another millionaire, Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., put no dollar
value on the trusts that make up the bulk of his wealth although he
reported income of at least $596,747. Kennedy has the type of
trusts whose worth are not subject to the disclosure law.
   Some other probable millionaires: John C. Danforth, R-Mo., a
member of the Ralston-Purina family; John Heinz, R-Pa., of the
ketchup-and-pickle family; Claiborne Pell, D-R.I.; Lowell Weicker,
R-Conn., of the Squibb drug fortune; Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas; John
Warner, R-Va.; Chic Hecht, R-Nev.; and Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.;
William Armstrong, R-Colo.; Alan Dixon, D-Ill.; John Stennis,
D-Miss.; and Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
   Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas won top honors in the
talk-for-pay category last year. He reported $106,050, mostly for
speechmaking, and gave $80,000 of it to charity. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., picked up $47,350 in honoraria, giving $12,500 to charity.
   Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., reported $37,350 in honoraria; David
Boren, D-Okla., $59,175, almost $30,000 of which was given to
charity; Tom Daschle, D-S.D., $60,450, including $23,450 given to
charity; and Sam Nunn, D-Ga., $50,500, of which $16,007 went to
charity.
   Senators are allowed to earn as much as they like by
speechmaking, but they cannot keep for their own use honoraria
exceeding 40 percent of their Senate salary. The salary reached its
current annual level of $89,500 in March, meaning that members
earned slightly less than that in 1987.
   Several senators picked up pocket change last year by writing
for newspapers and magazines. The New York Times' standard fee
appeared to be $100; the Los Angeles Times paid $150 or $200; USA
Today paid $150; the Christian Science Monitor paid $33.33. Gordon
Humphrey, R-N.H., pocketed $300 for an article in Conservative
Digest.
   A few listed among their honoraria fees for ``appearances'' _ no
writing or speaking, just appearing. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., was
paid $2,000 for an appearance before McDonnell Douglas aircraft
company in St. Louis. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., got $1,000 for an
appearance before the American Business Conference.
   Banking Committee Chairman William Proxmire, D-Wis., whose panel
oversees the securities industries, owns not one share of stock.
Like many colleagues, he favors tax-free municipal bonds; freshman
Robert Graham, D-Fla., a millionaire, laid out a list of
municipal-bond holdings that appeared to include an issue for every
hamlet in his home state.
   Senators consider banks a safe place to put their money.
Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., reported all his assets _
a maximum of $70,000 _ in bank accounts. The largest single
investment held by David Durenberger, R-Minn., outside his blind
trust was in a bank certificate of deposit.
   Senators visited the far reaches of the Earth last year, and in
many cases, a special-interest group of one kind or another picked
up the tab.
   Tom Harkin, D-Iowa., was reimbursed for travel to Hollywood to
give a $2,000 speech to the International Foundation for the
Conservation of Birds. Kasten and his wife, Eva Jean, went to
Santiago, Chile, at the expense of the U.N. Economic Commission for
Latin America. Daschle got $2,000 and expenses for speaking to the
Chamber of Commerce of Curacao.
   Among the gifts: Thad Cochran, R-Miss., got a framed
illustration of the Battle of Corinth; Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., a
$180 case of scotch; DeConcini, two clock radios and a Navajo rug;
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, a $150 ring to commemorate Texas A&M's Cotton
Bowl championship; Kent Conrad, D-N.D., World Series tickets valued
at $320 from baseball Commissioner Peter Ueberroth.
   Some other disclosures:
   _A dozen senators list zero liabilities.
   _Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., was paid an $800 advance for
his new book.
   _Paul Simon, D-Ill., a former candidate for president, was paid
$1,250 by Northwest Airlines for losing his luggage.
   _Armstrong, a millionaire, had no honoraria, no liabilities and
no gifts to report.
   _J. James Exon, D-Neb., spoke to the American Association of
Airport Executives in Waikowa, Hawaii. He was paid $1,000 plus $934
``mounting of fish for Mrs. Exon.''
   House members' disclosure forms will be released next Wednesday.
</TEXT>
