<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Greece     05-20 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Greece,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkey Rejects Negotiations With Greece For Full EEC Membership</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkey has rejected a West German proposal
that it negotiate with Greece in a move to improve Turkey's
association with the European Economic Community, Foreign Minister
Mesut Yilmaz said Friday.
   Turkey also said it will not discuss with Greece the dispute
over Cyprus, divided between Greek- and Turkish-Cypriot communities.
   Greece is a member of the European Economic Community, or Common
Market. Turkey has been an associate member since 1966 and a year
ago it applied for full membership.
   West German officials have told Turkey that an EEC meeting with
associate members cannot be convened before Germany's rotating
presidency of the organization ends June 30, Yilmaz said.
   Greece then will assume the presidency for six months.
   ``We were told that the future of the meeting depended upon
bilateral talks between Greece and Turkey,'' Yilmaz told reporters.
   Yilmaz will go to Athens Monday for talks with Greek officials
but he said neither Cyprus nor the EEC issue would be discussed.
   ``In our understanding the Cyprus problem is not a bilateral
issue even though it influences these relations,'' he said. ``Our
relations with the EEC is not a bilateral issue either. It is out
of the question that the matter will be raised in my talks in
Greece.''
   Monday's meeting in Athens will be the first of a Turkish-Greek
political committee established under a recent accord to improve
relations between the historic rivals.
   Another joint committee to consider cultural exchanges and
cooperation in trade and tourism will meet in Ankara Tuesday.
   The two committees were set up following a meeting in the Swiss
resort of Davos last January between prime ministers Turgut Ozal of
Turkey and Andreas Papandreou of Greece.
   But Greece maintains that the presence of Turkish soldiers on
Cyprus is a major obstacle fo improved bilateral relations and
Turkish links with the European Economic Community.
   Turkey insists that Cyprus is not part of the Davos
reconciliation and that dispute should be resolved under United
Nations sponsorship.
   Turkey invaded Cyprus in 1974 after Greek-Cypriot national guard
officers briefly seized control of the government in an effort to
make the island part of Greece. Northern Cyprus now is controlled
by Turkish Cypriots and the southern zone by Greek Cypriots.
</TEXT>
