<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CzechChurch     05-20 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czech Church,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Official Rejects Cardinal's Letter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior government official on
Friday dismissed a critical letter from a Roman Catholic leader as
too confrontational, an official report said.
   Deputy Premier Matej Lucan rejected the cardinal's letter at a
meeting of church dignitaries and cultural officials. He said the
letter ``adopts and authorizes opinions of those who actually try
to misuse the interests of believers and churches for political
purposes leading to pressure.''
   In the letter, dated April 23, Czechoslovak Catholic primate
Frantisek Tomasek demanded a new state policy toward religion. He
signaled Catholics were ready to fight for religious freedom.
   Relations between the Communist authorities and the church have
been strained over the government's refusal to allow any bishops to
be appointed in the last 15 years. The Vatican has refused to
accept candidates from the state-sponsored clergy association Pacem
in Terris.
   Half a million Catholics signed a petition organized by a
Catholic lay activist in December to demand more bishops, more
priests and an end to harassment for churchgoers.
   The cardinal, in the letter sent to Premier Lubomir Strougal,
said that force used by police to break up a peaceful demonstration
in Bratislava in March illustrated the need for a new policy of
dialogue.
   Tomasek said contacts between the state and church had reached a
state of crisis. He said that Catholics who ``are conscious of
their rights will demand them and are prepared to make sacrifices.''
   Lucan, however, responded that ``due to its confrontation
platform and tactless procedure, the letter cannot create a basis
for constructive relations, and the government is therefore forced
to reject it.''
   Lucan also complained that the letter was made available to the
Western media ``as background material for new attacks.''
   Authorities and the church recently reached agreement on the
appointment of two bishops to assist Tomasek and an apostolic
administrator for the Slovak diocese of Trnava.
   Still, 10 of the country's 13 bishops' posts remain vacant, a
situation the cardinal described as ``catastrophic.'' The three
bishops are all over 75.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
