<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Lehder 1stLd-Writethru a0835 05-20 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Lehder, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0835,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Justice Minister Says Lehder Sentence Must Be Limited To 30
Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, Lehder's seven-month ... CORRECTING number
of years from 350 to 150. Picks up 6th graf pvs, In an .. .</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Lehder, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. conviction of Colombian drug
trafficker Carlos Lehder Rivas received scant attention in
Colombia's press Friday with most papers concentrating on
Colombia's 3-1 soccer victory over Finland.
   None of Colombia's 20 daily newspapers ran editorial comment on
the case and several did not mention the case at all.
   No public demonstrations for or against the conviction were
reported. Indeed, the legal aspects of the case drew the most
attention.
   Former Justice Minister Felio Andrade said Friday that a
U.S.-Colombia treaty limits to 30 years the U.S. sentence that may
be imposed on convicted drug traffickers extradited from Colombia,
echoing a point that Lehder's lawyer tried to make in the United
States.
   Lehder's seven-month trial in U.S. District Court in
Jacksonville, Fla., ended Thursday when he was convicted of
smuggling 3.3 tons of cocaine and of related charges. He faces up
to life plus 150 years in prison and $350,000 in fines when he is
sentenced July 20.
   In an interview with the radio chain Caracol former Cabinet
member Andrade said, ``The Colombian government should make a case
in the U.S. courts to the effect that a Colombian citizen cannot be
sentenced ... to a term not encompassed by Colombian law.''
   The maximum sentence in Colombia is 30 years in prison.
   Another former justice minister, Jose Manuel Arias Carrizosa,
criticized the trial for using evidence from criminals trying to
get lighter sentences. However, Colombia's attorney general,
Horacio Serpa Uribe, said soon after the conviction that Lehder was
known to be involved in the drug trade.
   Colombian authorities captured Lehder on Feb. 4, 1987, and he
was extradited the same day.
   Lehder is the biggest Colombian drug trafficker ever convicted
in a U.S. court. He was identified as belonging to the Medellin
Cartel, a group of Colombians who control cocaine smuggling into
the United States.
   A 1979 treaty says no Colombian extradited to the United States
can be sentenced to more than the maximum penalty _ 30 years in
this case _ that the defendant would have faced in Colombia.
   After Lehder was extradited last year, Colombia's Supreme Court
ruled the extradition treaty unconstitutional on a technicality.
Lehder was the last of 15 people sent by Colombia to the United
States to face drug charges.
   The U.S. State Department insists that the treaty is valid.
   Former Minister Arias Carrizosa suggested in a broadcast
interview Friday with Caracol that Lehder did not get a fair trial
because much of the evidence against him came from criminals on the
lookout for reduced sentences for themselves.
   Serpa Uribe told reporters during an impromptu news conference
Thursday that Lehder's conviction did not surprise him since
``Lehder's link to drug trafficking was common knowledge.''
   While in Colombia, Lehder bragged publicly about being involved
in drug trafficking.
   Earlier this year in Tegucigalpa, the capital of Honduras,
thousands of people rioted to protest the extradition to the United
States of Juan Ramon Matta, accused of being a major drug smuggler.
</TEXT>
