<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Noriega 4thLd-Writethru a0831 05-20 0950</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Noriega, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0831,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US and Panamanian Negotiators Agree on a Noriega Deal</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf bgng, `The talks,' to UPDATE
with Noriega not commenting on reports of deal, saying there can be
no discussions without respect for the Panamanian president</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and Panamanian negotiators have
tentatively agreed on a deal that calls for Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega to leave Panama for nine months starting this August and
for the United States to drop drug smuggling indictments against
him, an administration official said Friday.
   The arrangement would give Noriega a role in setting up a
transition government before leaving, said the official, who has
followed the negotiations but insisted on anonymity.
   The agreement, subject to final approval by both governments,
allows Noriega to return to Panama for holidays and to go back
permanently after presidential elections set for May 1989, said the
official, who described himself as opposed to the arrangement.
   He said Vice President George Bush has expressed reservations.
   However, one of Noriega's criminal attorneys in Miami said
Friday night that no agreement has been reached.
   ``I've just talked to a high-ranking member of General Noriega's
staff in Panama City, and he denies that any deal has been
struck,'' Raymond Takiff said.
   Roman Popadiuk, deputy White House press secretary, also denied
that a tentative agreement had been reached.
   ``The talks have not broken down, nor has there been any
agreement,'' he said. ``The process still continues.''
   Noriega on Friday made no reference to the reports of a deal
when he addressed thousands of supporters in the San Miguelito
district outside the capital of Panama City.
   In response to questions from local officials about talks with
the United States, Noriega said any discussions must be based on
``respect for the president of the republic, Manuel Solis Palma.''
   ``There cannot be conversation, there cannot be a solution if an
exaggerated number of troops remain on our territory as
psychological aggression,'' Noriega said. ``Neither can there be
any solution as long as the popular forces and a militantly
recognized government are not part of it.''
   Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, said Friday that the vice
president opposes negotiating with Noriega over the conditions
under which Noriega might surrender power.
   ``The administration sources who have suggested that the vice
president favors ending the negotiations and bringing the envoy
back to Washington are essentially correct,'' Fuller said.
   Bush had lunch with President Reagan on Friday, but the vice
president's aides would not say whether they discussed the Noriega
negotiations.
   The official who discussed the tentative deal also said Bush has
recommended that the State Department recall deputy assistant
secretary Michael G. Kozak from Panama. Kozak has spent virtually
all of May in Panama trying to work out an agreement.
   The official who disclosed the tentative agreement to an
Associated Press reporter said, ``If it gets accepted, it gives
Noriega everything he wants.''
   The official said there were no assurances that Noriega was
negotiating seriously and he raised the possibility that the
defense chief has no intention of resigning his post, as the
agreement specifies.
   If the deal receives final approval, the official said Noriega
would be in a position to leave his associates in positions of
authority because he will be able to influence the formation of the
transition government.
   Late Friday, State Department spokesman Charles Redman said
Kozak was returning to Washington for consultations.
   He said Kozak's return does not mean any change in the process.
   ``The process continues,'' Redman said, declining further
comment.
   Associates of Noriega have said in recent weeks that Noriega
sees Aug. 12 as an appropriate time to resign because that is the
fifth anniversary of his accession as commander of the Defense
Forces.
   The State Department view is that dropping the indictments
against Noriega is a defensible bargaining position because he
cannot be extradited so long as he remains in Panama.
   It contends that if Noriega's price for leaving Panama is
dismissal of the indictments, this would be a low cost way of
resolving the 12-week old crisis, which has dropped U.S.-Panamanian
relations to a low point and produced economic collapse in Panama.
   According to a published report earlier this week, the United
States would reserve the right to reinstate the indictment once
Noriega returns to Panama.
   The Reagan administration has been calling on Noriega to step
down since the indictments were returned on Feb. 5.
   President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire Noriega on Feb. 25
but was ousted himself the following day by the pro-Noriega
National Assembly. The United States continues to recognize
Delvalle as the legitimate authority in Panama.
   A series of U.S. economic sanctions have contributed to Panama's
economic demise.
   U.S. apprehensions about Noriega were heightened on Thursday
when a pro-government newspaper published photographs of U.S.
Embassy employees and their families so that Panamanians will
``know the Gringos who are starving us to death.''
   The supplement in the newspaper Critica, a propaganda organ of
the government, said the Americans ``think the walls of their
embassy are impregnable.''
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the supplement
has been ``noted with concern'' and that appropriate security
measures have been taken.
   He declined to elaborate and refused to say whether any
Americans associated with the embassy are being evacuated.
   ``We have seen a pattern of harassment over a period of time in
Panama,'' Redman said. ``This appears to be part of that. The way
to deal with that is to continue to take the precautions that need
to be taken.''
   Redman had no comment on the negotiations. White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater also refused comment except to say they were
continuing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
