<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZeroTolerance 1stLd-Writethru   05-20 0604</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zero Tolerance, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0688,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard May Back Off Boat Seizure Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after fourth graf pvs, ``The Atlantis
....'' to UPDATE with details of agreement on returning Atlantis
II, crewman pleading guilty to drug charges; picks up 5th graf pvs,
``Privately, Customs ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The furor over expensive yachts confiscated for as
little as a single marijuana cigarette has led the Coast Guard to
review, but not abandon, the ``zero tolerance'' anti-drug policy.
   Civil libertarians have attacked the seizures as
unconstitutional, arguing searches are often illegal and owners are
being punished for something done by others.
   U.S. Customs Service Commissioner William Von Raab said Friday
the Atlantis II, which explored the wreck of the Titanic, was the
latest confiscated vessel to be returned to its owners. The ship
was seized in San Diego when a crewman was found with a small
amount of marijuana.
   ``The Atlantis II is being given back because the owners were
perfectly innocent, and they're actually shocked because they were
trying to improve their security,'' said Von Raab.
   The crewman pleaded guilty Thursday to misdemeanor drug
possession and was sentenced to a year of unsupervised probation
and fined $100, said Mike Fleming, a Los Angeles-based Customs
spokesman.
   Under an agreement reached Friday, the Atlantis II will resume
scientific expeditions technically under Customs' control while its
owner, the Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution of Massachusetts,
petitions the seizure, he said.
   Privately, Customs officials have expressed anger at the Coast
Guard's highly publicized aggressive seizures of boats.
   ``They are destroying the program,'' said one Florida Customs
official who spoke on condition of anonymnity.
   In Florida, the Coast Guard boarded and confiscated the $2.5
million Ark Royal, as well as the Monkey Business, notorious as the
Bahamas vacation boat of Gary Hart and Donna Rice and their
friends. Both yachts carried only minute amounts of drugs.
   Under zero tolerance, the Coast Guard is supposed to turn over
all vessels seized for drugs to Customs.
   But Customs refused to take custody of the Monkey Business
because officials felt the search was poorly done. That yacht had
to be returned to its owners by the Coast Guard without fines or
penalties.
   The Coast Guard has now agreed to take another look at such
seizures.
   Specific changes will be implemented ``within a couple of
weeks,'' Capt. John C. Trainor, who heads the Coast Guard's
enforcement division, said Thursday.
   ``We realized that, although the owner is responsible for that
boat, there had to be some reasonableness to it,'' Trainor said.
``We're not in the business of harassing boaters, and we're not in
the business of seizing boats,'' he said.
   Among changes being considered are delaying seizures of charter
vessels until after the boats return to port and drop off their
passengers, employing ``technical seizures'' that allow owners to
keep their vessels while they argue against forfeiture, and
educating Coast Guard officers on exemptions in the zero tolerance
policy.
   But Trainor said the changes don't mean the Coast Guard is
abandoning enforcement of the policy.
   ``We are part of the national effort to stamp out drugs in this
country,'' Trainor said. ``We're holding everybody accountable for
his own actions.''
   The American Civil Liberties Union is conducting a review of its
own, said attorney Barbara Levinson.
   ``From reports I've heard, Coast Guard officers are jumping on
board and not bothering to check safety _ they're going right to a
search. That means people's billfolds, that means drawers, that
means closets,'' she said. ``The search of every nook and cranny
when there's no reasonable cause _ that violates people's
constitutional rights.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
