<HEAD>Soviet Withdrawal Negotiator Named To Key Ecuador Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. Undersecretary-General Diego
Cordovez, the diplomat who helped negotiate the Soviet withdrawal
from Afghanistan, was named Ecuador's next foreign minister on
Friday by President-elect Rodrigo Borja.
   Borja told reporters that Cordovez had accepted the Cabinet post
and would take up his new position when Borja takes office in
August. Cordovez, 52, has served since 1981 as the U.N. official in
charge of special political matters.
   Borja, of the Democratic Left Party, was elected president on
May 8. He said one of Cordovez's first jobs will be to help restore
diplomatic relations with Nicaragua.
   Outgoing President Leon Febres Cordero, a conservative, cut ties
with Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government in late 1985
following an argument with President Daniel Ortega.
   Cordovez has served at the United Nations since 1963.
   ``The management of international policy could not be in better
hands,'' Borja said of the diplomat.
   Cordovez arrived Thursday night in Quito to discuss the offer.
