<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-20 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Severe Storms Precede Cold Front in Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A western cold front spawned thunderstorms, high winds and hail
over most of the Great Plains and central United States Friday,
while the rain-saturated East Coast got still more precipitation.
   Severe thunderstorms blanketed the Great Plains, with clusters
of showers over central Texas, northern Oklahoma and southern
Kansas, as well as eastern Nebraska to southwest Minnesota.
   Residents in Hobbs, N.M., reported seeing two tornadoes touch
down Friday. One twister tore part of the roof and a side from a
building, uprooted trees, knocked down telephone poles and
overturned a pickup truck, slightly injuring the driver. The second
tornado destroyed an unoccupied mobile home, and tore off parts of
the roofs of two houses, a witness said.
   The storm system brought golf ball-sized hail at Hunt and
Kerrville, Texas, and marble-sized hail near El Dorado, Kan.
   Showers over the central High Plains and southern and central
Rockies were accompanied by blustery north winds gusting to 40 mph,
sending the mercury plunging into the 40s and 50s.
   Rain and drizzly weather continued in the Northeast, with severe
storms stretching from Maryland to eastern North Carolina during
the afternoon and evening.
   In Pennsylvania, where 8 inches of rain have fallen in parts of
the state since Monday, a 16-year-old youth drowned Thursday night
while rafting with some friends on a rain-swollen creek in
Fayetteville, state police said.
   The heavy rains have caused creeks and streams to overflow, as
well as minor flooding in low-lying areas.
   Southwestern and eastern Pennsylvania, parts of eastern New York
state, northern and western New Jersey, northern Delaware, northern
and central Maryland, northern Virginia and the eastern Panhandle
of West Virginia had all issued flood watches through the evening.
   Sunny skies prevailed west of the Rockies and in the Southeast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Limon, Colo., to 100 at Palm Springs, Calif. The morning
low for the nation was 19 degrees in West Yellowstone, Mont.
   Saturday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms
stretching from New England to the upper Ohio Valley, Virginia and
eastern North Carolina and from the southern Plains throughout the
central Plains and the lower Missouri Valley to the upper
Mississippi Valley, with rain heaviest over Oklahoma and northwest
Texas. Sunny skies were predicted for the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures should remain below 70 in the central High
Plains and the central Rockies, with highs only in the 50s in
eastern Colorado and southeastern Wyoming, and in the 60s in
northern Minnesota, as well as southern and eastern New England.
Highs should rise into the 80s west of the Rockies and in the South
Atlantic Coast, reaching into the 90s from southern Arizona through
southern Nevada and western California into southwestern Oregon,
topping 100 in desert areas of California and Arizona.
</TEXT>
