<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WorldBank-Interest     05-20 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-World Bank-Interest,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Are Asked to Waive Debtor Countries' Interest Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank suggested Friday that
commercial banks in the United States and other countries
voluntarily give up $5 billion to $6 billion of interest owed them
by 17 heavily indebted countries.
   In a special report, the bank, which is owned by 151
governments, said interest waivers of about two percentage points
on the debt owed by the so-called ``middle income countries'' would
generate the same financial relief in the first year as a $5
billion to $6 billion loan.
   The ``middle income countries'' in question are Argentina,
Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Costa Rica, Ecuador, Ivory Coast,
Jamaica, Mexico, Morocco, Nigeria, Peru, Philippines, Uruguay,
Venezuela and Yugoslavia. They have foreign debts of about $500
billion.
   The 42-page report, ``The World Bank and the Heavily Indebted
Middle-Income Countries,'' did not say how long the waivers should
be continued.
   The same suggestion was made privately last month by Barber B.
Conable, the bank's president, to representatives of member
countries.
   Conable and government financial leaders including Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III, have criticized commercial banks for
not lending more.
   The commercial banks, meanwhile, say governments and
intergovernmental bodies like the World Bank and its sister body,
the International Monetary Fund, should do more lending.
   The report said governments of borrowing countries are reluctant
to borrow more without some relief. They complain they are already
paying out $30 billion a year to more prosperous countries, mostly
on old debt.
   ``In many of these countries, per capita income and consumption
have fallen considerably over the past five years and are for some
countries back to levels that were already attained in the early
1960s,'' according to the report.
   The average Argentine earned $2,350 in 1986, compared with $160
for the average Nepalese, $17,840 for the average Swiss and $17,500
for the average American, according to the World Bank's figures.
   The report cites Mexico, where 700,000 teen-agers reach working
age every year and few jobs have been created since 1981.
Unemployment in Mexico increased by 70 percent between 1981 and
1984, it says.
   The World Bank is the largest source of aid money to nearly 120
countries, lending about $17 billion annually. That figure is
expected to increase to more than $20 billion in the 1990s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
