<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JetLeak 1stLd-Writethru a0751 05-20 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jet Leak, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0751,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Flight Developed Leak, Made Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The flight...' to UPDATE with number of
passengers aboard; picks up 4th graf pvs, `The pilot...' Industrie
cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2-week-old American Airlines jet made
an emergency landing in Bermuda last week after a leak spewed fuel
into the Atlantic Ocean, officials said Friday.
   No injuries were reported when the twin-engine jet, a wide-body
Airbus A300-600R, landed with one engine operating after losing
fuel through a crack in the right engine, American spokesman Steve
McGregor said.
   The flight was en route to San Juan, Puerto Rico, from New
York's John F. Kennedy Airport with 90 passengers aboard on May 10,
when a fuel pump split in the right engine, he said.
   The pilot tried to stop fuel flowing to the damaged pump, but
the shut-off valve was beyond the crack. He then released
fire-extinguisher bottles in the engine to shut it down and
diverted to Bermuda, McGregor said.
   He said the jet did not run out of fuel and added that
authorities have not determined the cause of the split.
   After the incident, repairmen from General Electric _ which
manufactures the plane's engines _ flew people to Bermuda to fix
the pump, said David Venz, spokesman for Airbus Industrie of North
America Inc. of Herndon, Va.
   The plane was then flown back to New York and put back into
service the next day, McGregor said.
   Venz said the 267-person-capacity jet, designed so it can
operate on just one engine if necessary, was delivered to American
two weeks prior to the incident.
</TEXT>
