<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Egypt,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Palestinians, Israel Must Be Considered in Peace
Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev told Egypt's foreign minister
Friday that any Middle East peace settlement has to take both
Palestinian and Israeli interests into account.
   The Soviet leader reiterated in his talks with Foreign Minister
Esmat Abdel-Meguid the comments he made at a meeting last month
with Palestine Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat.
   ``Without the PLO's involvement the process of a settlement will
not go forward,'' Gorbachev said according to a report published by
the official Tass news agency.
   ``But it is no less important to take account of the interests
of other sides, namely Syria, Jordan and Israel,'' Tass quoted him
as saying. ``The present situation opens up opportunities to
convene an international conference under the U.N. aegis. These
opportunities should not be missed.''
   Gorbachev offered much the same formula at his April 9 meeting
with Arafat.
   The Soviet Union broke ties with Israel after the 1967
Arab-Israeli war but recently has moved to improve relations with
the Jewish state.
