<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Noriega 1stLd-Writethru a0851 05-20 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Noriega, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0851,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Says No Talks With U.S. If `Aggression Continues'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 8 grafs of detail from rally and paramilitary exercise.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN MIGUELITO, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Military leader Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega said Friday that talks between Panama and the United States
cannot be held ``if the aggression continues.''
   Noriega told thousands of supporters in the San Miguelito
district outside the capital that: ``There cannot be conversation
if aggression continues, aggression at whatever level, whatever
magnitude, whether it be psychological or economic aggression.''
   He made no reference to reports in Washington that U.S. and
Panamanian negotiators have tentatively agreed on a deal calling
for Noriega to leave Panama in August and stay away until May 1989
when presidential elections will be held.
   A Reagan administration official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, told reporters that in return for Noriega's departure,
the United States would agree to drop federal drug smuggling
charges against him and give him a role in setting up a
transitional government.
   The agreement, subject to final approval by both governments,
allows Noriega to return to Panama for holidays and to go back
permanently after the presidential elections, the official said.
   Noriega, in response to questions from local officials about
talks with the United States, said any discussions must be based on
``respect for the president of the republic, Manuel Solis Palma.''
   ``There cannot be conversation, there cannot be a solution if an
exaggerated number of troops remain on our territory as
psychological aggression,'' he said.
   ``Neither can there be any solution as long as the popular
forces and a militantly recognized government are not part of it,''
he said at the inauguration of a grandstand at a sports complex in
San Miguelito.
   Noriega, as head of the 15,000-member Panamanian Defense Forces,
is the power behind the civilian government.
   The Reagan administration has imposed sweeping economic
sanctions against the country in an effort to force Noriega's
ouster.
   The United States still recognizes Eric Arturo Delvalle, who has
been in hiding, as Panama's legitimate president. Noriega allies in
the National Assembly dismissed him Feb. 26, the day after Delvalle
tried to fire Noriega.
   There are about 10,000 U.S. military personnel stationed at 10
installations in Panama.
   Noriega said Panama is a democratic country but it is a
democracy, ``without the U.S.A. label, democracy with the
Panamanian tricolor, with the taste of Panamanian soup and with the
tone and the tune of the little drum.''
   Arrayed on the field before Noriega were hundreds of members of
so-called Dignity Battalions. The volunteer battalions have been
formed to confront what the Noriega-controlled government says is
the danger of a U.S. invasion.
   About 30 volunteers, clad in T-shirts and blue jeans and
carrying World War II-era rifles, ran through an obstacle course,
then jabbed or battered a dummy dressed in olive green as a
demonstration of their training.
   ``San Miguelito will be the tomb of Yankee imperialism,'' said
an announcer through loudspeakers as the volunteers went through
their paces.
   Noriega said the militias would fight any invaders.
   ``Those powerful ones who think they can come to this territory
without getting a whipping are mistaken,'' he said.
   The master of ceremonies who introduced the general addressed
himself to the foreign journalists gathered below him.
   ``If there is an invasion, you won't be filming Panamanian
cadavers, but the cadavers of North American soldiers that we will
send home to North American mothers,'' he said.
   Noriega concluded the list of conditions for a U.S.-Panama
solution by saying, ``If I have said nothing, it is because I know
them (the Americans), and because I know them, I remain silent.''
</TEXT>
