<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Denmark-Politics     05-20 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Denmark-Politics,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Prime Minister Gets New Crack at Forming Coalition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Acting Prime Minister Poul Schlueter
won approval Friday to form a new government after two other
leaders failed during a political crisis over NATO and the
country's ban on nuclear weapons.
   Schleuter had hoped for a clear mandate from May 10
parliamentary elections for full Danish participation in NATO and
against a stronger anti-nuclear ban.
   However, Schlueter's center-right coalition merely kept its 70
seats in the 179-member legislature. The two-party socialist
opposition lost ground but still holds 79 seats, making it
difficult for Schlueter to form a new government.
   Schleuter, now caretaker prime minister, was asked to try to
form a new government by Queen Margrethe II.
   ``It's a hard task and far from certain that I will succeed,''
said Schlueter on Friday.
   The socialist opposition pushed a resolution through Parliament
April 14 calling on Schlueter's government to notify each visiting
warship of Denmark's longstanding peacetime ban on nuclear weapons.
   
   Schleuter said he hoped a new government would be in place for
the opening of Parliament on Thursday.
   The non-partisan chairman of Parliament and the leader of the
centrist Social-Liberal Party both failed to forge a ruling
coalition among the eight parties elected to the legislature on May
10.
