<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SierraLeone-Arrests     05-20 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sierra Leone-Arrests,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Servants, Bankers Arrested For Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday arrested 20
senior civil servants and commercial banking officials on fraud
charges.
   It was the biggest sweep since President Joseph Momoh declared a
state of public economic emergency last November.
   Most of the 20 were in custody Friday night and officials said
they would be formally charged in High Court.
   Officials said the charges mainly involve forged government
documents which led to the payment of millions of leones, the local
currency. One dollar is worth about 27.5 leones. No details were
given of the alleged criminal actions. Among those arrested were
Peter Kuyembeh, the financial secretary in the Finance Ministry;
his deputy, Henry Ngongor; the Central Bank deputy director, Mrs.
Damaris Faux, and Christie Greene, a former minister of state in
the Finance Ministry, officials said.
</TEXT>
