<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WrongBodies     05-20 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wrong Bodies,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family Horrified to Find Their Loved One Cremated by Mistake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Eagan family was horrified when they
saw a stranger in the casket at a Hamden funeral home and found out
that the man they came to mourn had been cremated by mistake, a
newspaper reported Friday.
   Thomas P. Eagan, 68, of North Haven, died May 9, as did William
J. Gormley, 73, of East Haven. Both men were taken first to the
morgue at Yale-New Haven Hospital and then to separate branches of
Sisk Brothers funeral homes in New Haven and Hamden, a town about 8
miles to the north, the New Haven Register reported.
   Eagan was to have been buried May 13 but instead was cremated.
Gormley was to have been cremated, but his body appeared dressed in
Eagan's suit in an open coffin May 12 during calling hours at the
funeral home in Hamden, according to the newspaper.
   The Eagans Thursday filed a complaint against the funeral home
with the state Department of Health Services and has hired an
investigator to find out who made the error, the newspaper reported.
   ``There had to be an extremely large number of mistakes made in
order for this to have happened,'' Thomas P. Eagan Jr. of North
Branford, one of Eagan's three sons, was quoted as saying.
   ``I would never want another family to have to go through this.''
   Patrick Sisk, one of the funeral home's owners, blamed Yale-New
Haven Hospital and said his attorney was preparing to file a
complaint against the hospital, the newspaper reported.
   ``The tags were wrong,'' he was quoted as saying. ``They
released the wrong bodies to us.''
   But Thomas Urtz, a hospital spokesman, said Friday that the
mixup had to have occurred at the funeral home.
   ``One was taken to the morgue five hours before the other man
arrived in the emergency room. These individuals went to the morgue
properly tagged and were properly identified,'' he said.
   A state medical examiner, Audrey Goldstein, had signed a
certificate which had allowed Eagan's unintended cremation, the
newspaper reported.
   Gormley's daughter-in-law, Karen Gormley, was quoted by the
newspaper as saying that the funeral home did not tell her family
what had happened and only asked that a relative identify Gormley's
body on May 13.
   Karen Gormley said her husband found it strange that Gormley's
body was dressed in a stranger's suit. ``We didn't know where the
suit came from. No one had sent it,'' she was quoted as saying.
   The Eagans' attorney, Thomas W. Boyce Jr., said Thursday he did
not know who was responsible for the mistake but filed a complaint
against the funeral home because ``they're the ones that ultimately
made the arrangements.''
   Eagan's cremated remains were placed in a casket on May 13 by
Keenan Funeral Home, which replaced Sisk brothers at the family's
request, and were buried after a funeral mass, the newspaper
reported.
   Gormley was cremated and a memorial service for him was held at
Sisk Brothers, the newspaper reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
