<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shooting-Hospital, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0765,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Evanston Hospital, Staff Scrambles To Help Young Shooting
Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-School Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st and 2nd graf to ADD detail; ADDS 11th graf, `Police
stormed...' to UPDATE suspect is dead. Moves up 10th graf, pvs: `It
was like...' to 9th graf. </NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital worker winced and shut his eyes
at the pain of a young, bloodied shooting victim in Evanston
Hospital's emergency room, as the little victims of a schoolhouse
shooting began arriving Friday.
   ``It was a big trauma. Everybody was running around,'' said
Adrian Hatter, a supply technician who was in the emergency room
when ambulance drivers said they were coming from the school in
Winnetka with four children, victims of the shooting. Both cities
are affluent northern suburbs of Chicago.
   ``It kind of affected me because I've got kids of my own,''
Hatter, 26, said.
   He said he was especially moved by a young blonde girl who was
shot in the wrist and chest.
   ``She looked like she was fighting for her life; she was rolling
back and forth on the cart,'' Hatter said. ``I had to close my eyes
a couple times and listen for my next orders.''
   Parents of the wounded children were secluded in a room to await
word and to avoid reporters.
   ``In view of these circumstances, they are doing remarkably
well,'' Dr. David Winchester, a surgeon who operated on some of the
children, said of the parents.
   The four children _ Mark Tebourek, 8, Robert Trossman, 6,
Lindsay Fisher, 8, and Kathryn Miller, 7 _ were in critical
condition with neck and chest wounds, said hospital spokeswoman
Cheryl Soohoo.
   ``It was like a zoo,'' said Tyrone Harris, 31, a nursing
assistant at Evanston Hospital. ``At first, people were running
everywhere. We had regular cases scheduled but we had to cancel
them to make room for the patients who came in from the shooting.''
   Police said a woman armed with at least three guns walked into
the Hubbard Woods Elementary School. Two other children were rushed
to Highland Park Hospital where one 8-year-old boy died. A seventh
person was shot at a home were the woman fled from the school.
   Police stormed the Winnetka house Friday evening and found the
woman, identified as Lori Dann, dead of a single gunshot wound to
the head.
</TEXT>
