<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0855 05-20 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0855,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Talks Falter Between Sandinistas And Contras; New Date
Set</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with government comment on
date, radio interview put off at government request. PICKS up 6th
graf, `The Sandinista ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S-backed Contras agreed Friday
to Nicaragua's proposed dates for the next round of peace talks,
but the two sides suggested different sites.
   Jorge Rosales, spokesman for the Nicaraguan Resistance, said in
a phone interview from Miami that leaders of the Contra rebels will
attend two days of peace talks beginning Wednesday, as the
government has proposed.
   He said the rebel leaders will arrive for talks at the border
town of Sapoa, where the agreement was reached in March for a
60-day cease-fire lasting until May 30.
   But Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco said in a note to
the rebels that the talks must be held in Managua.
   To hold the discussions outside of the capital, he said, ``is to
go back in the advances that, with great difficulties, have been
achieved'' in the cease-fire talks.
   Tinoco said earlier that the rebels had not yet responded to a
government proposal to extend the cease-fire one month past the May
30 deadline.
   The Interior Ministry, meanwhile, ordered Radio Catolica to pull
off the air until Tuesday a news program that carried an interview
with a rebel chief, according to Auxiliadora Echegoyen, director of
the program.
   She said the suspension notice cited ``an interview which we
transmitted with a rebel chief, whose pseudonym is Tigrillo, and
which we monitored from another radio.''
   She did not say which station had originally carried the
interview.
   The Interior Ministry said in a statement that the station
should have cleared the interview with the government.
   Radio Catolica, which is operated by the Roman Catholic Church,
was one of three privately owned radio stations barred from
broadcasting news programs earlier this month because it reported a
workers' strike.
   The Sandinista government and the Contras have been blaiming
each other for the faltering peace plan to end more than six years
of war.
   Almost two months after the two sides signed the pact, they
agree only on the desire to end the fighting. The government has
warned it will stage the largest offensive to date if the
cease-fire is not extended after May 30 or if no progress is made.
   The Contras, meanwhile, are suffering from infighting, a move
that favors the ruling Sandinistas. From the government's point of
view, the best way for the war to end would be for the enemy to
self-destruct.
   Pro-Sandinista newspapers were giving widespread coverage to the
Contra bickering.
   The problems surrounding the cease-fire plan appear to have
started almost immediately after the March 23 signing. If all had
gone according to plan, the war would just about be over and
Nicaragua would be well on its way to full democracy.
   Because the cease-fire plan has not moved forward, the
Sandinistas have not freed more than 3,000 political prisoners nor
permitted the Contras to have a say in internal politics.
   Talks with the internal opposition political parties stand at an
impasse. The meetings were suspended by the opposition as a show of
support for the strikers. The government responded by saying it
would consider whether future talks would be held.
   According to the cease-fire plan, the first measures should have
been completed by April 15. In exchange, the Contra rebels would
have gathered in agreed upon cease-fire zones and been permitted to
receive humanitarian aid through a neutral organization.
   The Sandinistas have said the insurgents could now receive food,
medicine and clothes distributed by the International Red Cross.
But the Contras rejected that, saying the organization sympathizes
with the government.
   Meanwhile, sources said thousands of rebel troops moved toward
the northern border. The U.S. Agency for International Development
is providing supplies to the Contras through Honduras.
   A group of rebellious Contras has demanded the ouster of the top
Contra military officer, Col. Enrique Bermudez, a former officer
under the ousted dictator Anastasio Somoza.
   Matamoros, the Contras' main spokesman, said recently the talk
of divisions was exaggerated.
   Nicaraguan Vice President Sergio Ramirez said Sunday that the
Contra infighting puts into doubt future cease-fire negotiations.
   ``In Honduras the mercenary forces (the Contras) are on the
verge of civil war,'' he said. ``The political heads that come here
to negotiate have very little influence.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
