<DOCNO> AP880520-0282 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1725EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:ApartheidFilm Adv25   05-20 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Apartheid Film, Adv 25,0662</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, May 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Play Becomes a Movie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If it bombed in Pretoria, will it play in
Peoria? Paul Slabolepszy hopes so.
   At one theater in South Africa, the entire audience walked out
on Slabolepszy's new anti-apartheid film, ``Saturday Night at the
Palace.'' Now he's looking for a more sympathetic crowd in the
United States.
   ``People couldn't take it,'' Slabolepszy said of the movie's
South African run. ``It's kind of like showing a movie of someone
dying of lung cancer to an audience who are all heavy smokers. It's
so real and so close.''
   The movie is based on a real event _ a rampage by two white men
at a black-run roadhouse on the outskirts of Johannesburg. It was
made into a play that ran in South Africa and Europe.
   Slabolepszy, 40, who wrote the successful play on which the film
is based, plays Vince, a white racist who winds up at a diner late
one night with his nerd of a roommate, Forsie. The black manager of
the roadhouse, played by Tony Award-winning actor John Kani, is
just closing up for the night.
   Forsie wants only to use the telephone, but Vince demands that
the manager, whose name is September, reopen for business. In a
scene that encompasses the last half of the movie, an increasingly
ugly confrontation pits the characters, in shifting allegiances,
against one another.
   The movie, produced and directed by South African Robert Davies,
is a catharsis of sorts for Slabolepszy, who based Vince's
character _ loud, abusive, violent _ on some of the people with
whom he grew up in a small South African town. The son of Polish
immigrants, he moved to South Africa when he was 3 years old.
   ``I grew up in a kind of white racist area _ the attitudes were
very deep,'' he said in a recent interview. ``And when I went to
college (University of Cape Town) ... I was studying alongside
blacks and meeting them socially, and it was a stunning
transformation. Because all of the prejudices I'd grown up with
suddenly melted away, and I realized I'd been living in the middle
of this kind of lie.
   ``I can't watch the movie,'' he said. ``I just slide down in my
seat and I'm praying for someone to get rid of this guy (Vince).
It's just too much _ it assaults and assaults and assaults. But in
a way it's a story that has to be told.''
   At one point in the film, Vince, the unemployed roustabout,
delivers a monologue that frames the movie's political message.
   Enraged at the stubborn gentility of September, he roars,
``Who's he to be in charge of a roadhouse when I'm out of work?
Everywhere you go, all you see is black faces. Bus drivers, bank
tellers _ bloody three-piece suits, man!''
   Apartheid, says Slabolepszy, ``comes from the soul of that kind
of character. It comes from fear _ it's a fear of being swamped.''
   ``This character, Vince, has, I think, the central line of the
(film) when he says, `My old man said if you let a black man get
the better of you, that's the end, you're finished; there's no
going back.' That's his belief.''
   This is a heady time for Slabolepszy and others in South
Africa's artistic community. A series of hit plays have emerged
from Johannesburg _ ``Master Harold ... and the Boys,''
``Sarafina,'' ``Woza Albert,'' among others. South African music
has become an international rage and there is an emergence of black
South African art and literature.
   ``History is happening,'' said Slabolepszy, who yearns to
someday ``make a picture of hope.'' Perhaps, he muses, there will
be a ``happy accident'' in South Africa. In the meantime, he finds
his drama in turmoil.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
