<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1852EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv23   05-20 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 23,0797</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday May 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>Short Sellers, `Bear Raiders' New Subject of Post-Crash Concern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the search for stock saboteurs and
bear-market villains hiding in the aftermath of the October crash,
a new group of suspects has emerged _ the short sellers, investors
who bet money that prices will drop.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission and New York Stock
Exchange have quietly been probing allegations that improper short
selling may have contributed to the crash, though evidence of
wrongdoing hasn't yet emerged.
   The National Association of Securities Dealers, which runs the
over-the-counter market, is considering whether to implement
restrictions on short selling.
   In addition, several companies have raised a post-crash clamor
about alleged manipulation of their stock by users of the trading
tactic. The head of one such company, Urgent Care Health Systems
Inc., is co-sponsoring a conference Monday on short selling, titled
``Is Anyone Really Safe?''
   Short selling in itself isn't a crime. In theory, short sellers
sell borrowed stock they believe is overvalued, on the hunch the
price will decline. Potential profits can be immense.
   For example, if a short seller borrows 100 shares at $1 a share
and sells them, he earns $100 and uses the money as collateral for
the borrowed shares. If the stock drops to 50 cents a share, the
short seller buys 100 shares, returns the borrowed stock and
pockets $50.
   Defenders of short selling argue that it injects liquidity into
the market and helps all investors more accurately determine
whether a touted stock is worth buying or not.
   ``Selling short enables market participants to adjust positions
and causes stock to be more responsive,'' said Peter J. DaPuzzo,
head of retail equities at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
``I think short selling has a lot of positive attributes.''
   Critics say short selling can be disastrous to fledgling
companies trying to raise capital, especially in the post-crash
environment when so many investors already are avoiding the stock
market.
   ``There's nothing illegal about selling short if you think a
company is going to be in decline. What's bad is when people
deliberately circulate adverse information that may be false for
the purpose of causing a stock to go down,'' said A.A. Sommer, a
former SEC commissioner and securities lawyer in the Washington,
D.C., law firm of Morgan, Lewis & Bockius.
   Foes of short selling often recall how the strategy was widely
abused after Crash of 1929, when it played a central role in the
``Bear Raids'' in which speculators would relentlessly gang up on a
target company, spreading lies about it to drive down the stock
price.
   Such abuses led the NYSE to implement the short-sale rule, also
known as the uptick rule, which theoretically prevents short
sellers from mercilessly depressing a stock price.
   Under the rule, a short sale may be executed only if the
previous sale moved the stock up at least [ point, or one ``tick.''
But there are strategies for sidestepping this rule, and a debate
has intensified on whether it works.
   Moreover, the stocks most susceptible to short-selling assaults
haven't been protected by the uptick rule, since they are usually
small, over-the-counter issues such as upstart high-technology or
research concerns.
   These stocks soared in value in the 1982-87 bull market and
became visible targets for short sellers.
   In the case of Occupational Urgent Health Care Systems, for
example, founder James Cameron has contended that short sellers
tried to destroy his company by spreading vicious rumors about its
management.
   The stock of Carrington Laboratories, a drug firm working on a
substance that could advance treatment for AIDS, sank after false
rumors surfaced that the company was prohibited from testing in the
United States. Carrington's management claims short sellers spread
the rumors.
   Still, many investment professionals believe the argument
against short selling isn't persuasive and that further regulation
would make U.S. stock markets less attractive.
   ``We're not going to try to defend anybody who lies about a
company to knock its stock down. That's wrong,'' said Michael
Murphy, a short-selling strategist who publishes the Overpriced
Stock Service Newsletter. ``But 98 percent of the effort in the
securities business is aimed at touting stocks. There's far, far
more lying pushing stocks up then pushing them down.''
   The real effect of short sellers, Murphy argues, is to expose
companies that have serious deficiencies.
   ``People say short selling is un-American. But it's the reason
America has the best capital market in the world,'' Murphy said.
``You need to get a lot of opinions into the market.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday May 23</NOTE>
