<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-20 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0523</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers are accusing the authors of a White
House report on financial markets of ignoring the exchanges' wildly
swerving behavior and the resulting flight of small investors from
Wall Street.
   But the top-level federal officials who conducted the study
defended their recommendations Thursday and insisted the economic
forces responsible for the market volatility of recent months are
beyond government control.
   The officials recommended instituting a ``circuit breaker'' to
temporarily halt trading on the nation's stock, futures and options
exchanges should the Dow Jones industrial average fall by 250
points in a single day.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee unanimously has
approved legislation requiring lenders to make full disclosure on
home equity loans.
   The bill, approved Thursday, also is designed to put an end to
the use of unfair contract provisions and misleading advertisements.
   Under the bill, banks and credit unions would be required to
disclose important information about the terms and conditions of a
loan, such as the various repayment options.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A number of senators have renewed the
government's pledge to stand behind deposits in the nation's
savings and loan institutions, after a congressional agency
reported the doubling of the deficit in the federal S&L insurance
fund.
   Frederick D. Wolf, director of the accounting and financial
management division of the General Accounting Office, said Thursday
that the liabilities of the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance
Corp. exceeded its assets by $13.7 billion at the end of 1987, up
from the $6.3 billion deficit a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush may be getting valuable
election-year help from Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III,
according to some economists who suggest Baker has been leaning on
U.S. allies to maintain Bush's most valuable campaign asset, the
65-month economic recovery.
   The Treasury Department wouldn't comment Thursday on such
speculation. But the economists point to recent activity in
international markets to bolster their contention.
   The activity includes intervention in currency markets by other
nations' central banks and heavy foreign purchases of U.S. Treasury
securities.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conference of leading industrial nations ended
after the United States failed to persuade European governments to
accept its proposal for ending public aid to farmers by the year
2000.
   But trade and finance ministers from the 24 members of the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development promised
Thursday they would work together to reform global farm trading
rules.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flamboyant financier Paul Bilzerian, now
chairman of Singer Co., is the target of major Securities and
Exchange Commission and federal grand jury investigations for
possibly violating a litany of securities laws, according to
published reports.
   The Wall Street Journal said Thursday that documents it obtained
and interviews conducted with business associates show Bilzerian
may have engaged in insider trading, tax fraud, filing false
documents with the SEC and ``parking'' stock in accounts that
conceal its ownership.
   Bilzerian had no comment on the report.
</TEXT>
