<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PaylessCashways Bjt   05-20 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Payless Cashways, Bjt,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Edelman, Lumber Company Acquire Stake in Payless Cashways</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Payless Cashways Inc. says takeover strategist
Asher B. Edelman and his partners _ who control 7.6 percent of the
building materials retailer and may make a takeover offer _ have
``nothing to contribute to this company.''
   Edelman and Sutherland Lumber-Southwest Inc. of Kansas City,
Mo., disclosed Thursday they had bought about 2.56 million shares
of Payless, the nation's third-largest building materials retailer.
   With about 33.66 million shares outstanding, Kansas City-based
Payless has a market value of about $728 million based on
Thursday's closing price.
   Payless stock rose $1.37{ a share to close at $21.62{ in New
York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   The Edelman-Sutherland holdings were disclosed in a Securities
and Exchange Commission filing.
   Perry Sutherland, one of the family members who runs
privately-held Sutherland Lumber, said he had no comment on a block
of 519,000 shares of Payless stock that was traded Thursday. If the
block went to the investment group, that would boost its stake to
about 9.2 percent.
   David Stanley, chairman and chief executive of Payless, said in
a statement that ``in our view, Mr. Edelman and his group have
nothing to contribute to this company or its shareholders, nor do
we believe the reported plan to dismantle the company serves any
constructive purpose.''
   The Edelman group said in its SEC filing that it would consider
selling Payless operations as ``going concerns'' in many regions of
the country.
   Sutherland called it a ``possibility'' that his company would
acquire at least some of the Payless operations that would be sold.
``Our expertise in management is part of the partnership'' with
Edelman, he said.
   Payless has 194 retail facilities in 23 states and reported 1987
revenue of $1.7 billion.
   Spokeswoman Brenda Nolte confirmed that the Payless board of
directors approved a complex shareholder rights plan last week to
``protect shareholders from attempts to acquire control of Payless
at an inadequate price.''
   Nolte noted the board said the plan was intended to
``encourage'' buyers to negotiate with the board before attempting
a takeover.
   Perry Sutherland said his father has had a business relationship
with Edelman for several years. He said Dwight Sutherland, the
company's chief executive officer, serves on the boards of
directors of United Stockyards Corp., Datapoint Corp. and Intelogic
Trace Inc. along with Edelman, who has large investments in these
companies.
   Edelman has launched unsuccessful takeover bids for a gamut of
companies, including Lucky Stores Inc., Fruehauf Corp. and
Burlington Industries Inc., earning millions in the process.
   He acquired the restaurant chain Ponderosa Inc. but is believed
to have made no profit when he sold it.
   National Home Center News, an industry trade publication,
recently ranked Payless the third-largest building materials and
do-it-yourself retailer in the nation.
   The magazine ranked Sutherland Lumber ninth, with estimated
annual revenue of about $650 million. Sutherland Lumber's 86 stores
are concentrated in the Midwest and South.
   In an investment report last month, Sutro & Co. noted Payless
had been considered a potential takeover target for three years.
Sutro contended an acquirer could boost its earnings instantly by
closing down a score of Payless stores in the depressed oil patch
region, where sales were off 45 percent last year.
   Sutro also said pieces of Payless, such as its New England
operation, could be sold at ``substantial premiums ... After some
paring, an acquiror could still retain a major national presence in
the industry through 125-150 profitable, well-located stores.''
</TEXT>
