<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ProgramTrading     05-20 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Program Trading,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bear Stearns Re-Evaluating Index Arbitrage Position</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's
remarks strongly supporting program trading have prompted Bear
Stearns & Co. to reconsider its recent move to halt its use of the
controversial strategy, the firm says.
   Bear Stearns, one of several major Wall Street firms to reduce
their program trading activity, will ``re-examine its position'' in
light of Greenspan's remarks and other factors, Alan Greenberg,
Bear Stearns' chairman and chief executive officer, said Thursday.
   Bear Stearns went further than four other investment firms when
it announced last week it would stop index arbitrage _ a major form
of program trading _ not only for its own accounts but also for its
customers.
   Salomon Brothers Inc., Morgan Stanley & Co., PaineWebber Group
Inc. and Kidder Peabody & Co. halted index arbitrage for their own
accounts amid concern that the popular form of program trading was
at least partly responsible for the stock market's volatility.
   Greenspan, testifying before the House telecommunications and
finance subcommittee, said Thursday that excessive restriction of
index arbitrage would limit market liquidity and tend to
destabilize the market.
   He said ``insufficient arbitrage between cash and futures can be
a destabilizing force in a declining market.''
   In index arbitrage, traders use computers to buy or sell baskets
of stocks with offsetting trades in stock-index futures to help
them profit from brief price discrepancies.
   Greenspan said that ``reduced arbitrage implies less connection
between cash and futures markets and more price disparities across
these markets.''
   He also said, ``it is a mistake to single out one segment of the
broad marketplace as the culprit for large and rapid price
movements.''
   Bear Stearns' Greenberg said his firm had been ``monitoring
closely the action and the liquidity problems of the stock market
for the past week.''
   He also pointed to other firms' ``suspension of index arbitrage
activity for themselves but (continuation of) those activities for
customers'' as further reason for the firm to re-evaluate its
position.
   ``If we do decide to re-enter index arbitrage, we will consider
limiting our activities to buying on a downtick and attempting to
sell on an uptick in the stocks involved,'' Greenberg said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
