<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers     05-20 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beazer Group Says 75 Percent Of Koppers Stock Owned Or Tendered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investor group waging a $1.7 billion
hostile takeover offer for Koppers Co. says it controls or has been
tendered more than three-quarters of the company's outstanding
common shares.
   The group led by the British construction company Beazer PLC and
the investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. stated Thursday
that about 73.2 percent of outstanding common shares and about 68.7
percent of outstanding preferred shares had been tendered as of
Wednesday under its $60 a share tender offer.
   The group also extended its tender offer through midnight EDT
Wednesday.
   The common shares tendered, together with 2.1 million common
shares already owned by related entities, represent about 75.2
percent of the outstanding common shares, the Beazer group
indicated.
   The group must acquire 85 percent of Koppers' shares in order to
complete the deal under the anti-takeover law in Delaware, where
Koppers is incorporated.
   Right now, the group may not purchase Koppers' shares under
terms of federal court injunctions in Pittsburgh and Los Angeles.
   It appealed the Los Angeles ruling to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in San Francisco, but a decision has not been announced.
   Also Thursday, U.S. District Judge Maurice Cohill said he would
hold a hearing May 31 on the question of whether the hostile bid
violates federal securities rules.
   The hearing specifically will address whether the $540 million
of preferred securities that the group plans to issue to Shearson
in return for $540 million of its financing should be considered
stock or debt.
   Cohill said the tender offer as currently structured must be
permanently enjoined if the stock in question is found to be a debt
security. If that is the case, the Beazer group could restructure
the financing to comply with regulations.
</TEXT>
