<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Amfac     05-20 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Amfac,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Castle & Cooke Raises Stake In Amfac</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amfac Inc.'s proposed $807.7 million
leveraged buyout apparently was a move to stave off a takeover
threat by Castle & Cooke Inc., which is seeking to sharply raise
its stake in the company, analysts say.
   Los Angeles-based Castle & Cooke on Thursday raised its holdings
in Amfac to 7.3 percent from 4.9 percent, and said it had received
federal clearance to buy up to 15 percent of Amfac's roughly 17.2
million outstanding common shares.
   Castle & Cooke chairman David H. Murdock owns another 2.6
percent share of Amfac, according to documents filed with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Amfac management proposed its $41 a share buyout offer on
Wednesday to the company's board of directors.
   The company's stock soared $6.75 to $45.12{ a share Thursday on
the New York Stock Exchange, indicating speculation a higher offer
would emerge. Castle & Cooke stock closed at $24.75, up 50 cents a
share.
   The buyout would be led by Amfac President and Chief Executive
Officer Richard L. Griffith, who has said it would strengthen the
company's ability to develop Amfac's Hawaii asset base ``in a paced
and profitable manner.''
   Amfac is a diversified services company with main lines of
business in food processing, hotels and resorts, retail,
agriculture and property. It had revenue of $2.2 billion last year.
   Castle & Cooke has operations in food production, through its
Dole Food company, the world's biggest pineapple producer;
transportation equipment leasing; and real estate development.
   San Francisco-based Amfac is Hawaii's largest landowner, while
Castle & Cooke is No. 2.
   Murdock, who has made his reputation by buying and turning
around failing companies, met with Amfac officials in January to
talk over a real estate venture Amfac did not pursue, the
Securities and Exchange filing said.
   Amfac said Murdock proposed merging some of his property into
Amfac in exchange for Amfac stock.
   Securities analyst Kevin Skislock, of Rotan Mosle Inc. in
Houston, said Murdock's aim is to control Amfac's 56,400 acres of
Hawaiian real estate and Amfac's buyout offer is an attempt to
prevent such a move.
   Analyst Randy Havre of J.B. Havre Securities Inc. in Honolulu
said Amfac's valuable Hawaiian land made the $41-a-share buyout
offer ``too cheap.''
   ``My feeling is that shareholders should not tender for less
than $50,'' Havre said. ``Hawaiian real estate is a hot commodity.''
   Analyst Charles Bureker, of Sutro & Co. Inc. in San Francisco,
said there has been speculation that Murdock might be working with
Japanese investors to gain control of Amfac's real estate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
