<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MarketReport     05-20 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Market Report,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Officials Defend Stock Market Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also ran on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock market crashes similar to last October's
could happen again even if market procedures are changed, say the
top-level federal officials who produced a White House study of the
nation's financial markets.
   The officials told the House telecommunications and finance
subcommittee Thursday that their proposals for changing some market
procedures could do little about external factors that influence
investors.
   Their report is being criticized by lawmakers for its lack of
significant recommendations.
   ``We cannot provide an ironclad guarantee that there will not be
another Oct. 19 in our future,'' said Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan, one of the report's authors. ``Unforeseen
economic forces could, on their own, conceivably trigger such an
event.''
   The White House report, released Monday, focused on the record
508-point drop in the Dow Jones Industrial Average of last Oct. 19,
and the unusually large price swings that have occurred repeatedly
ever since. The report was written by Greenspan, Treasury
Undersecretary George D. Gould, Securities and Exchange Commission
Chairman David S. Ruder and Commodity Futures Trading Commission
Chairwoman Wendy Gramm.
   The officials recommended instituting a ``circuit breaker'' that
would temporarily halt trading on the nation's stock, futures and
options exchanges in case the Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped
by 250 points in a single day. That has happened only once, last
Oct. 19.
   The report also urged that improvements be made in the credit,
clearing and settlement procedures the markets use to complete
transactions.
   But the working group suggested no limitations on computerized
program trading, some forms of which have been blamed for adding to
market volatility. It also failed to agree on whether to change the
margins, or up-front payments, required for futures transactions.
Margin requirements are lower on futures exchanges than for stock
markets, which critics say causes speculation.
   The group ignored as well a recommendation made by an earlier
White House panel headed by Nicholas F. Brady, an investment
banker, that the Fed or some other agency oversee issues that
affect all markets.
   The working group's members have cautioned that it would be
unrealistic to take steps such as curbing program trading.
   ``We cannot go back to the days of the abacus or mechanical
adding machines,'' Gould said.
   Lawmakers, however, accused the report of not going far enough
to ease volatility and soothe worried investors.
   ``It is you and your panel who continue to embrace anachronistic
regulatory reforms that have been outstripped by new
technologies,'' said the subcommittee chairman, Rep. Edward Markey,
D-Mass.
   Further criticism came from Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman
of the House Energy and Commerce Committee, of which the finance
subcommittee is a part. He accused the working group of having
``given birth to a mouse'' and of failing to take steps to restore
investors' confidence.
   ``You should not come by my office when people start buying rope
and heating pots of tar and collecting feathers to apply to persons
... who have sat idly by ... while the financial situation of this
nation erodes,'' Dingell said.
   The subcommittee has been holding hearings on the market's
problems for months, but so far has written no legislation. Asked
outside the hearing room when a bill would emerge, Dingell said,
``As soon as circumstances permit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0296 </DOCNO>
