<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SunshineStrike     05-20 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sunshine Strike,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement in Silver Mine Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KELLOGG, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Picketing has ended at the nation's
largest silver mine after a 4{-hour negotiating session produced
tentative agreement on a three-year contract.
   Negotiators for 260 striking miners and Sunshine Mining Co.
announced the agreement late Thursday, the ninth day of the walkout.
   The union's negotiating committee will recommend ratification
when members of United Steelworkers of America Local 5089 vote on
the offer a week from Saturday, said Steve Brown, union
international staff representative.
   ``It took a lot of work and two years,'' Brown said.
   Workers will return starting with the graveyard shift Sunday,
Brown said.
   Production work will resume Monday, said Harry Cougher, vice
president of Sunshine's local operations.
   Both sides refused to release details on the settlement until
union members could review it.
   Workers at the Sunshine Mine downed tools and walked out at
midnight May 10 after overwhelmingly rejecting a contract offer.
Medical coverage, pay, job classifications and production
incentives were among the unresolved issues.
   The mine reopened last November after an 18-month shutdown due
to depressed silver prices. Union members agreed to return under
company-imposed terms while negotiations continued, then struck
when the talks broke down.
   Negotiations resumed Tuesday, ran well into the night Wednesday
and returned Thursday afternoon.
</TEXT>
