<DOCNO> AP880520-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-JuiceDebut     05-20 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Juice Debut,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minute Maid Launches All-Natural Juice In New England</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new all-natural orange juice has been introduced
in New England to challenge Tropicana Products Inc.'s domination of
the estimated $1.6 billion ready-to-serve orange juice industry.
   The Minute Maid Premium Choice, which contains no additives,
marks Houston-based Coca-Cola Food's entry into the
not-from-concentrate orange juice market, which surpassed frozen
juice in sales in 1986.
   Vice President of Marketing George G. Woody III would not
comment on when the product may be sold in other sections of the
country. It will be available in about 1,200 New England stores.
   Woody said growth in the orange juice market contributed to the
decision to challenge Tropicana, which has a virtual lock on
all-natural orange juice sales.
   ``We consider ourselves the leaders in total orange juice sales
and this is one segment of the market where we looked to expand,''
said Woody on Thursday.
   Woody said New England was chosen for the introduction due to
strong all-natural juice sales, which represent less than 20
percent of the total ready-to-serve orange juice sales.
   Since 1979, orange juice sales in the United States have
increased by 23 percent, with most growth in the chilled,
ready-to-serve market, Coca-Cola Foods reported.
   Per capita consumption of juice in 1987 was 6.1 gallons, down
from a peak of 7.8 gallons in 1983, according to Cleveland-based
Beverage Industry magazine.
   Chilled, ready-to-serve orange juice accounted for 57 percent of
total orange juice sales of about $2.8 billion last year.
   Coca-Cola Foods, a division of The Coca-Cola Co. in Atlanta,
reported sales of approximately $1.2 billion last year. The
division also produces Hi-C fruit juices and Bacardi cocktail
mixers.
   Tropicana, a subsidiary of Beatrice Cos. Inc., is ranked second
by most industry publications, but the Florida-based company does
not release sales figures.
   Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc. of Plymouth, the third-ranked juice
company, reported sales of about $735 million last year.
</TEXT>
