<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0005 05-20 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0005,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Break Two-Day Slide, Bonds Up for First Time This Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS new grafs 1-6 to UPDATE with consumer price index for
April, edit to conform; picks up 2nd graf pvs bg'ng, A number ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in April, only marginally
better than March's 0.5 percent gain, the government reported today.
   More than one-fourth of the April rise came from a steep 2.0
percent jump in clothing costs, tying March for the greatest
one-month gain since price records were first kept in 1947.
   Grocery prices climbed at their fastest pace in 20 months, while
energy prices were up sharply as well _ reflecting the steepest
rise in gasoline prices since August.
   The April gain meant that for the first four months of 1988
retail prices were up at an annual rate of 4.5 percent.
   While this was little changed from the 4.4 percent for all of
1987, economists were concerned because much of the inflationary
pressure has shown up in the last two months. Analysts noted that
the March rise had been the most severe since January 1987.
   On Thursday, investors set aside worries about inflation long
enough to help the stock and bond markets break their recent slides.
   A number of senators, meanwhile, have reaffirmed the
government's pledge to stand behind deposits in the nation's
savings and loan institutions after a congressional agency reported
the doubling of the deficit in the federal S&L insurance fund.
   ``There is absolutely no doubt the U.S. Congress stands behind
our deposit insurance program,'' Banking Committee Chairman William
Proxmire, D-Wis., said at a hearing Thursday by his panel.
   On Wall Street, stock prices staged a partial recovery Thursday
that traders attributed to ``bargain shopping'' and lessening of
recent tension over inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell a total of
56.54 points Tuesday and Wednesday, rose 7.63 to 1,958.72. Broader
market gauges were mixed.
   Bond prices advanced after falling in the first three sessions
this week. The price of the bellwether 30-year Treasury bond rose
nearly $2.50 for every $1,000 in face value as its yield slipped to
9.27 percent from 9.29 percent late Wednesday.
   In the report on thrifts, Frederick D. Wolf, director of the
accounting and financial management division of the General
Accounting Office, said the liabilities of the Federal Savings and
Loan Insurance Corp. exceeded its assets by $13.7 billion at the
end of 1987, up from $6.3 billion a year earlier.
   He also said the money available to the insurance fund _ $28
billion over the next 10 years _ ``probably will not be adequate''
to restore the industry's health by closing or merging 505
institutions listed as insolvent.
   Wolf estimated it would cost $30 billion to $35 billion to clean
up the S&L mess, which is centered primarily in Southwestern states
hard hit by depressed real estate and oil markets. That estimate
does not include an additional 435 ``barely solvent'' institutions,
he said.
   In other economic developments Thursday:
   _The two broadest measures of the nation's money supply rose in
early May while a narrower measure fell, the Federal Reserve Board
reported.
   _The nation's 24 largest investor-owned utilities charged their
commercial and industrial electric users an average 6.28 cents per
kilowatt-hour over the 12 months ended April 30, down from 6.29
cents a year earlier, a study by the consulting firm National
Utility Service Inc. said.
   _Assets of the nation's 425 money market mutual funds rose $3.70
billion to $274.12 billion in the latest week, more than offsetting
a $3.35 billion drop the previous week, the Investment Company
Institute said.
</TEXT>
