<1ST_LINE>r f BC-IBM-Dutch     05-20 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-IBM-Dutch,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IBM Says European Community Dropped Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp.,
confirming an important legal victory, said Friday that that the
European Community Commission has dropped an antitrust inquiry
against the computer maker.
   The European Community Commission inspected IBM's computer
leasing operations in the Netherlands last year in response to
complaints by three Dutch leasing companies that IBM engaged in
predatory pricing.
   IBM said the last complaint has been withdrawn and the
commission has decided to close its books.
   ``We are pleased that the commission has confirmed our view that
the allegations of illegal behavior were unfounded,'' the company
said in a statement.
   The probe in the Netherlands was the first notable antitrust
challenge the company had faced in Europe since the settlement in
1984 of an 8-year-old antitrust case. In that case, IBM agreed to
give rivals the technical information necessary to make computers
and related products compatible with its System 370 mainframe
computers.
</TEXT>
