<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced in moderate trading
early today, extending Thursday's rebound, as Wall Street drew some
reassurance from the latest news on inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks was up 5.80 points
at 1,964.52 at 10 a.m. EDT on Wall Street.
   Gaining issues outnumbered losers by about 2-to-1 on the New
York Stock Exchange, with 639 issues advancing, 278 declining and
452 unchanged. Volume on the Big Board totaled 20.6 million shares
in the first half-hour of trading.
   The government reported today that consumer prices rose 0.4
percent in April, a level that had been widely anticipated by
economists and traders.
   The retail inflation report ``really was right on the money,''
said Jack Baker, the head of block trading at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. ``Everyone felt much better ... People seem to be more
willing to bid for stocks today.''
   The stock and bond markets have been haunted this week by fears
that inflation could be rekindled, and the anxiety pushed the Dow
average down a total of 56.54 points on Tuesday and Wednesday.
   If the April rise in consumer prices had been more than the
expected 0.4 percent, many analysts said, stocks and bonds would
likely have taken another sharp hit today.
   Despite today's reprieve, though, analysts said concern about
inflationary pressures continues to hang over the market.
   The NYSE's composite index of all listed issues was up 0.40 at
143.41. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose
0.38 to 292.17.
   On Thursday, the Dow Jones industrials rose 7.63 to close at
1,958.72 after dropping 25 points in early trading.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4-to-3 in
nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 843 down, 640 up and
496 unchanged. NYSE volume totaled 165.16 million shares, down from
209.42 million shares in the previous session.
