<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Wometco-Cablevision     05-20 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wometco-Cablevision,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Cablevision Industries Close to Buying Part of Wometco
Cable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cablevision Industries Inc., a cable television
operator, is close to acquiring some of the assets of Wometco Cable
Co. from the Robert M. Bass Group Inc. for stock valued at about
$750 million, a published report said today.
   The Wall Street Journal cited unnamed industry executives for
its report.
   Calls were placed to Cablevision, which is based in Liberty,
N.Y., and to Wometco, which is based in Miami, but spokesmen were
said to be unavailable.
   A woman who answered the telephone at Bass Group, based in Fort
Worth, Texas, said the company has a policy of not commenting on
its activities.
   The newspaper said the Bass Group quietly put part of the assets
of Wometco up for sale last month.
   Wometco has about 440,000 subscribers and operates cable systems
mostly in the Southeast.
   The story said Cablevision will acquire systems serving about
300,000 subscribers for stock and will assume certain Wometco debt.
The Bass Group will retain about 140,000 subscribers from Wometco
systems and also has an interest in a cable system acquired earlier
this year in Atlanta, the story said.
   Cablevision Industries is a privately-held concern controlled by
its founder Alan Gerry and is currently the 21st largest cable
company with about 600,000 subscribers, the story said.
   The Bass Group purchased Wometco in a 50-50 venture with Taft
Broadcasting Co. in 1986 for about $620 million, and later acquired
Taft's interest, the report said.
</TEXT>
