<HEAD>Coleco Faces More Troubles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coleco Industries Inc., which is
battling to avoid bankruptcy, has lost its license to market the
popular Trivial Pursuit board game.
   The West Hartford toymaker also faces the possibility of losing
its valuable license to market Cabbage Patch Kids products and
dolls, according to officials.
   Coleco will lose the right to market Trivial Pursuit after Dec.
31. Horn Abbott Ltd. of Toronto, the company with the rights to the
game, said Thursday that Tonka Corp. of Minneapolis will
manufacture and market the game beginning in January 1989.
   ``It was a business decision on our part,'' said James G. Ware,
Horn Abbott president.
   Sean McGowan, a vice president with Balis Zorn Gerard Inc. in
New York, said the license for Cabbage Patch Kids, which accounted
for 25.1 percent of Coleco's sales in 1987, may be affected by the
company's financial troubles.
   ``There is no question it is in jeopardy,'' McGowan said.
``There is no question Xavier Roberts does not want to do business
with a company that is in bankruptcy.''
   Roberts is the creator of Cabbage Patch Kids.
   Coleco reported Wednesday that it lost $47.4 million in the
first quarter. The company has a negative net worth of $130.7
million. The company has cut its blue-collar work force in half and
trimmed its corporate staff by more than 30 percnti bid to remain
in business.
</TEXT>
