<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RubberStrike     05-20 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rubber Strike,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodyear Workers Begin Voting; Firestone Walkout Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative contract settlement between the
United Rubber Workers and Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. has been
approved by four of the five union locals that have voted on the
pact, a union spokesman said today.
   Voting by the remaining six locals continues through Monday. The
union represents 15,000 workers at 11 Goodyear plants nationwide.
   Meanwhile, a walkout by 4,700 Firestone Inc. union workers in
six states continues for a sixth day with no contract talks planned.
   URW workers in Union City, Tenn.; Marysville, Ohio; and Topeka,
Kan., voted in favor of the proposed Goodyear contract on Thursday
and workers in Sun Prairie, Wis., approved it today, said URW
spokesman Curt Brown said.
   Workers in Madisonsville, Ky., rejected the offer Thursday, he
said.
   With the approval by Union City, the proposal appears headed for
ratification nationwide. Under URW bylaws, ratification must be
made by a majority of the locals representing a majority of the
membership.
   An earlier tentative agreement with Goodyear was rejected, and
Union City, with about 2,500 members, was one of the pivotal locals
because of its size.
   If the voting by the remaining locals follows the first
ratification vote, the three-year pact would be approved.
   ``It would appear that the improvements made to the contract
during the negotiations session May 17 turned around the vote in
Union City, Tennessee and satisfied their needs and their
concerns,'' said Brown.
   Firestone workers in six states went on strike Sunday after
union negotiators rejected Firestone's offer, saying it didn't
match an earlier agreement with Goodyear.
   Brown said a local in Danville, Va., is voting today; locals in
Akron and St. Mary's, Ohio; Lincoln, Neb.; New Bedford, Mass. vote
on Sunday; and Gadsden, Ala., on Monday.
   

</TEXT>
