<HEAD>Soybeans Open Higher, Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade, with soybeans slightly higher, wheat
slightly lower and corn prices mixed.
   The higher soybean opening surprised many traders who had
expected a continution of Thursday's late sell-off and quieter
activity after the exchange increased margins overnight for the
second time this week.
   The price to play the grain futures market has more than doubled
since Monday, with initial margins on soybeans now $2,000 compared
to $900 on Friday. For that reason, traders expected small
speculators to shy away from the soybean market this morning.
   Many of the weaker players did take profits on Thursday. But
with forecasts calling for continued dry weather in the Midwest,
speculators were still betting that grain and soybean prices will
go higher, said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   ``There is still very strong support here for the grains,'' he
said. ``The market did start steady to easier, but then everybody
wanted to buy it.''
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.40{ a bushel; corn was { cent
lower to { cent higher with July at $2.18 a bushel; oats were {
cent to 1 cent lower with July at $1.71\ a bushel; soybeans were 1
cent to 1} cents higher with July at $7.69 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .38 cent higher with June at
73.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .02 cent lower to .30 cent
higher with May at 80.75 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent to .28
cent higher with June at 53.75 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were unchanged to .60 cent higher with May at 53.20 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Thursday.
