<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MediaGeneral-Sugarman f0028   05-20 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Media General-Sugarman, f0028,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugarman Seeks Media General Board Seats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Sugarman proposal at
meeting; uppicks 6th graf pvs: Sugarman is...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California investor Burt Sugarman today
urged the family that controls Media General Inc. to consider
splitting the company into two or more publishing and broadcast
firms.
   Sugarman, who is engaged in a takeover bid for Richmond-based
Media General, said at the annual stockholders meeting that his
interest ``is not in taking the newspapers away'' from company
Chairman D. Tennant Bryan and his family.
   Sugarman and two associates were submitted as candidates for
election to the company's board of dierectors. Stockholders will
vote on board members today, but the results will not be announced
until later, after all proxies have been counted.
   One item not on the agenda for the meeting was Sugarman's buyout
offer. Media General officials rejected Sugarman's original
$61.50-per-share offer to buy all the company's stock. That offer
was made Feb. 29, and Sugarman has since sweetened his bid to $70 a
share.
   Sugarman and his associates own 10.1 percent of Media General
Class A stock, an investment of more than $111 million.
   Members of the Bryan family own 70 percent of the company's
Class B stock, which controls seven of the 10 board seats. The
Bryan family also owns about 12 percent of the publicly traded
Class A stock.
   Sugarman is seeking to have himself, Harold Simmons and David
Gotterer named Class A directors. Media General has recommended
that its three directors be re-elected.
   The days leading up to the annual meeting were marked by charges
and countercharges between the two parties.
   On Saturday, lawyers for Media General and Sugarman aired their
allegations of unfair tactics in the proxy battle before U.S.
District Judge Richard L. Williams. Both sides had filed motions
for injunctions to stop the opposition from delivering what they
characterized as false and misleading information to shareholders.
   Williams denied both sides' motions, calling adversaries in
proxy fights ``the world's most thin-skinned people'' and saying he
found no evidence of irreparable harm by either party. The judge
also said the proper time for the parties to assess damages was
after the annual meeting.
   Earlier this week, Media General officials said Sugarman had
offered to end his attempt to land three board seats in exchange
for control of the company's cable television franchises in Fairfax
County and Fredericksburg.
   Sugarman strongly denied ever making such an offer, and called
Media General's claim ``a desperate move to make it appear as
though we are losing the proxy contest. In my opinion, this
last-minute trick just won't work.''
</TEXT>
