<DOCNO> AP880520-0311 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Bonds     05-20 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bonds,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices slipped in light dealings this
morning as inflation worries continued to weigh on the market
despite a new government report that consumer prices rose only
modestly in April.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond edged down [ point, or
about $1.25 for every $1,000 in face value, by midday as its yield
rose to 9.29 percent from 9.27 percent late Thursday.
   As trading got underway today, the government said consumer
prices rose 0.4 percent in April, compared with a 0.5 percent rise
in March.
   While low inflation is usually seen as good news for bond
investors, the report failed to inspire any buying in today's
market.
   That was partly because the size of the increase had been widely
expected, and partly because investors remain fearful that the
economy is growing so quickly that inflation may eventually
accelerate, analysts said.
   William V. Sullivan Jr., director of money market research at
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said the reaction ``is the hallmark of a
bear market.''
   ``There is some good news in the April statistics that should
allay concerns that inflation is accelerating, and the market
ignores that. It gravitates to bad news,'' he said.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments slipped 1-32 point, intermediate maturities fell 3-32
point and 20-year issues were off 9-32 point, according to Telerate
Inc., a financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Merrill Lynch Daily Treasury Index, which measures price
movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities of a
year or longer, was off 0.07 at 108.68. The Shearson Lehman Hutton
Daily Treasury Bond Index, which makes a similar measurement, fell
0.95 to 1,137.11.
   Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures
price movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, was up 0.02 at 274.66.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose 10 basis points to
6.24 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point.
Six-month bills rose 5 basis points to 6.60 percent and one-year
bills rose 4 basis points at 6.95 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 7[ percent, up from 6 15-16 percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
