<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1402EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SmithKline-Nova     05-20 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SmithKline-Nova,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SmithKline and Nova Pharmaceutical to Market Drugs Jointly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nova Pharmaceutical Corp. has agreed to a joint
venture with SmithKline Beckman Corp. to develop and market a
variety of painkilling and central nervous system drugs, pending
approval from both firm's boards, Baltimore-based Nova announced.
   The preliminary agreement, estimated to be worth $72.5 million
to Nova, eventually will give Philadelphia-based SmithKline an
estimated 20 percent stake in Nova, which was founded in 1982.
   The two firms would be advancing work on a range of drugs Nova
has developed, including a class of painkillers targeted at
bradykinin, which Nova and the Johns Hopkins Medical Institutions
report plays a key role in relaying pain messages to the nervous
system. The findings were reported in the current issue of the
Proceedings of the National Academy of Science.
   ``This is quite significant for Nova,'' Arda M. Minocherhomjee,
a health-care analyst with Cable, Howse & Ragen Inc. in Seattle,
said of the joint venture. ``It gives them access to an excellent
marketing partner, and, furthermore, it gives them the capital
needed to develop their products.''
   After the agreement was announced Thursday, Nova's stock closed
unchanged in over-the-counter trading at $8.25 a share.
   ``Nova cut a very attractive deal as far as they're concerned,''
said David M. Bartash, pharmaceutical analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds in New York. ``It's very good, and they get SmithKline to
carry some of the development costs.''
   ``You need to raise the funds when you don't need them,'' said
Dr. Hans Mueller, president and chief executive of Nova, which
analysts estimate had $2.4 million in cash and more than $15
million in available funds as of March 31, more than enough to
finance its research and development expenses this year.
   For the first quarter ended March 31, the company lost $1.4
million, compared with a loss of $2 million a year ago. Revenues
increased to $4.1 million from $1.6 million.
   Nova received Food and Drug Administration approval in January
to start clinical testing on an analgesic that blocks the
transmission of bradykinins, a powerful pain-producing substance in
the body.
   The company is conducting clinical trials on a nasal spray form
of the drug to block symptoms of the common cold and plans to seek
FDA approval to test the drug's effectiveness in relieving
inflammation and blocking burn pain.
   Analysts estimate that the potential annual market for the
analgesic could easily top $100 million three or four years after
it is released.
   Nova also is developing compounds to treat central nervous
system disorders including epilepsy, Parkinson's disease and
Huntington's chorea.
   Under the terms of the agreement, Nova and SmithKline would form
separate partnerships to develop and market the painkillers and the
central nervous system products.
   As part of the latter agreement, SmithKline would make an
immediate cash payment of $25 million to Nova in return for 2.7
million newly issued common shares and warrants to purchase 775,000
shares of SmithKline at $9.28 a share.
   SmithKline has also agreed to purchase by December 1991 $24
million worth of Nova common stock and warrants to purchase an
undisclosed number of shares at 15 percent above market price at
the time of the purchase.
   The partnership, which is to be 60 percent owned by SmithKline,
would receive the right to license SmithKline's psychiatric drugs,
including Thorazine and Stelazine _ which currently account for
about $40 million in annual revenues _ once the first central
nervous system product was marketed.
   The analgesics partnership calls for SmithKline to pay an
initial $1 million and assume $21.5 million of debt primarily to
commercialize the painkiller. SmithKline would manufacture it and
obtain exclusive worldwide marketing rights, while Nova would
retain a 50 percent share of control over that partnership and half
the profits obtained from product sales.
   ``We fully expect to take a leadership role in the evolving
field of neurobiology,'' Henry Wendt, SmithKline's chairman and
chief executive, said in a prepared statement. ``Nova's exciting
research projects, together with our drug development and marketing
capability, makes a powerful combination.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
