<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1413EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-BritishRail     05-20 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-British Rail,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Rail Reportedly Under Study For Privatization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government is considering selling off
British Rail, the national railroad system, the Economist magazine
reported in its latest issue.
   The plan is being worked on by a policy unit within Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher's office, the magazine said in its May
21 issue, which was made available Friday.
   Spokesmen for the prime minister, British Rail and the
Department of Transport said Friday they were unaware of any plans
for the privatization of the railway.
   A report in London's Evening Standard, however, said the prime
minister's office confirmed that a study of the state company's
privatization is in progress but stressed that it was at an early
stage.
   The Economist said three options are being explored. The first
is selling the entire network as a going concern. But that would be
made difficult by British Rail's current troubled financial state,
which requires government subsidies for operation.
   A second option calls for splitting British Rail into regional
companies. The magazine said this option is under study by Greg
Bourne, a special adviser in the prime minister's policy unit.
   Bourne declined to answer questions about the reports.
   The third option would be to form a ``track authority'' which
would put operation of British Rail's track and signaling hardware
up for private bidding, the magazine said.
   The Economist said plans for a split-up of British Rail into
regional companies are also being studied by the Center for Policy
Studies, a private think tank, which will publish its conclusions
next month.
   Mrs. Thatcher's government has sold off billions of pounds worth
of state assets, including British Telecom PLC, the phone company,
British Gas PLC, and British Airways PLC, since she came into power
in 1979.
   It currently is in the process of preparing the sale of the
electicity industry of England and Wales.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
