<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-20 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Up 9.6 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange closed
higher, but below their best levels Friday as an uncertain start to
business on Wall Street reduced London trading volume to a trickle.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index rose 9.6
points, or 0.5 percent, to close at 1,770.2.
   Volume came to 493 million shares compard with 442.3 million
shares on Thursday.
   Equities continued to closely track performances in overseas
stock markets. Gains in New York on Thursday and in Tokyo earlier
Friday, pushed up the 100-share index more than 14 points in late
morning.
   But shares drifted back Friday afternoon as Wall Street
surrendered early gains and moved back into negative territory. By
the end of London trading, the Dow Jones industrial average was
barely changed on the day.
   Dealers said institutional activity was light, with selling
interest roughly offsetting purchases.
   ``U.K. institutions really aren't showing direction,'' one
dealer said.
   The market shrugged off news that British retail prices rose a
greater-than-expected 1.6 percent in April. Dealers said the
inflation figures are frequently distorted by seasonal factors in
April, the first month of Britain's fiscal year.
   London players kept a closer eye on the release of U.S.
inflation figures, but they were in line with many economists'
forecasts and ended up having little effect on London equities.
   The U.S. consumer price index gained 0.4 percent in April,
compared with an 0.5-percent increase in March.
   The Financial Times 30-share index was up 7.1 points at 1,415.2
at the close.
   The Financial Times 500-share index rose 5.77 points to close at
1,000.80.
</TEXT>
