<DOCNO> AP880520-0317 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Seabrook Bjt   05-20 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Seabrook, Bjt,0907</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Years Later, PSNH Still Faces Nuclear Hurdles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after Public Service Company
of New Hampshire announced it would build it own atomic reactor,
the ill-fated Seabrook project has become a symbol for the problems
that extinguished many of America's grandest hopes for nuclear
power.
   Public Service is the first major public power company to seek
refuge from its creditors in bankruptcy court, and there remains no
assurance that Seabrook, its pricetag now at $5.4 billion and
rising $50 million a month, ever will clear evacuation-planning
hurdles and generate electricity.
   Spokesman Nicholas Ashooh conceded this week that, with the
benefit of hindsight, Public Service would have followed a
different course if the decision to build were being made again.
   ``But that's irrelevant,'' Ashooh said. ``The bigger question
is, how can we have a regulatory system that after 20 years cannot
make a decision on a major power project?''
   Public Service narrowly averted bankruptcy in 1984, completing a
$425 million bond sale that was the largest financing in utility
industry history. But nuclear disasters _ first at Pennsylvania's
Three Mile Island in 1979 and then at Chernobyl in the Soviet Union
in 1986 _ dealt Seabrook a devastating blow.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, now the likely 1988
Democratic presidential nominee, cited Chernobyl when he decided to
oppose evacuation planning for Massachusetts communities near
Seabrook. Dukakis has since become a key obstacle, though New
Hampshire's evacuation plans also still lack final approval.
   The environment surrounding nuclear power in May 1968 and Public
Service's early experiences with it gave little clue of the
troubles that lay ahead.
   A byproduct of research that produced the atomic bomb during
World War II, nuclear power in the 1940s and 1950s was seen by many
as ``the key to the world's future,'' Christopher Flavin of the
Worldwatch Institute wrote in his 1983 report ``Nuclear Power: The
Market Test.''
   ``It would supply infinite amounts of energy indefinitely and
remove many of the constraints under which humanity had struggled
for millennia,'' Flavin wrote.
   Another early claim by nuclear proponents was that it would
provide energy too cheap to meter. Energy from New England's first
nuclear plant, Yankee Rowe in Rowe, Mass., wasn't too cheap to
meter. But it was only pennies per kilowatt-hour, cheaper than
other alternatives at the time.
   Public Service owned 7 percent of Yankee Rowe, which cost $44
million to build and began operation in 1960 as one of a half-dozen
prototype reactors nationwide funded by the U.S. government. By
1968, Public Service also had investments in other nuclear plants
operating or under construction _ Connecticut Yankee, Vermont
Yankee and Maine Yankee.
   After conducting studies that projected continued strong growth
in energy demand, Public Service decided to join dozens of other
utilities that were jumping on the nuclear bandwagon.
   New Hampshire's largest power company announced on May 20, 1968,
that it would build an 860-megawatt reactor on the Piscataqua River
in Newington, N.H. Public Service was to own 50 percent of the
plant, with United Illuminating of Connecticut to pick up most of
the rest of the tab.
   The plant was to cost $150 million and be operating commercially
by the fall of 1974, company Chairman Avery Schiller announced.
   But the federal government squelched the original plan, saying
the Newington location was too close to Pease Air Force Base.
Public Service chose an alternate site on marshland at Seabrook.
   Public Service shelved the plans in 1969 after problems arose in
financing the plant. Later, utility studies showed a need for a big
new power plant, and the company revived its nuclear plans on Feb.
1, 1972.
   The plans were subsequently revised to include two
1,150-megawatt reactors, the first to be operating commercially in
1979, the second in 1981. The total cost was estimated at $850
million.
   Although the oil crisis of 1973 heightened awareness about
energy, Seabrook began running into problems that earlier nuclear
plants had not faced. Ashooh drew a comparison between Seabrook and
Maine Yankee in Wiscasset, an 826-megawatt reactor that began
operating in 1972 at a construction cost of $239 million.
   ``They went through their environmental (impact) hearings in an
afternoon,'' Ashooh said. ``It took Seabrook several years.''
   Controversy over Seabrook's cooling-water system wasn't finally
settled until August 1978, causing years of delays and adding
hundreds of millions of dollars to the plant's cost. By then,
Seabrook also had become the target of highly visible opposition.
   Civil disobedience actions began at the plant site in 1976,
months before groundbreaking, and a May 1977 protest that ended
with 1,414 arrests _ the largest at any U.S. nuclear plant at that
time _ made Seabrook the focus of the nation's anti-nuclear
movement.
   As further delays kept boosting the project's pricetag, interest
rates skyrocketed in the late 1970s, and Public Service's financial
health deteriorated.
   In the aftermath of the partial meltdown at Three Mile Island,
the Nuclear Regulatory Commission enacted rules that now represent
the final major obstacle to a commercial license for Seabrook,
requiring approved evacuation plans for a 10-mile zone around all
nuclear power plants.
   Also in the spring of 1979, New Hampshire Gov. Hugh Gallen
signed a law barring utilities from charging ratepayers for power
plants before they operate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
