<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     05-20 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises In Quiet European Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in lackluster European trading
Friday. Gold prices fell.
   Dealers said trading was extremely thin and quiet, partly
because many traders on the Continent went home early before a
three-day weekend.
   ``You could hear a pin drop in the trading room today,'' said
one dealer at a British merchant bank.
   The dollar's slight gains were due to a flurry of buying in the
morning after Hashemi Rafsanjani, the speaker of Iran's parliament,
reiterated that his country was at war with the United States and
called for an arms buildup.
   The dollar jumped up on the report. But then it barely moved for
several hours until it edged back late in the day, dealers said.
   One dealer said market players did not take the report seriously
but that it gave them something to do.
   The dollar was not affected by news that the U.S. consumer price
index rose 0.4 percent in April because the rise was in line with
expectations, dealers said.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. The
pound fell to $1.8615 from $1.8665 late Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose fractionally to a closing 124.82 yen from 124.80
yen late Thursday. Later, in London, it was quoted at 124.85 yen.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.7030 West German marks, up from 1.6990; 1.4195 Swiss
francs, up from 1.4155; 5.7560 French francs, up from 5.7542;
1.9070 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9042; 1,263.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,262.00; and 1.2420 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2442.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose 45 cents a troy ounce to close at a bid
$458.01 an ounce.
   Later gold fell in London to a late bid price of $455.20 a troy
ounce from late Thursday's $456.90. In Zurich, gold closed at a bid
$455.50 a troy ounce compared with $458.00 late Thursday.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.64 a troy ounce, compared
with late Thursday's $6.72 an ounce.
</TEXT>
