<1ST_LINE>r f BC-US-Trade-Yeutter     05-20 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-US-Trade-Yeutter,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Rep Cautious On U.S. Trade Balance Trend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter warned Friday that the sharp narrowing in the nation's
trade deficit in March does not necessarily signal a trend.
   The gap narrowed to $9.75 billion from $13.83 billion in
February, catching the markets and some government officials off
guard.
   Yeutter, the top U.S. trade official, said the improvement was a
``pleasant surprise,'' but said he preferred to look at quarterly
averages, which give a better idea of trends.
   ``We have to be concerned that this isn't an aberration,'' he
said.
   Yeutter said a $1.3 billion rise in U.S. imports to $38.7
billion did raise concern.
   He called on foreign firms to ``stop dumping'' but added: ``We'd
have a healthy situation if our consumer demand were a bit less
strong.''
   Yeutter was in Zurich during a European trip to address the
Swiss Farmers' Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
