<DOCNO> AP880520-0321 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1518EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Multifoods-Bregman     05-20 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Multifoods-Bregman,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bregman Partners May Seek Control of Multifoods, Filing Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bregman Partners, which broke off takeover
talks with International Multifoods Corp. on Thursday, said it
still may launch a tender offer for the food giant, government
documents show.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission on
Thursday, Bregman Partners said it may ``seek control of the
company through negotiations with the board of directors and
management, through a tender offer,'' or through the purchase of
additional shares of Multifoods stock.
   But the filing, which contained a laundry list of alternatives,
also stated the group may simply opt to sell its Multifoods
holdings.
   Last December Bregman Partners disclosed in an SEC filing that
it held 10.7 percent of International Multifoods' outstanding
common stock. Earlier, it had sought federal government clearance
to raise its stake to as high as 25 percent.
   Bregman Partners said in its Thursday filing that it has
``contacted several third parties regarding their possible interest
in providing financing'' for a takeover of Multifoods. The Canadian
group also said it has contacted a number third parties that may be
interested in buying certain Multifoods business units.
   Bregman Partners, which consists mainly of the Bregman family of
Toronto and Belzberg banking family of Vancouver, said last year it
might seek control of International Multifoods, an international
food manufacturer and distributor.
   The Minneapolis-based company said Thursday it had received a
letter from Bregman Partners ending the Canadian group's
consideration of an acquisition and thus terminating a standstill
agreement between the two concerns.
   Bregman Partners had agreed not to purchase additional
International Multifoods shares while negotiations were under way.
   The company has said it would oppose any takeover attempt by
Bregman Partners, and in October filed suit alleging that the
partnership had illegally caused speculation in its stock and filed
misleading government disclosure statements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880520-0322 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Facet-Pennzoil     05-20 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Facet-Pennzoil,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shareholders Accept Pennzoil Offer For Facet Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pennzoil Co. said Friday that 95 percent of
Facet Enterprises Inc.'s common stock has been tendered into its
$32-a-share cash offer for the filter maker.
   The $250 million offer expired at 11 p.m. Thursday, and more
than 5.7 million Facet shares were tendered by the deadline, the
oil giant said.
   Tulsa-based Facet sought Pennzoil as a ``white knight'' to help
fight off hostile bidder Prospect Group Inc.
   The Facet board rejected a $27.50-a-share offer from Prospect
and instituted anti-takeover provisions. Prospect dropped its $199
million bid shortly after Pennzoil came on the scene.
   Facet is Houston-based Pennzoil's first acquisition since it
received $3 billion in cash from Texaco Inc. as settlement in their
four-year legal dispute over control of Getty Oil Co.
   Pennzoil officials have said, however, that the Facet purchase
is not part of their strategy for using that money. Pennzoil
officials will meet next month to discuss further acquisitions.
   Pennzoil, Facet's largest customer, has said it will operate the
company from its current headquarters as a separate entity.
   As part of the deal, Pennzoil reportedly will assume $50 million
in Facet debt, which resulted mostly from its $67 million
acquisition of Purolator Products Inc. last year.
   Facet President James Malone said the company would be in a
better position to accelerate its expansion plans under Pennzoil
control.
   Facet is considering acquisitions _ in the aviation and auto
filter businesses as well as in the medical and food filtration
businesses _ to help boost its annual revenue from the current $350
million to $1 billion by 1990, Malone said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
