<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FederatedLayoffs     05-20 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federated Layoffs,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lazarus Stores Laying Off 1,200</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lazarus, a division of Federated Department
Stores Inc., announced Friday it is laying off 1,200 employees as a
result of Federated's purchase by Campeau Corp. of Canada.
   Lazarus, a Cincinnati-based department store group, said 600
employees will lose their jobs in the company's central
organization and the remaining 600 will be laid off from the 43
stores and regional organization. Lazarus has 15,000 employees and
operates in Ohio, Kentucky, Indiana, West Virginia and Michigan.
   All of the employees will know their status by June 11, company
officials said. Those laid off will be given severance money and
benefits and will be offered help finding jobs elsewhere, Lazarus
said in a statement.
   The layoffs are part of a ``streamlining plan'' developed by the
Lazarus management team, the company said.
   Beth Charlton, public relations spokeswoman for Lazarus, said
she could not discuss details of the severance packages for those
being laid off.
   Asked whether there will be further layoffs, Ms. Charlton said,
``I have no way of telling that, but this is all that's been given
to us.''
   ``The reduction of approximately 1,200 associates is due to the
uncertain retail environment that the Midwest has experienced since
last October, to streamline structural problems resulting from two
mergers and an acquisition, and the need to service the financial
cost of the purchase of Federated,'' Lazarus said in its statement.
   Campeau Corp., headed by Canadian businessman Robert Campeau,
recently won the right to buy the Cincinnati-based Federated for
$6.6 billion, ending a takeover battle begun Jan. 25. Campeau
Corp., a Toronto-based development company, bought Allied Stores
Corp. in December 1986. Federated operates more than 650 stores
nationwide and had 1987 sales of $11 billion.
   Campeau has said its costs of the Federated purchase, including
borrowing money for the deal, will be more than $8 billion.
   Prior to the takeover battle, Federated had consolidated its
retail operations in 1986 and 1987 by merging eight of its store
groups, including Lazarus, into three retail units. The other store
groups involved were Foley's, Sanger Harris, Levy's, Shillito's,
Rike's, Gold Circle and Richway.
</TEXT>
