<DOCNO> AP880520-0325 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FarmersGroup     05-20 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers Group,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Has Hands Full In Warding Off Takeover Bid, Chairman Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers Group Inc. faces a
difficult challenge in attempting to defeat BAT Industries' $4.5
billion takeover bid, the insurer's chairman said Friday.
   The $63-a-share offer is ``perhaps the test of Farmers'
mettle,'' Leo E. Denlea Jr., Farmers' chairman, told about 500
people attending the company's annual meeting here.
   The offer by BAT and its American subsidiary, Batus Inc., has
been vigorously opposed by management at Farmers, the nation's
third-largest home and auto insurance company and the
seventh-largest property and casualty insurer.
   Denlea warned shareholders against becoming confused by the
offer.
   ``Farmers' record is unparalleled. We are supremely confident we
can continue to enhance shareholder value in the future,'' Denlea
said.
   Results of a non-binding shareholder resolution proposed by
Batus, which urged Farmers' board to negotiate, will not be
available for at least a week, Denlea said.
   Also addressing Farmers' shareholders was BAT's chairman, Pat
Sheehy. He agreed with Denlea's upbeat forecast for Farmers and
reiterated earlier statements that BAT would pay substantially more
than $63 a share if Farmers would only negotiate.
   ``We want to buy Farmers because it's a first-class organization
that has excellent growth prospects,'' Sheehy said.
   ``We are pleased with the support that we received from Farmers
Group shareholders on our resolution recommending the Farmers'
directors reconsider their refusal to negotiate with us,'' Sheehy
said. ``We look forward to receiving the actual tally.''
   Batus, a diversified company whose better-known interests
include Kool cigarettes and Saks Fifth Avenue stores, said Thursday
about 18 percent of the company's shareholders had offered to sell
their stock to Batus at the offered price of $63 a share.
   The outcome of the proxy vote may not be known for some days,
because anything other than an obviously overwhelming vote one way
or the other will have to be independently verified, said Jerry
Faulwell, Farmers vice president and treasurer.
   The battle for control of the company has been spirited, with
Farmers criticizing BAT for doing business in South Africa and
suggesting its tobacco holdings make it unfit to control an
insurance company that gives non-smoker discounts.
   Louisville-based Batus, for its part, has responded by pointing
out that Farmers has invested $200 million of the money collected
from policy holders in U.S. companies that do business in South
Africa.
   Batus has committed to maintaining non-smoker discounts, and
points out that British insurers owned by BAT Industries have
instituted non-smoking rates since BAT acquired them. BAT does less
than 1 percent of its business in South Africa and subscribes to
Common Market guidelines for such businesses aimed at bettering the
lot of blacks under apartheid, spokesmen have said.
   Batus owns Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp., maker of Kool,
Viceroy, Raleigh and Belair cigarettes, and retailers including
Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's. It also owns Appleton
Papers Inc.
</TEXT>
