<HEAD>Grain Soybeans Close Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed higher Friday on
the Chicago Board of Trade with soybeans up sharply on fears of
continued dry weather.
   Weekend weather forecasts were mixed, but even the most
optimistic outlooks called for scattered showers to bring only
slight moisture to parts of the Corn Belt, analysts said.
   With soybean stockpiles declining, a poor crop this year could
lead to tight supplies next year.
   ``My weatherman is the market and the market says we're not
going to get much rain this weekend, so that's what I'm going by,''
said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   But if more rain should fall than expected this weekend, grain
and soybean prices probably would plummet on Monday, Lespinasse
said.
   ``It's a very nervous market,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 5\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.46{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 3} cents higher with July at $2.21\ a bushel; oats
were \ cent lower to 1\ cents higher with July at $1.73 a bushel;
soybeans were unchanged to 12 cents higher with July at $7.80 a
bushel.
