<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2207EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Eastern-Cutbacks     05-20 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Cutbacks,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilots Say Eastern to Cut Back Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financially strapped Eastern Airlines will cut back
its operations by nearly 20 percent starting this summer, its
pilots union says.
   The Air Line Pilots Association said Eastern officials told
union representatives of the plans at an April 29 meeting during
discussion of pilots' scheduling, The Miami Herald reported in
Friday's editions.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said the 20 percent ``is a
speculative figure.''
   ``That's from ALPA,'' she said. ``We haven't determined or
finalized our flying plans beyond July.''
   But Eastern, a subsidiary of giant Texas Air Corp., said in its
most recent quarterly report to the Securities and Exchange
Commission that more cutbacks and losses are imminent.
   ``In anticipation of continuing losses, Eastern is considering
and anticipating a further downsizing of the operations,'' said the
report made public this week.
   Eastern sustained a net loss of $30.9 million in the first
quarter.
   The union representing some 3,500 Eastern pilots said they were
told by Eastern that the planned flight reductions stem from a
worsening pilot shortage, a huge backlog of pilot vacations
postponed by the company to keep planes flying and a ``training
logjam'' on A300 and Boeing 757 jetliners.
   According to union calculations, Eastern would operate 56,812
block hours this September, down sharply from 78,236 this month. A
block hour measures how long it takes a plane to taxi and fly from
one airport to another. Flight levels have not been that low since
1968, the pilots said.
   ALPA said, though, there was no indication that Eastern would
lay off more workers to adjust for the cutbacks.
   The union also said Eastern estimates it has lost 1,037 pilots
since July 1986. A total of 392 will have been hired, for a net
reduction of 645. Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said the carrier
has enough pilots to meet its planned schedules.
   Employment at Eastern has been slashed from 40,000 to around
32,000 workers since Eastern's 1986 takeover by Texas Air.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
