<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MurrayOhio     05-20 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murray Ohio,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge To Rule Monday on Murray Ohio Hostile Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET HABERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge said Friday that he
would rule after the financial markets close Monday on Murray Ohio
Manufacturing Co.'s attempt to block a $182 million hostile
takeover by AB Electrolux of Sweden.
   U.S. District Judge Thomas A. Wiseman said he would review the
case over the weekend before ruling on Murray Ohio's request for a
preliminary injunction against the Swedish appliance manufacturer.
   Murray Ohio produces lawn mowers and bicycles.
   A five-day hearing had focused on the New York law firm Sullivan
& Cromwell, which represented AB Electrolux in its $48-a-share
offer made May 6. But the firm also offered advice in 1987 to
Murray Ohio on strategy for fighting takeovers, testimony showed.
   In closing arguments, Murray Ohio attorney Robert J. Walker
contended that the huge Electrolux benefited from inside
information provided by Sullivan & Cromwell.
   Walker said the law firm was privy to sensitive information
about Murray Ohio, including financial projections and takeover
tactics.
   He said Neil Anderson, a Sullivan & Cromwell partner advising AB
Electrolux on the takeover, knew that his firm had confidential
information about Murray Ohio in its files,
   Anderson then told Daniel R. Elliott, an AB Electrolux vice
president, of the existence of the information and then advised the
Swedish company on what price to offer for Murray Ohio's shares,
Walker said.
   ``He (Elliott) was being told how to bet by one who knew,'' he
said.
   But AB Electrolux attorney William G. McGuinness said his
clients were ``innocent bystanders.''
   He said that no witness, including those from Murray Ohio,
testified about any specific insider information being given to AB
Electrolux.
   In addition, he said thousands of pages of files produced for
the hearing offered no evidence that Electrolux ever used
confidential information to analyze Murray Ohio for the takeover.
   The analysis was based on public sources, he said.
   ``If Electrolux had any inside information ... you would think
some of it would be documented somewhere,'' he said.
</TEXT>
