<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PentagonContracts     05-20 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pentagon Contracts,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contracts Awarded For Developing New High-Speed Computer Chip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon selected four contractor teams
Friday to develop a new type of high-speed, gallium arsenide
computer chip.
   The three-year contracts, ranging in value from $49 million to
about $69 million, call for each team to design, fabricate, package
and test the same type of computer chip. Each team, however, is
pursuing development of the chip with an eye toward its use in
different weapons or communications systems, the Pentagon said.
   The chips ``are expected to be of great value for radar,
electronic warfare, communications and smart munitions systems,''
the Pentagon said.
   It said the four contracts were awarded by the Defense Advanced
Research Projects Agency, or DARPA, under a program known as MIMIC
_ Microwave-Millimeter-Wave Monolithic Integrated Circuits.
   The four contractor teams are led by the Martin-Marietta Corp.
and ITT Corp.; TRW Inc.; Raytheon Co. and Texas Instruments Inc.,
and Hughes Aircraft Co. and General Electric Co.
   The Martin-Marietta-ITT team includes four other partners and
received a contract totaling $49.3 million. The TRW team includes
three other partners and received a contract worth $57.5 million.
The Raytheon-Texas Instruments team includes eight other partners
and received a contract totaling $68.6 million. And the Hughes-GE
team includes seven other partners and received a contract worth
$50 million.
</TEXT>
