<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet     05-20 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street,0583</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks crawled to a mixed finish Friday in the
lightest trading of the year, capping a loss-riddled week in which
investor apathy and concern over higher interest rates dominated
the market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks spent part of the
day barely ahead but weakened by late afternoon and finished with a
6.13 point loss to 1,952.59, bringing its decline for the week to
37.95. Broader market indices were mixed.
   New York Stock Exchange volume totaled 120.6 million shares vs.
165.16 million the previous session. It was the most lethargic pace
since a 111.58 million-share day Dec. 29. Without the inflating
influence of dividend-capture trading in selected stocks, the
volume would have been substantially lighter.
   ``It's just a continuation of complete lack of interest by the
public,'' said John Muldowney, head of equity trading at the
Richmond, Va. investment firm of Scott & Stringfellow Inc.
   The government reported that consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in
April. Although that level was widely anticipated by economists and
traders, it substantiated some anxiety about inflation that haunted
the market all week.
   This concern pushed yields on the key 30-year Treasury bond to
the 9.34 percent Friday, the highest of the year, making bonds an
increasingly attractive and less risky alternative to stocks.
   ``The market has said something loud and clear: I'm going to
attach myself to the tail of the bond market,'' said Stephen
Shobin, a vice president and market analyst for Merrill Lynch & Co.
in New York.
   Nevertheless, Shobin said he saw the potential for a stock
rally, arguing that fears over inflation are highly exaggerated and
that any further substantial rise in interest rates is unlikely.
   ``I think the market has very little vulnerability here,''
Shobin said. ``The level of fear is very high right now, but fear
is very fashionable. The market rarely rewards what the Street
considers fashionable.''
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 3-to-2 in
nationwide trading of NYSE-listed stocks, with 841 issues up, 605
down and 514 unchanged.
   Among the most prominent Big Board issues, Texaco fell 1~ to 45|
on reports that the company was considering a restructuring plan
that would reduce the 14.8 percent stake of its largest
shareholder, takeover strategist Carl Icahn.
   Other notable blue chips included Boeing, up 1{ to 50{; DuPont,
down } to 80{; IBM, down 1 to 109{; Merck, down 1] to 149; and
Union Carbide, up { to 18|.
   Interest-sensitive stocks such as banks and utilities were
widely higher, suggesting that concern over higher interest rates
may be peaking. Chemical Bank rose } to 26|, American Express rose
[ to 23}, Manufacturers Hanover rose ] to 26], AT&T rose [ to 26}
and US West rose { to 52.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 142.40 million shares.
   The Wilshire Associates 5,000 Equity Index, the market value of
5,000 NYSE, American and OTC issues, rose by $3.622 billion.
   The NYSE index rose 0.29 to 143.30.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials rose 0.45 to 293.42,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index also rose 0.45 to 253.02.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 0.05
to 291.84. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 366.03, down 0.22.
</TEXT>
