<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MediaGeneral 2ndLd-Writethru   05-20 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Media General, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugarman Proposes Splitting Media General</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: grafs 10-15 new to UPDATE with Media General comment on vote
and edit, picks up 16th graf pvs: Sugarman criticized ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Burt Sugarman, apparently conceding
that his $1.8 billion bid for Media General Inc. has stalled, on
Friday suggested splitting the communications firm into two or more
parts.
   Speaking at the company's annual shareholders meeting, Sugarman
also played down the bitter proxy fight he has waged with Media
General Chairman D. Tennant Bryan over the election of directors to
the company's board.
   ``The questions that I have are not based on personalities,''
Sugarman said. ``It's time to get down to business ... Let's meet
together. Let's talk together.''
   Bryan, whose family owns 71 percent of Media General's powerful
Class B shares, presided at the meeting but did not respond to
Sugarman's offer to negotiate. Bryan has said the family's stake in
the company is not for sale.
   Sugarman, who controls about 10 percent of the company's Class A
shares, initially offered $61.50 a share, but later boosted his bid
to $70 a share.
   Subsequently, he and two allies have challenged three directors
seeking re-election to Media General's nine-member board.
   Sugarman told the stockholders that his slate would be fair to
the Bryans and would seek to split the company's assets in a way
that preserved the family's publishing concerns. ``My interest is
not in taking the newspapers away'' from the Bryans, he said.
   In addition to the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News
Leader, the Tampa Tribune and other daily and weekly newspapers,
Media General owns several television stations and cable television
operations.
   Bryan, meanwhile, received a lengthy ovation from the crowd of
about 400 shareholders when he read his own name for re-election to
the board.
   Because of delays in counting proxy votes, the tally on the
election of directors will not be released until May 27. But Media
General President and Chief Executive Officer James R. Evans, said
``based on the proxies that we have received, we believe the
incumbent ... directors have defeated Sugarman and his dissident
slate.''
   Sugarman, however, said after the two-hour meeting that he
believed the vote was nearly even. ``I think you'll find I was not
the only shareholder who voted for our slate,'' he said.
   But several shareholders said Sugarman's proposal to split the
company indicated some doubt about his chances.
   Still, Sugarman said his $70-per-share bid still stands.
   Media General closed Thursday at $42.62{ a share. ``Look at the
disparity in those numbers,'' he said.
   The stock dropped $1.12{ a share Friday to close at $41.37{ on
the American Stock Exchange.
   Sugarman criticized the two-tier stock arrangement and said he
was seeking congressional action to eliminate such structures. Last
month a federal district court in Richmond rejected Sugarman's
challenge to the system.
   Like several media companies including the New York Times Co.
and the Washington Post Co., Media General has two classes of stock
to keep control of the company in the hands of a few. While there
are fewer Class B shares outstanding, those shares are more
powerful than the Class A shares.
   Under Media General's arrangement, the Bryan family controls the
election of a majority of the board through its Class-B shares.
   Sugarman is chairman of the California-based Barris Industries,
which produces ``The Dating Game'' and other popular television
game shows and the South Carolina-based Giant Group Ltd., a cement
company.
</TEXT>
