<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-20 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Platinum Surges As Inflation Signals Strengthen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Platinum futures prices jumped more than $11 a troy ounce
Friday, leading other precious metals higher as key indicators
reinforced ideas that inflation is worsening, analysts said.
   On other markets, most livestock and meat futures gained; the
pork markets received some startling news about supplies; grains
and soybeans advanced; energy futures were mixed; and stock index
futures retreated.
   A combination of inflationary signals and indications of
economic growth have made platinum the leader of the
precious-metals complex because platinum is used as both an
industrial metal and a hedge against inflation, analysts said.
   Friday's government report showing a 0.4 percent increase in
consumer prices in April supported the metals rally on Friday. But
the real boost came late in the day when a sudden surge in soybean
and grain futures prices propelled the Commodity Research Bureau's
price index of 21 commodities up sharply.
   With Friday's 1.31-point gain, the CRB index for May delivery
ended the week at 246.11, up 6.81 points from the previous Friday's
close on the New York Futures Exchange.
   ``That's really a fantastic move,'' said Craig Sloane, metals
analyst for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York. ``All
these things _ commodity prices, strength of the economy _ they're
all feeding into why the metals are beginning to move.''
   Platinum settled $11.10 to $11.20 higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, with the contract for delivery in July at
$568.60 a troy ounce.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold was 50 cents to 70
cents higher with June at $458.70 a troy ounce; silver was 7.5
cents to 7.9 cents higher with May at $6.69 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures finished mostly higher in light,
pre-weekend trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. But a
government cold-storage report released after the close prompted
predictions that pork futures would open lower on Monday.
   The Agriculture Department said the number of hams in cold
storage nearly doubled during April to 51.6 million pounds. That
compares with 24 million pounds on April 1 and 11.3 million pounds
on May 1, 1987.
   The USDA said the total amount of pork in cold storage was up 82
percent from last year, including 102.5 million pounds of frozen
pork bellies, the third-largest May 1 total ever, said Chuck
Levitt, an analysts in Chicago with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The large stocks of frozen pork won't have an immediate impact
on futures prices but will begin exerting heavy price pressure in
July, when demand for pork products typically outstrips the supply
of fresh meat, Levitt said.
   Live cattle settled .40 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June
at 73.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .25 cent
higher with May at 80.90 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to
.35 cent higher with June at 53.87 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .75 cent lower to .37 cent higher with May at 53.25
cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures closed higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade with soybeans up sharply on fears of continued dry weather.
   Weekend weather forecasts were mixed, but even the most
optimistic outlooks called for scattered showers to bring only
slight moisture to parts of the Corn Belt, analysts said.
   With soybean stockpiles declining, a poor crop this year could
lead to tight supplies next year.
   The National Weather Service, in a six-to-10 day outlook issued
after the close, predicted warm temperatures and normal rainfall
for most of the Midwest during the latter half of next week and the
Memorial Day weekend.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 5\ cents higher with July at $3.46{ a
bushel; corn was unchanged to 3} cents higher with July at $2.21\ a
bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{ cents higher with July at $1.73} a
bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 11} cents higher with July at
$7.78} a bushel.
   Energy futures finished mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange as the contract for June delivery of crude oil expired at
$17.17 a barrel.
   West Texas Intermediate crude settled unchanged to 8 cents
higher with July at $17.70 a barrel; heating oil was .06 cent lower
to .11 cent higher with June at 47.71 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .12 cent lower to .10 cent higher with June at 52.36
cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange. The contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poor's
500 index settled .20 point lower at 252.70.
</TEXT>
