<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 0628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PSNHBankruptcy     05-20 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Grants Limited Extension in Bankruptcy Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge on Thursday
granted Public Service Company of New Hampshire at least four extra
months to come up with a reorganization plan, and may grant another
two months after that.
   After a seven-hour hearing, Judge James Yacos said he doubted he
would grant the utility the eight months it had requested.
   But he said the utility was entitled at least to a four-month
extension because ``the first 120 days have been used for
organization in a rather unique case.
   ``Realistically, (Public Service) is only now in a position they
would be in the first few weeks of a normal case,'' Yacos said.
   Federal bankruptcy law gives a debtor the exclusive right to
propose a reorganization plan for 120 days after it files for
protection from creditors. The exclusivity period for Public
Service _ the state's largest electric utility and main owner of
the stalled Seabrook nuclear power plant _ ends May 27.
   It had asked for an eight-month extension, citing the complexity
and uniqueness of the case.
   Yacos said he would consider lengthening the extension later if
he was assured that parties involved in the reorganization had
adequate access to information needed to develop and negotiate a
plan.
   Yacos said he either would grant a four-month extension with a
hearing in September to consider more time, or would grant a
six-month extension with a hearing in September to be certain that
necessary information is being made available to all involved.
   Several lawyers representing other parties to the bankruptcy had
proposed shorter extension periods.
   But Yacos said he was not convinced that it yet was appropriate
to open up the reorganization process to other proposals, although
he noted that ``one way to make things move is to make them
concrete, put them on the table.''
   Public Service sought bankruptcy protection because of financial
problems stemming from its 36 percent share of the $5.4 billion
Seabrook plant. It blames its woes largely on political opposition
to Seabrook and a state law barring the company from charging
customers for the plant until it operates commercially, which had
forced the company to borrow heavily.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
