<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AMAX-Stock     05-20 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AMAX-Stock,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMAX Repurchases 15.2 Million Shares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AMAX Inc. said Friday it has repurchased
15.2 million shares from Chevron Corp. for $23 each, or about $350
million.
   A statement from the companies said Chevron has a one-time
option to request additional payment for the shares over the next
two years if AMAX stock rises above $23 a share, with a ceiling of
$28 a share.
   Chevron, which acquired its interest in AMAX in 1975, was the
largest shareholder in the metals, oil and gas company.
   Analysts said the move highlights Chevron's interest in focusing
on its basic oil businesses.
   Jordan Estra, vice president of S.G. Warbug & Co. in New York,
said, ``What it really means is Chevron is focusing its effort back
to its basic businesses and its interest in diversification is
diminished.''
   Alan Born, president and chief executive officer of AMAX, said
the company will have to borrow to finance the repurchase, but he
expected the funds to be repaid from the current year's cash flow.
   ``AMAX has completed a number of major steps to improve its
profitability and potential and is experiencing significant
improvement in its operating results,'' Born said. ``This share
purchase will not dilute the earnings of AMAX's remaining
shareholders.
   ``We are currently expecting AMAX's net income in 1988 to be in
the order of $4 per share and with this purchase of shares, those
expected earnings should increase to about $4.25 per share,'' he
said.
   The repurchase represents Chevron's total holdings in AMAX.
   Although corporate headquarters for AMAX are in New York, the
company's headquarters for its metals businesses are in Greenwich.
Chevron is headquartered in San Francisco.
</TEXT>
