<1ST_LINE>r f AM-RubberStrike     05-20 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rubber Strike,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Union Locals Ok Goodyear Settlement; Firestone Strike
Continues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at four Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co.
plants approved a contract settlement, among them a key
2,500-member local union in Tennessee that had rejected an earlier
contract proposal, a union spokesman said Friday.
   Voting by six union locals is scheduled through Monday on the
tentative settlement reached by Goodyear and the United Rubber
Workers union shortly before a noon strike deadline last Tuesday.
   The URW represents 15,000 workers at 11 of Goodyear's 42 U.S.
plants.
   Meanwhile, a walkout by 4,700 Firestone Inc. union workers in
six states continued for a sixth day Friday. URW spokesman Curt
Brown said the union's president, Milan Stone, has asked
negotiators to return to the bargaining table in Akron on Saturday.
The talks will be the first in a week.
   Firestone spokesman Mike Connor confirmed that talks would
resume.
   URW workers in Union City, Tenn.; Marysville, Ohio; and Topeka,
Kan., voted in favor of the proposed Goodyear contract on Thursday
and workers in Sun Prairie, Wis., approved it Friday, Brown said.
   Workers in Madisonville, Ky., rejected the offer Thursday with
54 percent voting against the proposal, he said. Brown did not
release vote totals.
   The approval by the Union City local could be a key to its
ratification nationwide because of its size. Under URW bylaws,
ratification must be made by a majority of the locals representing
a majority of the membership.
   Firestone workers went on strike Sunday after union negotiators
rejected Firestone's offer, saying it didn't match the first
agreement with Goodyear, which was intended to served as a pattern
for Firestone.
   Firestone officials contended their latest offer was equal to
the Goodyear pattern. The Akron-based URW represents Firestone
workers in Noblesville, Ind.; Des Moines, Iowa; Decatur, Ill.;
Russellville, Akr.; Oklahoma City and Akron.
   Goodyear and the union reached its first tentative settlement on
April 21, but it was rejected a week later.
</TEXT>
