<FILEID>AP-NR-05-20-88 1926EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LuckyStores     05-20 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lucky Stores,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lucky, American Stores Agree to Merge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucky Stores Inc. has agreed to be acquired
by American Stores Co. for $2.5 billion in cash in a deal that
would create one of the nation's biggest supermarket concerns, both
companies announced Friday.
   At the same time, Lucky said its board terminated an April 28
agreement to merge with the New York investment firm Gibbons, Green
van Amerongen Ltd. for $2.35 billion in cash and stock.
   The three principals said they agreed to dismiss all pending
litigation involving the four-month takeover battle. Lucky said it
would pay Gibbons, Green a $20 million fee plus expenses for
breaking the pact.
   In composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Lucky
closed unchanged at $64.37{ Friday while American Stores fell $1 to
$53.25.
   The offer from Salt Lake City-based American Stores is subject
to certain conditions, including the tender of at least a majority
of Lucky's 38.6 million outstanding shares. American Stores said it
has received written commitments from commercial banks for all
financing required.
   The American Stores offer expires at midnight EDT June 1.
   ``We are extremely pleased that an agreement has been reached,''
said American Stores Chairman L.S. Skaggs. ``American Stores has
always considered Lucky to be the leading supermarket chain in
California and is enthusiastic about the combination of our Alpha
Beta (grocery store) operations with those of Lucky.''
   Under the agreement, any Lucky shares not purchased by American
Stores in the tender offer will be converted into the right to
receive $65 in cash in a merger between Lucky and a subsidiary of
American.
   On Tuesday, American Stores had raised its bid for Lucky to $65
a share, following the earlier Gibbons, Green offer of a leveraged
buyout that would pay $61 a share in cash for about 92 percent of
Lucky's outstanding shares. Gibbons, Green would also have issued
preferred shares valued at $7 a share for the remaining shares.
   American Stores' second bid followed the disclosure of
confidential information by Lucky to American, under the
stipulation that American would either sweeten its offer or end its
hostile bid.
   American Stores initiated the bidding with a $45-a-share offer
that Lucky rejected in March. Lucky also turned down an American
Stores' proposal to increase the bid to $50 a share in a negotiated
acquisition. The company stated at the time that it considered both
offers inadequate.
   In 1986, Lucky underwent a series of restructuring moves
designed to thwart a takeover bid by New York investor Asher
Edelman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
